{"title_page": "Timothy Bell, Baron Bell", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Timothy Bell|the NASCAR driver|T. J. Bell}}\n{{redirect|Tim Bell|the New Zealand computer scientist|Tim Bell (computer scientist)}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix   = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name               = The Lord Bell\n| honorific_suffix   = \n| image              = Lord Bell  2008.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Bell in 2008\n|office6          = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br/>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start6       = 31 July 1998\n|term_end6         =25 August 2019 <br/>[[Life peer|Life Peerage]]\n| birth_name         = Timothy John Leigh Bell\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1941|10|18|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Southgate, London]], England\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2019|08|25|1941|10|18|df=y}}\n| death_place        = London, England\n| known_for          = Campaign work for [[Margaret Thatcher]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Field|first=Michele|title=Tim Bell Love Newspapers, Gorillas and Maggie T|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=kswzAAAAIBAJ&sjid=U5UDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2059,4927186&dq=tim-bell&hl=en|newspaper=The Age|date=24 January 1986}}</ref>\n| occupation         = Advertising and public relations executive\n| party              = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n}}\n\n'''Timothy John Leigh Bell, Baron Bell''' (18 October 1941 \u2013 25 August 2019), was a British advertising and [[public relations]] [[Executive (management)|executive]], best known for his advisory role in [[Margaret Thatcher]]'s three successful general [[election campaign]]s and his co-founding and 30 years of heading [[Bell Pottinger]].\n\n==Early life and career==\nBell was born in Southgate, North London on 18 October 1941, to [[Belfast]]-born Arthur Leigh Bell, a [[Crosse & Blackwell]] sales representative, and Greta Mary Finlay, an Australian. His father left the family when his son was four, moving to [[South Africa]] and becoming a radio broadcaster known as \"Uncle Paddy.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/lord-bell-obituary-hf007pmww|title=Lord Bell obituary|date=26 August 2019|via=www.thetimes.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2019/aug/26/lord-bell-obituary|title=Lord Bell obituary|first=Stephen|last=Bates|date=26 August 2019|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Timothy John Leigh Bell, Baron Bell|url=http://thepeerage.com/p13721.htm#i137206 |publisher=Lundy Consulting Ltd |work=The Peerage |accessdate=7 December 2011 |date=10 May 2006 }}</ref> \nIn 1952 his mother remarried Peter Pettit, the solicitor who had handled her divorce.<ref name=TelegraphObit>''The Telegraph'' UK obit 28 Aug 2019</ref> Bell was educated at Osidge Primary School and [[Queen Elizabeth's Grammar School for Boys|Queen Elizabeth's Grammar School, Barnet]], and joined [[Associated British Corporation|ABC Television]] at 18 as a post boy.<ref name=\"telegraph1\">[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/mediatechnologyandtelecoms/7601491/Tim-Bell-Theres-never-been-so-much-tension-between-business-and-politicians.html \"Tim Bell: 'There's never been so much tension between business and politicians'\"], telegraph.co.uk, 17 April 2010</ref> He worked in various advertising/PR firms in the late 60s including the London agency Colman Prentice & Varley and later Geers Gross, before helping to found and becoming [[managing director]] of [[Saatchi and Saatchi]] in 1970, later serving as chairman and managing director of Saatchi and Saatchi Compton from 1975.\n\nOn 19 November 1977 Bell was fined \u00a350 for indecency. He had exposed himself while [[masturbation|masturbating]] at his Hampstead bathroom window on 21 October in full view of female passers-by.<ref>Mark Hollingsworth ''The Ultimate spin doctor: the life and fast times of Tim Bell'', London: Hodder & Stoughton, 1997, p.45</ref><ref>Brian Basham [http://www.marketingweek.co.uk/thatcher-exposed-in-tim-bell-revelations/2033946.article \"Thatcher exposed in Tim Bell revelations\"], ''Marketing Week'', 14 March 1997</ref> \n\nHe left the Saatchis to join [[Frank Lowe (advertiser)|Frank Lowe]] and Geoff Howard-Spink in 1985 to have his name on the door at Lowe Howard-Spink and Bell where he served as deputy chairman. Later, in 1989 he bought out the PR division which became his own agency, Lowe Bell Communications,<ref name=\"telegraph1\"/> and he became chairman of [[Chime Communications plc|Chime Communications]] in 1994 (which included the [[Bell Pottinger]] group).\n\n==Thatcher years==\nBell was instrumental in the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] general election campaign victories of [[Margaret Thatcher]] and was seen as Thatcher's \"favourite spin-doctor and confidante.\"<ref name=\"vecono\" >{{cite news|author=|title=A famous London PR firm suffers a PR disaster|url=https://www.economist.com/news/britain/21728677-bell-pottinger-which-managed-some-controversial-reputations-receives-blow-its-own-brand|work=[[The Economist]]|date=7 September 2017}}</ref>  For her first [[1979 United Kingdom general election|1979 victory]], he developed the strategy for the '[[Labour Isn't Working]]' campaign, created by Saatchi creative director [[Jeremy Sinclair]]<ref name=\"telegraph1\"/> and Bell advised the future Prime Minister on interview techniques, clothing, and even hairstyle choices. He also courted newspaper editors and worked on devastating attacks on the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]].\n\nIn 1984 Bell was seconded to the [[National Coal Board]] to advise on media strategy at the start of the [[UK miners' strike (1984\u20131985)|miners' strike]]. He worked on [[media relations]] and helped set the terms of the negotiations and course of government policy.\n\nBell was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in 1991<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=52543 |date=28 May 1991 |page=8208}}</ref> after nomination by Margaret Thatcher, and created a [[Life Peer]] after nomination as a Conservative [[working peer]] as '''Baron Bell''' ''of [[Belgravia]] in the [[City of Westminster]]'' on 31 July 1998.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=55216 |date=5 August 1998 |page=8519}}</ref> He was often later seen on panels and current affairs programmes discussing the issues of the day, and was chairman of the Conservative Party's ''Keep the \u00a3 Campaign''. He also served on various arts and public administration bodies. On 8 April 2013 it was Bell who officially announced the [[Death and funeral of Margaret Thatcher|news of Lady Thatcher's death]].\n\n==International work==\nBell advised [[Hern\u00e1n B\u00fcchi]], a former minister of the [[Military dictatorship of Chile (1973\u201390)|Pinochet dictatorship]], in the [[1989 Chilean general election|presidential election of 1989]].<ref>Andy Beckett, ''Pinochet in Piccadilly. Britain and Chile's Hidden History'' (Faber and Faber, 2002), p. 217.</ref> B\u00fcchi eventually lost by a large margin to [[Patricio Aylwin]].<ref name=AngellPollack1990>{{cite journal |last=Angell |first=Alan |last2=Pollack |first2=Benny |date=1990 |title=The Chilean Elections of 1989 |journal=[[Bulletin of Latin American Research]] |publisher=Society for Latin American Studies |volume=9 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201323 |doi= }}</ref>\n\nLord Bell, a friend of Russian tycoon [[Boris Berezovsky (businessman)|Boris Berezovsky]], handled the media attention behind poisoned Russian ex-spy [[Alexander Litvinenko]], who died in hospital 23 November 2006. The Bell Pottinger Communications agency distributed a photograph showing a hairless Litvinenko in his hospital bed. The PR Agency also offered advice to relatives of Litvinenko and his spokesman [[Alexander Goldfarb (microbiologist)|Alex Goldfarb]].<ref>{{cite web\n  | title = Berezovsky link draws Lord Bell into action\n  |work=Financial Times\n  | date = 24 November 2006\n  | url = http://www.ft.com/cms/s/a8cc1da4-7bf7-11db-b1c6-0000779e2340.html\n  | accessdate = 27 November 2006}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2006, Lord Bell successfully lobbied on behalf of the [[Saudi government]] to discontinue the [[Serious Fraud Office (UK)|Serious Fraud Office]] investigation into alleged bribes in the [[Al Yamamah#Investigation discontinued|Al Yamamah]] arms deal.<ref name=\"guardianbrutal\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/armstrade/story/0,,1973421,00.html| title=Brutal politics lesson for corruption investigators|author=David Leigh|author2=Rob Evans |date=16 December 2006|work=The Guardian |location=UK|accessdate=16 December 2006}}</ref>\n\nLord Bell also performed public relations work for the authoritarian government of [[Belarus]],<ref>[http://www.economist.com/agenda/displaystory.cfm?story_id=12342630&fsrc=rss \"No breakthrough in Belarus\"], ''The Economist'', 2 October 2008</ref> and for the [[Pinochet]] Foundation (Fundaci\u00f3n Pinochet). In addition, he worked as an advisor to former Malaysian Prime Minister [[Mahathir Mohamad]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Moseley |first=Ray |date=18 February 1994 |title=Malaysia Dam Linked To Arms Deal With Britain |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1994-02-18/news/9402180371_1_british-airways-british-aid-malaysian-prime-minister-mahathir |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |location=Chicago |accessdate=26 December 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn late 2011, Bell's lobbying interests were investigated by the [[Bureau of Investigative Journalism]] for ''[[The Independent]]'' newspaper which reported claims that the company attempts to interfere with Google results to \"drown\" out coverage of human rights abuses, that his employees had altered [[English Wikipedia]] entries to create a better impression of clients and had easy access (via former Conservative MP [[Tim Collins (politician)|Tim Collins]]) to the Cameron government and others overseas.<ref name=\"NewmanWright\">Melanie Newman and Oliver Wright  [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/caught-on-camera-top-lobbyists-boasting-how-they-influence-the-pm-6272760.html \"Caught on camera: top lobbyists boasting how they influence the PM\"], ''The Independent'', 6 December 2011</ref> Bell Pottinger, via a sting operation, were found to be willing to work for the authoritarian regime in Uzbekistan.<ref name=\"NewmanWright\"/> Bell launched an internal inquiry, but believed he had been singled out for his connection with Mrs Thatcher.<ref name=EveSta>Stephen Robinson [https://web.archive.org/web/20111208213424/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/lifestyle/article-24019238-of-course-i-regret-it-i-need-it-like-a-hole-in-the-head-all-this-st.do \"'Of course I regret it, I need it like a hole in the head, all this s**t'\"], ''Evening Standard'' (London), 8 December 2011. Retrieved 27 February 2013.</ref>\n\nChime disposed of Bell Pottinger in June 2012 (while retaining a 25% stake in the business), when Bell also resigned as a director of Chime.<ref name=ChimeCoD>{{cite web|title=Completion of Disposal|url=http://www.chime.plc.uk/announcements/chime-final-of-mbo-new-director-of-board|work=Market Announcements, Monday 02 July 2012|publisher=Chime plc|accessdate=20 August 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130114050941/http://www.chime.plc.uk/announcements/chime-final-of-mbo-new-director-of-board|archivedate=14 January 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Bell Pottinger exit under cloud of PR malpractice==\n[[Bell Pottinger#.27White Monopoly Capital.27|Bell Pottinger]] announced Lord Bell's departure as chairman to set up an advisory firm, Sans Fronti\u00e8res Associates, in August 2016. He retained a 7% stake in Bell Pottinger.<ref name=\"Mance-25Aug2016\">{{cite news|last1=Mance|first1=Henry|title=Lord Bell quits as Bell Pottinger chairman|url=https://www.ft.com/content/10114318-6adb-11e6-ae5b-a7cc5dd5a28c?mhq5j=e3|accessdate=29 June 2017|work=Financial Times|date=25 August 2016}}</ref> Tony Walford, partner at Green Square stated, \"Perhaps not coincidentally, Sans Fronti\u00e8res was the original name of the public relations firm he set up before it was renamed Bell Pottinger; it was also the name of the unit that handled the firm's controversial lobbying and consultancy work for the governments of countries such as Belarus and Sri Lanka.\"<ref name=\"TD-2Sep2016\">{{cite news|last1=Walford|first1=Tony|title=Why maverick PR man Lord Bell may enjoy being his own man again|url=http://www.thedrum.com/opinion/2016/09/02/sans-fronti-res-why-maverick-pr-man-lord-bell-may-enjoy-being-his-own-man-again|accessdate=5 September 2017|work=The Drum|date=2 September 2016}}</ref>\nA \"leading PR figure\" told ''[[The Times]]'' that his resignation from his own agency didn't come as a surprise, saying: \"Ultimately, he did not fit with the kind of corporate image Bell Pottinger wanted to project\", in the end.<ref name=\"TD-26Aug2016\">{{cite news|last1=Stuart|first1=Rebecca|title=Lord Bell departs from Bell Pottinger to open new PR firm Sans Fronti\u00e8res|url=http://www.thedrum.com/news/2016/08/26/lord-bell-departs-bell-pottinger-open-new-pr-firm-sans-fronti-res|accessdate=5 September 2017|work=The Drum|date=26 August 2016}}</ref> \nWalford explains that, \"there is big money to be made from representing governments and other entities, no matter how reviled they are. The problem is, this kind of activity sits increasingly uneasily with corporates keen on projecting a responsible image.\"<ref name=\"TD-2Sep2016\"/>\n\nIn January 2017 the ''[[Huffington Post]]'' reported that [[Johann Rupert]], CEO of [[Remgro]] and [[Richemont]], ended an 18 year old contract with Bell Pottinger due to their 'concerted effort on social and other media to discredit him'. Rupert had spoken out against [[state capture]] and called on President [[Jacob Zuma]] to resign \"for the sake of our children\". As the [[State capture#South Africa|Guptas]] back [[Jacob Zuma#Gupta family relationship|Zuma]], Rupert asserted that Bell Pottinger painted him as the embodiment of [[Bell Pottinger#.27White Monopoly Capital.27|white monopoly capital]] and as the counterweight to the Guptas and state capture, an example of how state capture allegedly worked under apartheid.<ref name=\"HP 25 January 2017\">{{cite news |last= du Toit |first= Pieter | authorlink= |title= How Rupert Was Warned About Bell Pottinger: 'They're Behind It.' |url= http://www.huffingtonpost.co.za/2017/01/25/how-rupert-was-warned-about-bell-pottinger-theyre-behind-it_a_21662494/| date= 25 January 2017|work= [[Huffington Post]] |location=London| accessdate= 5 September 2017 }}</ref>\n\nEleven months after leaving Bell Pottinger and six days after the [[Public Relations and Communications Association]] (PRCA) acknowledged receipt of the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance's]] complaint,<ref name=\"STSA-4Jul2017\">{{cite news|title=Bell Pottinger probed for stoking racial tension in SA|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2017-07-04-bell-pottinger-probed-for-stoking-racial-tension-in-sa/|accessdate=5 July 2017|work=Sunday Times (South Africa)|date=4 July 2017}}</ref> on 11 July 2017 Bell announces for the first recorded time to ''[[PRWeek]]'' that he had left Bell Pottinger after raising his concerns about its \"smelly\" relationship with the [[Gupta family]]'s Oakbay conglomerate in South Africa but that they had \"completely ignored me\"; Bell Pottinger denied his claims.<ref name=\"PRWeek 11 July 2017\">{{cite news |last= Burne James |first= Sam | authorlink= |title= 'I kept saying it was smelly': Lord Bell claims Bell Pottinger ignored his concerns over Gupta work |url= http://www.prweek.com/article/1439079/i-kept-saying-smelly-lord-bell-claims-bell-pottinger-ignored-concerns-gupta-work| date= 11 July 2017|work= [[PRWeek]] |location=London| accessdate= 4 September 2017 }}</ref>\n\nThe PRCA expelled Bell Pottinger for at least five years from September 2017 for inflaming racial tensions in [[South Africa]]. The PRCA found Bell Pottinger guilty of four breaches of its code of conduct and dispensed its toughest possible punishment. PRCA director-general, Francis Ingham told the [[Financial Times|FT]], \"This is the most blatant instance of unethical PR practice I\u2019ve ever seen. Bell Pottinger's work has set back South Africa by possibly 10 years.\"<ref name=\"FT 4 September 2017\">{{cite news |last= Bond |first= David | authorlink= |title= 'Bell Pottinger expelled by industry body for unethical practice |url= https://www.ft.com/content/66088476-9176-11e7-bdfa-eda243196c2c| date= 4 September 2017|work= [[Financial Times]] |location=London| accessdate= 4 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring a live ''[[Newsnight]]'' interview on 4 September 2017, Lord Bell mentioned that he was the most senior director at the several hour long initial meeting with the [[Gupta family|Guptas]]. Bell explained to [[Kirsty Wark]] that upon his return to London he told Bell Pottinger CEO [[James Henderson (businessman)|James Henderson]], \"it's a very interesting piece of business but we can't handle it because there's a conflict of interest\". [[Kirsty Wark|Wark]] then read Bell his own email, dated 26 January 2016, stating, \"The trip was a great success and we will put forward a deal whereby we will earn \u00a3100,000 per month plus costs and I will oversee this and make further reports.\" Wark asserted that the email was in \"direct conflict with what you just said\". Bell went on to deny this on the basis the email was sent before his return to London. Rather than oversee the deal, Bell claimed that upon his return \"I did absolutely nothing\", but Bell Pottinger \"submitted a [fee] proposal\". Bell went on to deny Wark's assertion that he is the senior figure working on the Gupta account, but rather he is a \"father figure of the meeting\". Wark asked that when Bell, as the founder of the company, stated that there was a conflict of interest, \"nobody listens? Really?\". Bell responded, \"Nobody listens to me. That's why I left the company\". Wark then produced a further Bell-authored email, dated 3 months later (April 2016), in which Bell offered further advice regarding the account. Bell retorted, \"You can attack me all you like but I had nothing to do with getting this account.\"<ref name=\"HP 4 September 2017\">{{cite news |last= Demianyk |first= Graeme | authorlink= |title= 'Lord Bell On BBC Newsnight: Bell Pottinger Co-Founder's Extraordinary Interview Amid Firm's South Africa Racism Row. His phone going off twice is just the tip of the iceberg. |url= http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/lord-bell-newsnight-bell-pottinger_uk_59adcd54e4b0354e440be8f1| date= 4 September 2017|work= [[Huffington Post]] |location=London| accessdate= 4 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nBell's Newsnight performance was pilloried by the UK press, with ''[[The Spectator]]'' labelling it, \"Lord Bell's Newsnight PR disaster\".<ref name=\"Spectator 5 September 2017\">{{cite news |last= Steerpike |first=  | authorlink= |title= 'Lord Bell's Newsnight PR disaster. |url= https://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:5z2gi9eE2V0J:https://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2017/09/lord-bells-newsnight-pr-disaster/+&cd=10&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=uk| date= 5 September 2017|work= [[The Spectator]] |location=London| accessdate= 5 September 2017}}</ref>\nThe ''[[Daily Express]]''{{'}}s take was, \"Lord Bell was left red-faced after his phone rang twice while he was live on air during a Newsnight interview.\".<ref name=\"The Express 5 September 2017\">{{cite news |last= Hunt |first= Darren | authorlink= |title=\"'Someone's popular!' Nail-biting moment Newsnight guest's phone interrupts tense interview.\" |url= http://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/850119/BBC-Newsnight-Bell-Pottinger-phone-stops-interview-interrupt-video-Lord-Bell | date= 5 September 2017|work= [[Daily Express]] |location=London| accessdate= 5 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nAn alternative view of what happened was published in The Drum on 5 September 2019. It stated Bell had a genuine desire to help the Indian-descended Guptas from being discriminated against in South Africa. However, Bell suffered a stroke in 2016 and was put on three months medical leave. CEO James Henderson used Bell's absence to ensure the account was run exclusively by his financial PR Team, under Victoria Geoghegan. Fake Twitter accounts were set up accusing white businessmen, such as Johann Rupert, of \"white monopoly capital\". When Bell returned from medical leave, he had a row with Henderson telling him he had to resign the account and when he refused, Bell resigned from the company. After the story broke in 2017, Johann Rupert claimed Bell was \"the only person to have acted with honour in the entire affair.\"<ref>https://www.thedrum.com/opinion/2019/09/05/with-the-passing-lord-bell-i-fear-we-will-not-see-his-again</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBell was married three times: first, in the 1960s, to Suzanne Cordran (marriage dissolved in 1985); in 1988 he married Virginia Hornbrook with whom he had a son and daughter (marriage dissolved in 2016); in 2017, he married Jacky Phillips.<ref name=TelegraphObit/>\n\nBell died from complications of vascular [[parkinsonism]] at his home in London on 25 August 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/obituaries/tim-bell-swaggering-pr-executive-and-spin-doctor-for-margaret-thatcher-dies-at-77/2019/08/26/1686949a-c80d-11e9-be05-f76ac4ec618c_story.html|title = Tim Bell, swaggering PR executive and spin doctor for Margaret Thatcher, dies at 77|date = 26 August 2019|accessdate = 26 August 2019|work = [[The Washington Post]]|last = Smith|first = Harrison}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://euobserver.com/24/26909 Lukashenko's PR man sheds light on EU campaign] EU Observer, 10 October 2008\n*[http://www.data.minsk.by/belarusnews/052008/244.html Can Lord Bell\u2019s PR skills combat the aroma of communism and cabbage?] Minsk.by, 28 May 2008\n*[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/how-to-sell-democracy-to-iraqis-bring-in-lord-bell-566189.html How to sell democracy to Iraqis: bring in Lord Bell] ''[[The Independent]]'', 13 March 2004\n*[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld199798/minutes/981014/ldminute.htm Announcement of his introduction at the House of Lords] House of Lords minutes of proceedings, 14 October 1998\n*[http://www.publicwhip.org.uk/mp.php?mpn=Lord_Bell&mpc=Lords&display=allvotes Parliamentary voting record for Lord Bell]\n*[http://www.charter97.org/en/news/2008/10/23/11396/ Belarusian have answered to Lord Bell]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bell, Timothy}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:Advertising people]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople awarded knighthoods]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in England]]\n[[Category:English businesspeople]]\n[[Category:English memoirists]]\n[[Category:English people of Australian descent]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:People educated at Queen Elizabeth's Grammar School for Boys]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Timothy Bell|the NASCAR driver|T. J. Bell}}\n{{redirect|Tim Bell|the New Zealand computer scientist|Tim Bell (computer scientist)}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix   = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name               = The Lord Bell\n| honorific_suffix   = \n| image              = Lord Bell  2008.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Bell in 2008\n|office6          = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br/>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start6       = 31 July 1998\n|term_end6         =25 August 2019 <br/>[[Life peer|Life Peerage]]\n| birth_name         = Timothy John Leigh Bell\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1941|10|18|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Southgate, London]], England\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2019|08|25|1941|10|18|df=y}}\n| death_place        = London, England\n| known_for          = Campaign work for [[Margaret Thatcher]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Field|first=Michele|title=Tim Bell Love Newspapers, Gorillas and Maggie T|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=kswzAAAAIBAJ&sjid=U5UDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2059,4927186&dq=tim-bell&hl=en|newspaper=The Age|date=24 January 1986}}</ref>\n| occupation         = Advertising and public relations executive\n| party              = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n}}\n\n'''Timothy John Leigh Bell, Baron Bell''' (18 October 1941 \u2013 25 August 2019), was a British advertising and [[public relations]] [[Executive (management)|executive]], best known for his advisory role in [[Margaret Thatcher]]'s three successful general [[election campaign]]s and his co-founding and 30 years of heading [[Bell Pottinger]].\n\n==Early life and career==\nBell was born in Southgate , North London on 18 October 1941, to [[Belfast]]-born Arthur Leigh Bell, a [[Crosse & Blackwell]] sales representative, and Greta Mary Finlay, an Australian. His father left the family when his son was four, moving to [[South Africa]] and becoming a radio broadcaster known as \"Uncle Paddy.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/lord-bell-obituary-hf007pmww|title=Lord Bell obituary|date=26 August 2019|via=www.thetimes.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2019/aug/26/lord-bell-obituary|title=Lord Bell obituary|first=Stephen|last=Bates|date=26 August 2019|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Timothy John Leigh Bell, Baron Bell|url=http://thepeerage.com/p13721.htm#i137206 |publisher=Lundy Consulting Ltd |work=The Peerage |accessdate=7 December 2011 |date=10 May 2006 }}</ref> \nIn 1952 his mother remarried Peter Pettit, the solicitor who had handled her divorce.<ref name=TelegraphObit>''The Telegraph'' UK obit 28 Aug 2019</ref> Bell was educated at Osidge Primary School and [[Queen Elizabeth's Grammar School for Boys|Queen Elizabeth's Grammar School, Barnet]], and joined [[Associated British Corporation|ABC Television]] at 18 as a post boy.<ref name=\"telegraph1\">[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/mediatechnologyandtelecoms/7601491/Tim-Bell-Theres-never-been-so-much-tension-between-business-and-politicians.html \"Tim Bell: 'There's never been so much tension between business and politicians'\"], telegraph.co.uk, 17 April 2010</ref> He worked in various advertising/PR firms in the late 60s including the London agency Colman Prentice & Varley and later Geers Gross, before helping to found and becoming [[managing director]] of [[Saatchi and Saatchi]] in 1970, later serving as chairman and managing director of Saatchi and Saatchi Compton from 1975.\n\nOn 19 November 1977 Bell was fined \u00a350 for indecency. He had exposed himself while [[masturbation|masturbating]] at his Hampstead bathroom window on 21 October in full view of female passers-by.<ref>Mark Hollingsworth ''The Ultimate spin doctor: the life and fast times of Tim Bell'', London: Hodder & Stoughton, 1997, p.45</ref><ref>Brian Basham [http://www.marketingweek.co.uk/thatcher-exposed-in-tim-bell-revelations/2033946.article \"Thatcher exposed in Tim Bell revelations\"], ''Marketing Week'', 14 March 1997</ref> \n\nHe left the Saatchis to join [[Frank Lowe (advertiser)|Frank Lowe]] and Geoff Howard-Spink in 1985 to have his name on the door at Lowe Howard-Spink and Bell where he served as deputy chairman. Later, in 1989 he bought out the PR division which became his own agency, Lowe Bell Communications,<ref name=\"telegraph1\"/> and he became chairman of [[Chime Communications plc|Chime Communications]] in 1994 (which included the [[Bell Pottinger]] group).\n\n==Thatcher years==\nBell was instrumental in the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] general election campaign victories of [[Margaret Thatcher]] and was seen as Thatcher's \"favourite spin-doctor and confidante.\"<ref name=\"vecono\" >{{cite news|author=|title=A famous London PR firm suffers a PR disaster|url=https://www.economist.com/news/britain/21728677-bell-pottinger-which-managed-some-controversial-reputations-receives-blow-its-own-brand|work=[[The Economist]]|date=7 September 2017}}</ref>  For her first [[1979 United Kingdom general election|1979 victory]], he developed the strategy for the '[[Labour Isn't Working]]' campaign, created by Saatchi creative director [[Jeremy Sinclair]]<ref name=\"telegraph1\"/> and Bell advised the future Prime Minister on interview techniques, clothing, and even hairstyle choices. He also courted newspaper editors and worked on devastating attacks on the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]].\n\nIn 1984 Bell was seconded to the [[National Coal Board]] to advise on media strategy at the start of the [[UK miners' strike (1984\u20131985)|miners' strike]]. He worked on [[media relations]] and helped set the terms of the negotiations and course of government policy.\n\nBell was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in 1991<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=52543 |date=28 May 1991 |page=8208}}</ref> after nomination by Margaret Thatcher, and created a [[Life Peer]] after nomination as a Conservative [[working peer]] as '''Baron Bell''' ''of [[Belgravia]] in the [[City of Westminster]]'' on 31 July 1998.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=55216 |date=5 August 1998 |page=8519}}</ref> He was often later seen on panels and current affairs programmes discussing the issues of the day, and was chairman of the Conservative Party's ''Keep the \u00a3 Campaign''. He also served on various arts and public administration bodies. On 8 April 2013 it was Bell who officially announced the [[Death and funeral of Margaret Thatcher|news of Lady Thatcher's death]].\n\n==International work==\nBell advised [[Hern\u00e1n B\u00fcchi]], a former minister of the [[Military dictatorship of Chile (1973\u201390)|Pinochet dictatorship]], in the [[1989 Chilean general election|presidential election of 1989]].<ref>Andy Beckett, ''Pinochet in Piccadilly. Britain and Chile's Hidden History'' (Faber and Faber, 2002), p. 217.</ref> B\u00fcchi eventually lost by a large margin to [[Patricio Aylwin]].<ref name=AngellPollack1990>{{cite journal |last=Angell |first=Alan |last2=Pollack |first2=Benny |date=1990 |title=The Chilean Elections of 1989 |journal=[[Bulletin of Latin American Research]] |publisher=Society for Latin American Studies |volume=9 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201323 |doi= }}</ref>\n\nLord Bell, a friend of Russian tycoon [[Boris Berezovsky (businessman)|Boris Berezovsky]], handled the media attention behind poisoned Russian ex-spy [[Alexander Litvinenko]], who died in hospital 23 November 2006. The Bell Pottinger Communications agency distributed a photograph showing a hairless Litvinenko in his hospital bed. The PR Agency also offered advice to relatives of Litvinenko and his spokesman [[Alexander Goldfarb (microbiologist)|Alex Goldfarb]].<ref>{{cite web\n  | title = Berezovsky link draws Lord Bell into action\n  |work=Financial Times\n  | date = 24 November 2006\n  | url = http://www.ft.com/cms/s/a8cc1da4-7bf7-11db-b1c6-0000779e2340.html\n  | accessdate = 27 November 2006}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2006, Lord Bell successfully lobbied on behalf of the [[Saudi government]] to discontinue the [[Serious Fraud Office (UK)|Serious Fraud Office]] investigation into alleged bribes in the [[Al Yamamah#Investigation discontinued|Al Yamamah]] arms deal.<ref name=\"guardianbrutal\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/armstrade/story/0,,1973421,00.html| title=Brutal politics lesson for corruption investigators|author=David Leigh|author2=Rob Evans |date=16 December 2006|work=The Guardian |location=UK|accessdate=16 December 2006}}</ref>\n\nLord Bell also performed public relations work for the authoritarian government of [[Belarus]],<ref>[http://www.economist.com/agenda/displaystory.cfm?story_id=12342630&fsrc=rss \"No breakthrough in Belarus\"], ''The Economist'', 2 October 2008</ref> and for the [[Pinochet]] Foundation (Fundaci\u00f3n Pinochet). In addition, he worked as an advisor to former Malaysian Prime Minister [[Mahathir Mohamad]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Moseley |first=Ray |date=18 February 1994 |title=Malaysia Dam Linked To Arms Deal With Britain |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1994-02-18/news/9402180371_1_british-airways-british-aid-malaysian-prime-minister-mahathir |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |location=Chicago |accessdate=26 December 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn late 2011, Bell's lobbying interests were investigated by the [[Bureau of Investigative Journalism]] for ''[[The Independent]]'' newspaper which reported claims that the company attempts to interfere with Google results to \"drown\" out coverage of human rights abuses, that his employees had altered [[English Wikipedia]] entries to create a better impression of clients and had easy access (via former Conservative MP [[Tim Collins (politician)|Tim Collins]]) to the Cameron government and others overseas.<ref name=\"NewmanWright\">Melanie Newman and Oliver Wright  [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/caught-on-camera-top-lobbyists-boasting-how-they-influence-the-pm-6272760.html \"Caught on camera: top lobbyists boasting how they influence the PM\"], ''The Independent'', 6 December 2011</ref> Bell Pottinger, via a sting operation, were found to be willing to work for the authoritarian regime in Uzbekistan.<ref name=\"NewmanWright\"/> Bell launched an internal inquiry, but believed he had been singled out for his connection with Mrs Thatcher.<ref name=EveSta>Stephen Robinson [https://web.archive.org/web/20111208213424/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/lifestyle/article-24019238-of-course-i-regret-it-i-need-it-like-a-hole-in-the-head-all-this-st.do \"'Of course I regret it, I need it like a hole in the head, all this s**t'\"], ''Evening Standard'' (London), 8 December 2011. Retrieved 27 February 2013.</ref>\n\nChime disposed of Bell Pottinger in June 2012 (while retaining a 25% stake in the business), when Bell also resigned as a director of Chime.<ref name=ChimeCoD>{{cite web|title=Completion of Disposal|url=http://www.chime.plc.uk/announcements/chime-final-of-mbo-new-director-of-board|work=Market Announcements, Monday 02 July 2012|publisher=Chime plc|accessdate=20 August 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130114050941/http://www.chime.plc.uk/announcements/chime-final-of-mbo-new-director-of-board|archivedate=14 January 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Bell Pottinger exit under cloud of PR malpractice==\n[[Bell Pottinger#.27White Monopoly Capital.27|Bell Pottinger]] announced Lord Bell's departure as chairman to set up an advisory firm, Sans Fronti\u00e8res Associates, in August 2016. He retained a 7% stake in Bell Pottinger.<ref name=\"Mance-25Aug2016\">{{cite news|last1=Mance|first1=Henry|title=Lord Bell quits as Bell Pottinger chairman|url=https://www.ft.com/content/10114318-6adb-11e6-ae5b-a7cc5dd5a28c?mhq5j=e3|accessdate=29 June 2017|work=Financial Times|date=25 August 2016}}</ref> Tony Walford, partner at Green Square stated, \"Perhaps not coincidentally, Sans Fronti\u00e8res was the original name of the public relations firm he set up before it was renamed Bell Pottinger; it was also the name of the unit that handled the firm's controversial lobbying and consultancy work for the governments of countries such as Belarus and Sri Lanka.\"<ref name=\"TD-2Sep2016\">{{cite news|last1=Walford|first1=Tony|title=Why maverick PR man Lord Bell may enjoy being his own man again|url=http://www.thedrum.com/opinion/2016/09/02/sans-fronti-res-why-maverick-pr-man-lord-bell-may-enjoy-being-his-own-man-again|accessdate=5 September 2017|work=The Drum|date=2 September 2016}}</ref>\nA \"leading PR figure\" told ''[[The Times]]'' that his resignation from his own agency didn't come as a surprise, saying: \"Ultimately, he did not fit with the kind of corporate image Bell Pottinger wanted to project\", in the end.<ref name=\"TD-26Aug2016\">{{cite news|last1=Stuart|first1=Rebecca|title=Lord Bell departs from Bell Pottinger to open new PR firm Sans Fronti\u00e8res|url=http://www.thedrum.com/news/2016/08/26/lord-bell-departs-bell-pottinger-open-new-pr-firm-sans-fronti-res|accessdate=5 September 2017|work=The Drum|date=26 August 2016}}</ref> \nWalford explains that, \"there is big money to be made from representing governments and other entities, no matter how reviled they are. The problem is, this kind of activity sits increasingly uneasily with corporates keen on projecting a responsible image.\"<ref name=\"TD-2Sep2016\"/>\n\nIn January 2017 the ''[[Huffington Post]]'' reported that [[Johann Rupert]], CEO of [[Remgro]] and [[Richemont]], ended an 18 year old contract with Bell Pottinger due to their 'concerted effort on social and other media to discredit him'. Rupert had spoken out against [[state capture]] and called on President [[Jacob Zuma]] to resign \"for the sake of our children\". As the [[State capture#South Africa|Guptas]] back [[Jacob Zuma#Gupta family relationship|Zuma]], Rupert asserted that Bell Pottinger painted him as the embodiment of [[Bell Pottinger#.27White Monopoly Capital.27|white monopoly capital]] and as the counterweight to the Guptas and state capture, an example of how state capture allegedly worked under apartheid.<ref name=\"HP 25 January 2017\">{{cite news |last= du Toit |first= Pieter | authorlink= |title= How Rupert Was Warned About Bell Pottinger: 'They're Behind It.' |url= http://www.huffingtonpost.co.za/2017/01/25/how-rupert-was-warned-about-bell-pottinger-theyre-behind-it_a_21662494/| date= 25 January 2017|work= [[Huffington Post]] |location=London| accessdate= 5 September 2017 }}</ref>\n\nEleven months after leaving Bell Pottinger and six days after the [[Public Relations and Communications Association]] (PRCA) acknowledged receipt of the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance's]] complaint,<ref name=\"STSA-4Jul2017\">{{cite news|title=Bell Pottinger probed for stoking racial tension in SA|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2017-07-04-bell-pottinger-probed-for-stoking-racial-tension-in-sa/|accessdate=5 July 2017|work=Sunday Times (South Africa)|date=4 July 2017}}</ref> on 11 July 2017 Bell announces for the first recorded time to ''[[PRWeek]]'' that he had left Bell Pottinger after raising his concerns about its \"smelly\" relationship with the [[Gupta family]]'s Oakbay conglomerate in South Africa but that they had \"completely ignored me\"; Bell Pottinger denied his claims.<ref name=\"PRWeek 11 July 2017\">{{cite news |last= Burne James |first= Sam | authorlink= |title= 'I kept saying it was smelly': Lord Bell claims Bell Pottinger ignored his concerns over Gupta work |url= http://www.prweek.com/article/1439079/i-kept-saying-smelly-lord-bell-claims-bell-pottinger-ignored-concerns-gupta-work| date= 11 July 2017|work= [[PRWeek]] |location=London| accessdate= 4 September 2017 }}</ref>\n\nThe PRCA expelled Bell Pottinger for at least five years from September 2017 for inflaming racial tensions in [[South Africa]]. The PRCA found Bell Pottinger guilty of four breaches of its code of conduct and dispensed its toughest possible punishment. PRCA director-general, Francis Ingham told the [[Financial Times|FT]], \"This is the most blatant instance of unethical PR practice I\u2019ve ever seen. Bell Pottinger's work has set back South Africa by possibly 10 years.\"<ref name=\"FT 4 September 2017\">{{cite news |last= Bond |first= David | authorlink= |title= 'Bell Pottinger expelled by industry body for unethical practice |url= https://www.ft.com/content/66088476-9176-11e7-bdfa-eda243196c2c| date= 4 September 2017|work= [[Financial Times]] |location=London| accessdate= 4 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring a live ''[[Newsnight]]'' interview on 4 September 2017, Lord Bell mentioned that he was the most senior director at the several hour long initial meeting with the [[Gupta family|Guptas]]. Bell explained to [[Kirsty Wark]] that upon his return to London he told Bell Pottinger CEO [[James Henderson (businessman)|James Henderson]], \"it's a very interesting piece of business but we can't handle it because there's a conflict of interest\". [[Kirsty Wark|Wark]] then read Bell his own email, dated 26 January 2016, stating, \"The trip was a great success and we will put forward a deal whereby we will earn \u00a3100,000 per month plus costs and I will oversee this and make further reports.\" Wark asserted that the email was in \"direct conflict with what you just said\". Bell went on to deny this on the basis the email was sent before his return to London. Rather than oversee the deal, Bell claimed that upon his return \"I did absolutely nothing\", but Bell Pottinger \"submitted a [fee] proposal\". Bell went on to deny Wark's assertion that he is the senior figure working on the Gupta account, but rather he is a \"father figure of the meeting\". Wark asked that when Bell, as the founder of the company, stated that there was a conflict of interest, \"nobody listens? Really?\". Bell responded, \"Nobody listens to me. That's why I left the company\". Wark then produced a further Bell-authored email, dated 3 months later (April 2016), in which Bell offered further advice regarding the account. Bell retorted, \"You can attack me all you like but I had nothing to do with getting this account.\"<ref name=\"HP 4 September 2017\">{{cite news |last= Demianyk |first= Graeme | authorlink= |title= 'Lord Bell On BBC Newsnight: Bell Pottinger Co-Founder's Extraordinary Interview Amid Firm's South Africa Racism Row. His phone going off twice is just the tip of the iceberg. |url= http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/lord-bell-newsnight-bell-pottinger_uk_59adcd54e4b0354e440be8f1| date= 4 September 2017|work= [[Huffington Post]] |location=London| accessdate= 4 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nBell's Newsnight performance was pilloried by the UK press, with ''[[The Spectator]]'' labelling it, \"Lord Bell's Newsnight PR disaster\".<ref name=\"Spectator 5 September 2017\">{{cite news |last= Steerpike |first=  | authorlink= |title= 'Lord Bell's Newsnight PR disaster. |url= https://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:5z2gi9eE2V0J:https://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2017/09/lord-bells-newsnight-pr-disaster/+&cd=10&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=uk| date= 5 September 2017|work= [[The Spectator]] |location=London| accessdate= 5 September 2017}}</ref>\nThe ''[[Daily Express]]''{{'}}s take was, \"Lord Bell was left red-faced after his phone rang twice while he was live on air during a Newsnight interview.\".<ref name=\"The Express 5 September 2017\">{{cite news |last= Hunt |first= Darren | authorlink= |title=\"'Someone's popular!' Nail-biting moment Newsnight guest's phone interrupts tense interview.\" |url= http://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/850119/BBC-Newsnight-Bell-Pottinger-phone-stops-interview-interrupt-video-Lord-Bell | date= 5 September 2017|work= [[Daily Express]] |location=London| accessdate= 5 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nAn alternative view of what happened was published in The Drum on 5 September 2019. It stated Bell had a genuine desire to help the Indian-descended Guptas from being discriminated against in South Africa. However, Bell suffered a stroke in 2016 and was put on three months medical leave. CEO James Henderson used Bell's absence to ensure the account was run exclusively by his financial PR Team, under Victoria Geoghegan. Fake Twitter accounts were set up accusing white businessmen, such as Johann Rupert, of \"white monopoly capital\". When Bell returned from medical leave, he had a row with Henderson telling him he had to resign the account and when he refused, Bell resigned from the company. After the story broke in 2017, Johann Rupert claimed Bell was \"the only person to have acted with honour in the entire affair.\"<ref>https://www.thedrum.com/opinion/2019/09/05/with-the-passing-lord-bell-i-fear-we-will-not-see-his-again</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBell was married three times: first, in the 1960s, to Suzanne Cordran (marriage dissolved in 1985); in 1988 he married Virginia Hornbrook with whom he had a son and daughter (marriage dissolved in 2016); in 2017, he married Jacky Phillips.<ref name=TelegraphObit/>\n\nBell died from complications of vascular [[parkinsonism]] at his home in London on 25 August 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/obituaries/tim-bell-swaggering-pr-executive-and-spin-doctor-for-margaret-thatcher-dies-at-77/2019/08/26/1686949a-c80d-11e9-be05-f76ac4ec618c_story.html|title = Tim Bell, swaggering PR executive and spin doctor for Margaret Thatcher, dies at 77|date = 26 August 2019|accessdate = 26 August 2019|work = [[The Washington Post]]|last = Smith|first = Harrison}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://euobserver.com/24/26909 Lukashenko's PR man sheds light on EU campaign] EU Observer, 10 October 2008\n*[http://www.data.minsk.by/belarusnews/052008/244.html Can Lord Bell\u2019s PR skills combat the aroma of communism and cabbage?] Minsk.by, 28 May 2008\n*[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/how-to-sell-democracy-to-iraqis-bring-in-lord-bell-566189.html How to sell democracy to Iraqis: bring in Lord Bell] ''[[The Independent]]'', 13 March 2004\n*[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld199798/minutes/981014/ldminute.htm Announcement of his introduction at the House of Lords] House of Lords minutes of proceedings, 14 October 1998\n*[http://www.publicwhip.org.uk/mp.php?mpn=Lord_Bell&mpc=Lords&display=allvotes Parliamentary voting record for Lord Bell]\n*[http://www.charter97.org/en/news/2008/10/23/11396/ Belarusian have answered to Lord Bell]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bell, Timothy}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:Advertising people]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople awarded knighthoods]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in England]]\n[[Category:English businesspeople]]\n[[Category:English memoirists]]\n[[Category:English people of Australian descent]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:People educated at Queen Elizabeth's Grammar School for Boys]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life and career:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: ,  \u2192 ,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Timothy_Bell,_Baron_Bell"}
{"title_page": "This Is How We Roll", "text_new": "{{short description|country song}}\n{{For|the Fifth Harmony song of the same name|Reflection (Fifth Harmony album)}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = This Is How We Roll\n| cover      = ThisIsHowWeRoll.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Florida Georgia Line]] featuring [[Luke Bryan]]\n| album      = [[Here's to the Good Times|Here's to the Good Times... This Is How We Roll]]\n| released   = {{Start date|2014|02|10}}\n| format     = [[Music download|Digital download]]\n| recorded   = 2013\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Country rap]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=40}}\n| label      = [[Republic Nashville]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Tyler Hubbard]]|[[Brian Kelley (musician)|Brian Kelley]]|[[Cole Swindell]]|Luke Bryan}}\n| producer   = [[Joey Moi]]\n| chronology = [[Florida Georgia Line]]\n| prev_title = [[The South (song)|The South]]\n| prev_year  = 2013\n| next_title = [[Dirt (song)|Dirt]]\n| next_year  = 2014\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Luke Bryan]]\n | type       = single\n | prev_title = [[Drink a Beer]]\n | prev_year  = 2013\n | title      = This Is How We Roll\n | year       = 2014\n | next_title = [[Play It Again (Luke Bryan song)|Play It Again]]\n | next_year  = 2014\n}}\n{{Extra album cover\n | header  = Alternate cover\n | type    = single\n | cover   = Florida Georgia Line - This Is How We Roll Remix (feat. Luke Bryan and Jason Derulo) (Official Single Cover).png\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption = Cover for the remix featuring [[Jason Derulo]]\n}}\n}}\n\"'''This Is How We Roll'''\" is a song recorded by American [[country music]] duo [[Florida Georgia Line]] with fellow country music singer [[Luke Bryan]]. It is the fifth and final single from Florida Georgia Line's debut studio album, ''[[Here's to the Good Times]]'', although it is only included on the 2013 ''This Is How We Roll'' re-release. [[Cole Swindell]] assisted the artists in writing the song. A remix, featuring [[Jason Derulo]] and Bryan was released on June 6, 2014.\n\n==Critical reception==\nIn a review of the album's rerelease, Matt Bjorke of ''Roughstock'' wrote that it is a \"song which is definitely well within the musical pocket each of the song\u2019s writers have in their music and an obvious choice for single at some point. It\u2019s another sing-a-long, small town love type of song but does that matter at this point, it\u2019s a song that\u2019s all about feeling good with people you love to be with.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roughstock.com/reviews/album-review-florida-georgia-line-here-s-to-the-good-times-this-is-how-we-roll|title=Album Review: Florida Georgia Line - Here's To The Good Times...This Is How We Roll|last=Bjorke|first=Matt|date=25 November 2013|work=Roughstock|accessdate=7 March 2014}}</ref> Website ''[[Taste of Country]]'' also reviewed the song favorably, saying that \"\u2018Get Your Shine On,\u2019 \u2018Round Here\u2019 and \u2018Stay\u2019 have found success on country radio, but this track from the group\u2019s deluxe edition of \u2018Here\u2019s to the Good Times\u2019 is their best moment since \u2018Cruise.\u2019 They can get away with the rapping now, and having the stamp of approval from country\u2019s reigning ACM Entertainer of the Year certainly won\u2019t hurt.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Florida Georgia Line (Feat. Luke Bryan), \u2018This Is How We Roll\u2019 [Listen]|url=http://tasteofcountry.com/florida-georgia-line-luke-bryan-this-is-how-we-roll/|work=Taste of Country|accessdate=7 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nThe music video was directed by [[Marc Klasfeld]] and premiered in March 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cmt.com/videos/florida-georgia-line/1009728/this-is-how-we-roll.jhtml|title=CMT : Videos : Florida Georgina Line : This Is How We Roll|publisher=[[Country Music Television]]|accessdate=March 9, 2014}}</ref>\n\nA biker named Kenny loses a bet and has to jump a tree. He fails, resulting in his dirt bike being stuck in the tree. When he, Travis Pastrana and other men are found stranded by Hubbard, Kelley, and Bryan as a result of the failed dirt bike trick, Kelley invites them to a party in the back of their semi truck, which is revealed throughout the video to consist of dancing women and beer. The trio can be seen both inside and on top of the truck as it travels. Towards the end of the video, dirt bikers perform tricks as they fly over the trio, who are standing on solid ground.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tasteofcountry.com/florida-georgia-line-this-is-how-we-roll-video-luke-bryan/|title=Florida Georgia Line Party Atop A Semi In 'This Is How We Roll' Music Video With Luke Bryan|first=Christina|last=Vinson|publisher=Taste of Country|accessdate=May 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Commercial performance ==\nThe song first entered the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart at number 75, and at number 18 on the [[Hot Country Songs]]  chart and sold 52,000 digital copies for the week when the deluxe version of the album, ''Here's To The Good Times...This Is How We Roll'', was released on November 25, 2013.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-615/5819664/garth-brooks-returns-to-top-country-albums-summit  |title=Garth Brooks Returns to Top Country Albums Summit |author=Wade Jessen |date= December 5, 2013 |work=Billboard}}</ref><ref name=\"Roughstock 12-04-2013\">{{cite news |title=Country Chart News - The Top 30 Digital Singles - December 4, 2013: Florida Georgia Line Dominate Top 5 & Top 30 Chart|url=http://www.roughstock.com/blog/country-chart-news-the-top-30-digital-singles-december-4-2013-florida-georgia-line-dominate-top-5-top-30-chart |last=Bjorke |first=Matt |work=Roughstock |date=2013-12-04}}</ref> It reached number one on the Hot Country Songs chart for the week ending of March 28, 2014 and stayed at number one for four weeks.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/chart-alert/6091998/chart-moves-florida-georgia-lines-good-times-keep-rollin-ben  |title=Chart Moves: Florida Georgia Line's 'Good Times' Keep Rollin', Ben & Ellen Harper Keep It in the Family |author= Keith Caulfield |date= May 16, 2014 |work=Billboard}}</ref> It also peaked on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 chart at number 15 for the week ending of April 26, 2014. After it was released to radio, the song received significant airplay to enter the Country Airplay chart at number 25 for the week ending of March 1, 2014. It continued climbing the chart and peaked at number 2 in May 2014.\n\nThe song reached its first million sales mark in April 2014,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart-watch/chart-watch-sell-14k-albums-top-10-172855366.html |title=Chart Watch: Pharrell Steps Up | author=Paul Grein |date=April 30, 2014 |work=Yahoo Music }}</ref> and its second in September 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart-watch/chart-watch-women-own-the-pop-chart-212718757.html |title=Chart Watch: Women Own The Pop Chart | author=Paul Grein |date=September 3, 2014 |work=Yahoo Music }}</ref> It was certified Platinum by the RIAA on May 1, 2014, double Platinum on September 16, 2014, and quintuple Platinum on December 12, 2018.<ref name=RIAA /> As of January 2015, the song has sold 2,276,000 copies in the US.<ref name=\"singles\">{{cite news |url=http://roughstock.com/news/2015/01/32252-country-musics-top-30-digital-singles-week-january-21-2015/ |title=Country Music\u2019s Top 30 Digital Singles: Week of January 21, 2015 |author= Matt Bjorke |date=January 21, 2015 |work=Roughstock }} Sales figures given [https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1OQSwu651Nu1PpvWGslphCoewhgaloUOuo5-Ooh6iODM/edit#gid=0 here]</ref>\n\nThe song is featured in the video game ''[[WWE 2K15]]''.\n\n==Charts and certifications==\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n=== Weekly charts ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Chart (2013\u201314)\n! Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canada|20|artist=Florida Georgia Line}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardcanadachrtop40|46|artist=Florida Georgia Line}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardcanadacountry|2|artist=Florida Georgia Line}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|15|artist=Florida Georgia Line}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardcountrysongs|1|artist=Florida Georgia Line}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardcountryairplay|2|artist=Florida Georgia Line}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardadultpopsongs|23|artist=Florida Georgia Line|note=Jason Derulo remix}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardpopsongs|25|artist=Florida Georgia Line|note=Jason Derulo remix}}\n|}\n\n===Certifications===\n{{certification Table Top}} \n{{certification Table Entry|region=United States|artist=Florida Georgia Line|title=This Is How We Roll|award=Platinum|number=5|certyear=2017|relyear=2012|type=single|salesamount=5,000,000<sup>{{double dagger}}</sup> / 2,276,000 |refname=RIAA |salesref=<ref name=\"singles\"/>}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom||noshipments=true|streaming=true}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (2014)\n!scope=\"col\"|Position\n|-\n| Canada [[Canadian Hot 100]]<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2014/canadian-hot-100 | title=Best of 2014: Canadian Hot 100 | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] | date=2014 | accessdate=December 9, 2014}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\" | 70\n|-\n| US ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]]<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2014/hot-100-songs | title=Best of 2014: Hot 100 Songs | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] | date=2014 | accessdate=December 9, 2014}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\" | 49\n|-\n| US [[Country Airplay]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2014/country-airplay-songs | title=Best of 2014: Country Airplay | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] | date=2014 | accessdate=December 9, 2014}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\" | 22\n|-\n| US [[Hot Country Songs]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2014/hot-country-songs | title=Best of 2014: Hot Country Songs | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] | date=2014 | accessdate=December 9, 2014}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\" | 1\n|-\n|}\n\n===Decade-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable \n|-\n! Chart (2010\u20132019)\n! Position\n|-\n| US Hot Country Songs (''Billboard'')<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/decade-end/hot-country-songs|title=Decade-End Charts: Hot Country Songs|work=Billboard|accessdate=January 23, 2020}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 16\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Release history==\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Country\n!scope=\"col\"|Date\n!scope=\"col\"|Format\n!scope=\"col\"|Version\n!scope=\"col\"|Record label\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| United States\n|February 10, 2014<ref>{{cite web|title=R&R :: Going For Adds :: Country|url=http://gfa.radioandrecords.com/PublishGFA/GFANextPage.asp?sDate=02/10/2014&Format=4|publisher=[[Radio & Records]]|accessdate=1 July 2014}}</ref>\n|[[Country music|Country radio]]\n|Original\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[Republic Records|Republic]]\n|-\n|June 17, 2014<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allaccess.com/top40-mainstream/future-releases |title=Top 40/M Future Releases |publisher=All Access Music Group |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6QL2dHy8M |archivedate=15 June 2014}}</ref>\n|[[Contemporary hit radio]]\n|Jason Derulo remix\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of number-one country singles of 2014 (U.S.)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Florida Georgia Line}}\n{{Luke Bryan}}\n{{Jason Derulo}}\n{{Billboard Year-End Hot Country Singles number one single of the year}}\n\n[[Category:2014 singles]]\n[[Category:Florida Georgia Line songs]]\n[[Category:Jason Derulo songs]]\n[[Category:Luke Bryan songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Cole Swindell]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Luke Bryan]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Joey Moi]]\n[[Category:Republic Records singles]]\n[[Category:Republic Nashville singles]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Marc Klasfeld]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot Country Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:2012 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Tyler Hubbard]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Brian Kelley (musician)]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot Country Songs number-one singles of the year]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|country song}}\n{{For|the Fifth Harmony song of the same name|Reflection (Fifth Harmony album)}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = This Is How We Roll\n| cover      = ThisIsHowWeRoll.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Florida Georgia Line]] featuring [[Luke Bryan]]\n| album      = [[Here's to the Good Times|Here's to the Good Times... This Is How We Roll]]\n| released   = {{Start date|2014|02|10}}\n| format     = [[Music download|Digital download]]\n| recorded   = 2013\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Country rap]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=40}}\n| label      = [[Republic Nashville]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Tyler Hubbard]]|[[Brian Kelley (musician)|Brian Kelley]]|[[Cole Swindell]]|Luke Bryan}}\n| producer   = [[Joey Moi]]\n| chronology = [[Florida Georgia Line]]\n| prev_title = [[The South (song)|The South]]\n| prev_year  = 2013\n| next_title = [[Dirt (song)|Dirt]]\n| next_year  = 2014\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Luke Bryan]]\n | type       = single\n | prev_title = [[Drink a Beer]]\n | prev_year  = 2013\n | title      = This Is How We Roll\n | year       = 2014\n | next_title = [[Play It Again (Luke Bryan song)|Play It Again]]\n | next_year  = 2014\n}}\n{{Extra album cover\n | header  = Alternate cover\n | type    = single\n | cover   = Florida Georgia Line - This Is How We Roll Remix (feat. Luke Bryan and Jason Derulo) (Official Single Cover).png\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption = Cover for the remix featuring [[Jason Derulo]]\n}}\n}}\n\"'''This Is How We Roll'''\" is a song recorded by American [[country music]] duo [[Florida Georgia Line]] with fellow country music singer [[Luke Bryan]]. It is the fifth and final single from Florida Georgia Line's debut studio album, ''[[Here's to the Good Times]]'', although it is only included on the 2013 ''This Is How We Roll'' re-release. [[Cole Swindell]] assisted the artists in writing the song. A remix, featuring [[Jason Derulo]] and Bryan was released on June 6, 2014.\n\n==Critical reception==\nIn a review of the album's rerelease, Matt Bjorke of ''Roughstock'' wrote that it is a \"song which is definitely well within the musical pocket each of the song\u2019s writers have in their music and an obvious choice for single at some point. It\u2019s another sing-a-long, small town love type of song but does that matter at this point, it\u2019s a song that\u2019s all about feeling good with people you love to be with.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roughstock.com/reviews/album-review-florida-georgia-line-here-s-to-the-good-times-this-is-how-we-roll|title=Album Review: Florida Georgia Line - Here's To The Good Times...This Is How We Roll|last=Bjorke|first=Matt|date=25 November 2013|work=Roughstock|accessdate=7 March 2014}}</ref> Website ''[[Taste of Country]]'' also reviewed the song favorably, saying that \"\u2018Get Your Shine On,\u2019 \u2018Round Here\u2019 and \u2018Stay\u2019 have found success on country radio, but this track from the group\u2019s deluxe edition of \u2018Here\u2019s to the Good Times\u2019 is their best moment since \u2018Cruise.\u2019 They can get away with the rapping now, and having the stamp of approval from country\u2019s reigning ACM Entertainer of the Year certainly won\u2019t hurt.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Florida Georgia Line (Feat. Luke Bryan), \u2018This Is How We Roll\u2019 [Listen]|url=http://tasteofcountry.com/florida-georgia-line-luke-bryan-this-is-how-we-roll/|work=Taste of Country|accessdate=7 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nThe music video was directed by [[Marc Klasfeld]] and premiered in March 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cmt.com/videos/florida-georgia-line/1009728/this-is-how-we-roll.jhtml|title=CMT : Videos : Florida Georgina Line : This Is How We Roll|publisher=[[Country Music Television]]|accessdate=March 9, 2014}}</ref>\n\nA biker named Kenny loses a bet and has to jump a tree. He fails, resulting in his dirt bike being stuck in the tree. When he, Travis Pastrana and other men are found stranded by Hubbard, Kelley, and Bryan as a result of the failed dirt bike trick, Kelley invites them to a party in the back of their semi truck, which is revealed throughout the video to consist of dancing women and beer. The trio can be seen both inside and on top of the truck as it travels. Towards the end of the video, dirt bikers perform tricks as they fly over the trio, who are standing on solid ground.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tasteofcountry.com/florida-georgia-line-this-is-how-we-roll-video-luke-bryan/|title=Florida Georgia Line Party Atop A Semi In 'This Is How We Roll' Music Video With Luke Bryan|first=Christina|last=Vinson|publisher=Taste of Country|accessdate=May 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Commercial performance ==\nThe song first entered the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart at number 75, and at number 18 on the [[Hot Country Songs]]  chart and sold 52,000 digital copies for the week when the deluxe version of the album, ''Here's To The Good Times...This Is How We Roll'', was released in November 25, 2013.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-615/5819664/garth-brooks-returns-to-top-country-albums-summit  |title=Garth Brooks Returns to Top Country Albums Summit |author=Wade Jessen |date= December 5, 2013 |work=Billboard}}</ref><ref name=\"Roughstock 12-04-2013\">{{cite news |title=Country Chart News - The Top 30 Digital Singles - December 4, 2013: Florida Georgia Line Dominate Top 5 & Top 30 Chart|url=http://www.roughstock.com/blog/country-chart-news-the-top-30-digital-singles-december-4-2013-florida-georgia-line-dominate-top-5-top-30-chart |last=Bjorke |first=Matt |work=Roughstock |date=2013-12-04}}</ref> It reached number one on the Hot Country Songs chart for the week ending of March 28, 2014 and stayed at number one for four weeks.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/chart-alert/6091998/chart-moves-florida-georgia-lines-good-times-keep-rollin-ben  |title=Chart Moves: Florida Georgia Line's 'Good Times' Keep Rollin', Ben & Ellen Harper Keep It in the Family |author= Keith Caulfield |date= May 16, 2014 |work=Billboard}}</ref> It also peaked on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 chart at number 15 for the week ending of April 26, 2014. After it was released to radio, the song received significant airplay to enter the Country Airplay chart at number 25 for the week ending of March 1, 2014. It continued climbing the chart and peaked at number 2 in May 2014.\n\nThe song reached its first million sales mark in April 2014,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart-watch/chart-watch-sell-14k-albums-top-10-172855366.html |title=Chart Watch: Pharrell Steps Up | author=Paul Grein |date=April 30, 2014 |work=Yahoo Music }}</ref> and its second in September 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart-watch/chart-watch-women-own-the-pop-chart-212718757.html |title=Chart Watch: Women Own The Pop Chart | author=Paul Grein |date=September 3, 2014 |work=Yahoo Music }}</ref> It was certified Platinum by the RIAA on May 1, 2014, double Platinum on September 16, 2014, and quintuple Platinum on December 12, 2018.<ref name=RIAA /> As of January 2015, the song has sold 2,276,000 copies in the US.<ref name=\"singles\">{{cite news |url=http://roughstock.com/news/2015/01/32252-country-musics-top-30-digital-singles-week-january-21-2015/ |title=Country Music\u2019s Top 30 Digital Singles: Week of January 21, 2015 |author= Matt Bjorke |date=January 21, 2015 |work=Roughstock }} Sales figures given [https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1OQSwu651Nu1PpvWGslphCoewhgaloUOuo5-Ooh6iODM/edit#gid=0 here]</ref>\n\nThe song is featured in the video game ''[[WWE 2K15]]''.\n\n==Charts and certifications==\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n=== Weekly charts ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Chart (2013\u201314)\n! Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canada|20|artist=Florida Georgia Line}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardcanadachrtop40|46|artist=Florida Georgia Line}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardcanadacountry|2|artist=Florida Georgia Line}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|15|artist=Florida Georgia Line}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardcountrysongs|1|artist=Florida Georgia Line}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardcountryairplay|2|artist=Florida Georgia Line}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardadultpopsongs|23|artist=Florida Georgia Line|note=Jason Derulo remix}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardpopsongs|25|artist=Florida Georgia Line|note=Jason Derulo remix}}\n|}\n\n===Certifications===\n{{certification Table Top}} \n{{certification Table Entry|region=United States|artist=Florida Georgia Line|title=This Is How We Roll|award=Platinum|number=5|certyear=2017|relyear=2012|type=single|salesamount=5,000,000<sup>{{double dagger}}</sup> / 2,276,000 |refname=RIAA |salesref=<ref name=\"singles\"/>}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom||noshipments=true|streaming=true}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (2014)\n!scope=\"col\"|Position\n|-\n| Canada [[Canadian Hot 100]]<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2014/canadian-hot-100 | title=Best of 2014: Canadian Hot 100 | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] | date=2014 | accessdate=December 9, 2014}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\" | 70\n|-\n| US ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]]<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2014/hot-100-songs | title=Best of 2014: Hot 100 Songs | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] | date=2014 | accessdate=December 9, 2014}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\" | 49\n|-\n| US [[Country Airplay]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2014/country-airplay-songs | title=Best of 2014: Country Airplay | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] | date=2014 | accessdate=December 9, 2014}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\" | 22\n|-\n| US [[Hot Country Songs]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2014/hot-country-songs | title=Best of 2014: Hot Country Songs | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] | date=2014 | accessdate=December 9, 2014}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\" | 1\n|-\n|}\n\n===Decade-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable \n|-\n! Chart (2010\u20132019)\n! Position\n|-\n| US Hot Country Songs (''Billboard'')<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/decade-end/hot-country-songs|title=Decade-End Charts: Hot Country Songs|work=Billboard|accessdate=January 23, 2020}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 16\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Release history==\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Country\n!scope=\"col\"|Date\n!scope=\"col\"|Format\n!scope=\"col\"|Version\n!scope=\"col\"|Record label\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| United States\n|February 10, 2014<ref>{{cite web|title=R&R :: Going For Adds :: Country|url=http://gfa.radioandrecords.com/PublishGFA/GFANextPage.asp?sDate=02/10/2014&Format=4|publisher=[[Radio & Records]]|accessdate=1 July 2014}}</ref>\n|[[Country music|Country radio]]\n|Original\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[Republic Records|Republic]]\n|-\n|June 17, 2014<ref>