gh\n| honorific-suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|KG|CBE|MC|TD|PCi}}\n| image            = Brookeborough_1963_UUC_Yearbook.jpg\n| imagesize        = 150px\n| office           = 3rd [[Prime Minister of Northern Ireland]]\n| monarch          = {{Plainlist|\n* [[George VI]]\n* [[Elizabeth II]]}}\n| governor         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[James Hamilton, 3rd Duke of Abercorn|The Duke of Abercorn]]\n* [[William Leveson-Gower, 4th Earl Granville|The Earl Granville]]\n* [[John Loder, 2nd Baron Wakehurst|The Lord Wakehurst]]}}\n| term_start       = 1 May 1943\n| term_end         = 26 March 1963\n| predecessor      = [[John Miller Andrews]]\n| successor        = [[Terence O'Neill]]\n| office3          = [[Leaders of the Ulster Unionist Party|Leader of the Ulster Unionist Party]]\n| term_start3      = 1 May 1946\n| term_end3        = 25 March 1963\n| predecessor3     = John Miller Andrews\n| successor3       = Captain Terence O'Neill\n| office4          = [[Minister of Commerce (Northern Ireland)|Minister of Commerce]]\n| primeminister4   = {{Plainlist|\n* [[J. M. Andrews]]\n* ''Himself''}}\n| term_start4      = 16 January 1941\n| term_end4        = 16 February 1945\n| predecessor4     = [[Milne Barbour|John Milne Barbour]]\n| successor4       = [[Roland Nugent]]\n| office5          = [[Minister of Agriculture (Northern Ireland)|Minister of Agriculture]]\n| primeminister5   = {{Plainlist|\n* [[James Craig, 1st Viscount Craigavon|The Viscount Craigavon]]\n* [[J. M. Andrews]]}}\n| term_start5      = 1 December 1933\n| term_end5        = 16 January 1941\n| predecessor5     = [[Sir Edward Archdale, 1st Baronet|Sir Edward Archdale]]\n| successor5       = [[Herbert Dixon, 1st Baron Glentoran|The Lord Glentoran]]\n| office7 =[[Northern Ireland Parliament|Member of the Northern Ireland Parliament]]<br /> for [[Lisnaskea (Northern Ireland Parliament constituency)|Lisnaskea]]\n| parliament7      = Northern Ireland\n| term_start7     = 22 May 1929\n| term_end7        = 22 March 1968\n| predecessor7     = New constituency\n| successor7      = [[John Brooke, 2nd Viscount Brookeborough|John Brooke]]\n| office2          = [[Lord Lieutenant of Fermanagh]]\n| monarch2      =[[Elizabeth II]]\n| term_start2      = 26 April 1963\n| term_end2        = February 1969\n| predecessor2     = [[Earl of Enniskillen]]\n| successor2       = ''Vacant''\n| office6          = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br>[[Lord Temporal]]\n | term_start6       = 5 July 1952\n| term_end6         = 18 August 1973 <br>[[Hereditary Peerage]]\n| predecessor6     =  ''Peerage created''\n| successor6       = [[John Brooke, 2nd Viscount Brookeborough|The 2nd Viscount Brookeborough]]\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1888|06|09|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Brookeborough|Colebrooke Park, Brookeborough, County Fermanagh]], [[Ireland]]\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1973|08|18|1888|06|09|df=y}} \n| death_place      = Colebrooke Park, Brookeborough, County Fermanagh, Northern Ireland\n| party            = [[Ulster Unionist Party]]\n| spouse           = {{Plainlist|\n* {{Marriage |[[Cynthia Brooke, Viscountess Brookeborough|Cynthia Brooke]] |1919|1970|end=d}} \n* {{Marriage |Sarah Eileen Bell Calvert |1971}}}}\n| children         = 3\n| nationality      = British\n| education        = [[Winchester College]]\n| alma_mater       = [[Royal Military College, Sandhurst]]\n| allegiance       = United Kingdom\n| branch           = [[British Army]]\n| serviceyears     = 1908\u20131920\n| rank             = [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Captain]] \n| unit             = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Royal Fusiliers]]\n* [[10th Hussars]]}}\n| command          =\n| battles          = [[First World War]]\n| mawards          = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Military Cross]]\n* [[Croix de guerre 1914\u20131918 (France)|Croix de Guerre]] (France)}}\n}}\n[[File:Coat of Arms of Basil Brooke, 1st Viscount Brookeborough, KG, CBE, MC, TD, PC (Ire).png|thumb|262px|right|Garter-encircled coat of arms of Basil Brooke, 1st Viscount Brookeborough, KG, as displayed on his Order of the Garter stall plate in St. George's Chapel, Windsor Castle.]]\n'''Basil Stanlake Brooke, 1st Viscount Brookeborough''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|KG|CBE|MC|TD|PCi}} (9 June 1888 \u2013 18 August 1973), styled '''Sir Basil Brooke, 5th Baronet''' between 1907 and 1952, was an [[Ulster Unionist Party]] (UUP) politician who became the third [[Prime Minister of Northern Ireland]] in May 1943, holding office until March 1963.\n\nLord Brookeborough had previously held several ministerial positions in the [[Government of Northern Ireland]], and has been described as \"perhaps the last Unionist leader to command respect, loyalty and affection across the social and political spectrum of the movement\".<ref>Walker, G, A history of the Ulster Unionist Party (Manchester 2004) p 150</ref> He has also been described as one of the most hardline [[anti-Catholic]] leaders of the UUP.<ref>Anti-Catholicism in Northern Ireland, 1600\u20131998\nThe Mote and the Beam\nby John D. Brewer with Gareth I. Higgins (1998)\n{{ISBN|0-333-74635-X}} (Paperback)</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBasil Stanlake Brooke was born on 9 June 1888 at Colebrooke Park, his family's [[Neo-classical architecture|neo-Classical]] [[ancestral seat]] on (what was then) the several-thousand acre Colebrooke Estate, just outside [[Brookeborough]], a village near [[Lisnaskea]] in [[County Fermanagh]], [[Ireland]].<ref>Barton, Brian, ''Brookeborough: The Making of a Prime Minister'', 1988, p. 15</ref>  He was the eldest son of [[Sir Arthur Douglas Brooke, 4th Baronet|Sir Arthur Douglas Brooke]], 4th [[Baronet]], whom he succeeded as [[Viscount Brookeborough|5th Baronet]] when his father died in 1907.<ref name=\"thepeerage.com\">{{cite web |last=Lundy |first=Darryl |url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p18091.htm#i180906 |title= thepeerage.com |publisher= The Peerage}}{{Unreliable source?|failed=y |date=September 2012}}<!--Lundy is not a reliable source so cite Lundy's reliable source See [[WP:SAYWHEREYOUREADIT]]--></ref> He was a nephew of [[Field marshal (United Kingdom)|Field Marshal]] [[Alan Brooke, 1st Viscount Alanbrooke|The 1st Viscount Alanbrooke]], [[Chief of the Imperial General Staff]] during [[World War II]], who was only five years his senior. His sister Sheelah married [[Sir Henry Mulholland, 1st Baronet|Sir Henry Mulholland]], Speaker of the Stormont House of Commons and son of Lord Dunleath. He was educated for five years at St. George's School in [[Pau, Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques|Pau]], France, and then at [[Winchester College]] (1901\u201305).<ref name=\"thepeerage.com\"/>\n\n==Military and paramilitary career==\nAfter graduating from the [[Royal Military College, Sandhurst]],<ref name=\"thepeerage.com\"/> the young Sir Basil Brooke, 5th Bt, was commissioned into the [[Royal Fusiliers]] on 26 September 1908 as a [[second lieutenant]].<ref name=\"LG 25 September 1908\">{{London Gazette |issue=28180 |date=25 September 1908 |page=6940 }}</ref> He transferred to the [[10th Hussars]] in 1911. He was awarded the [[Military Cross]] and [[Croix de guerre 1914-1918 (France)|Croix de Guerre]] with palm for his service during the [[First World War]].\n\nBrooke was a very active [[Ulster Unionist Party]] member and ally of [[Edward Carson]].  He founded his own paramilitary group, Brooke's [[Fermanagh Vigilance]], from men returning from the war front in 1918.  Although the umbrella [[Ulster Volunteers]] (UVF) had been quiescent during the war, it was not defunct. It re-emerged strongly in 1920, subsuming groups like Brooke's.<ref>Townshend, \"Easter 1916\" p.181.</ref>\n\nIn 1920, having reached the [[Ranks in the British Army|rank]] of [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]], Brooke left the [[British Army]] to farm the Colebrooke Estate, his family's [[country estate]] at [[Brookeborough]] in west [[Ulster]], at which point he turned towards a career in politics.<ref>Timothy Bowman, 'The Ulster Volunteer Force, 1910\u20131920: New Perspectives', in Boyce and O'Day (eds.), Ulster Crisis, pp.256\u20138.</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n{{Expand section|date=January 2008}}\n\nBrooke had a very long political career. When he resigned the [[Prime Minister of Northern Ireland|Premiership of Northern Ireland]] in March 1963, he was [[Northern Ireland]]'s longest-serving prime minister, having held office for two months short of 20 years.<ref name=\"The Times, 20 August 1973\"/> He had also established a United Kingdom record by holding government office continuously for 33 years.<ref name=\"The Times, 20 August 1973\"/>\n\nIn 1921 [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Captain]] Brooke was elected to the [[Senate of Northern Ireland]], but he resigned the following year to become Commandant of the [[Ulster Special Constabulary]] (USC) in their fight against the [[Irish Republican Army]] (IRA). He was created a [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] in 1921.<ref name=\"The Times, 20 August 1973\"/>\n\nIn 1929 he was elected to the [[House of Commons of Northern Ireland]] as [[Ulster Unionist Party]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]] for the [[Lisnaskea (Northern Ireland Parliament constituency)|Lisnaskea]] division of [[County Fermanagh]]. In the words of the ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]'', \"his thin, wiry frame, with the inevitable cigarette in hand, and clipped, [[anglicised]] accent were to be a feature of [[Stormont Estate|Stormont]] for the next forty years.\"\n\n===Cabinet minister===\nBrooke became [[Minister of Agriculture for Northern Ireland|Minister of Agriculture]] in 1933. By virtue of this appointment, he also acquired the rank of [[Privy Council of Northern Ireland|Privy Councillor of Northern Ireland]].<ref name=\"The Times, 20 August 1973\"/> He was thus known, from 1933 until his elevation to the [[British peerage|peerage]] in 1952, as [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Captain]] [[The Right Honourable]] Sir Basil Brooke, 5th [[Baronet]], [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]], [[Military Cross]], [[Privy Council of Northern Ireland]], [[Member of Parliament]]. From 1941 to 1943 he was [[Minister of Commerce for Northern Ireland|Minister of Commerce]].\n\nCapt. Brooke addressed an [[Orange Institution]] rally at [[Newtownbutler]] on 12 July 1933, where he said:\n{{quote|Many in this audience employ Catholics, but I have not one about my place. Catholics are out to destroy Ulster...If we in Ulster allow Roman Catholics to work on our farms we are traitors to Ulster...I would appeal to loyalists, therefore, wherever possible, to employ good Protestant lads and lassies.<ref>{{Cite book | last = Ryan | first = Alan | title = The Reader's Companion to Ireland | publisher = Harvest Books | year = 1999 | pages = [https://archive.org/details/readerscompanio000ryan/page/226 226] | isbn = 978-0-15-600559-3 | url = https://archive.org/details/readerscompanio000ryan/page/226 }}</ref><ref name=\"coogan\">{{Cite book | last = Coogan | first = Tim Pat | title = Ireland in the Twentieth Century | publisher = Palgrave Macmillan | year = 2004 | pages = [https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781403963970/page/299 299\u2013300] | isbn = 978-1-4039-6397-0 | url = https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781403963970/page/299 }}</ref>}}\n\nIn later years he expressed regret for the statement.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nPYhv7qrCTk</ref>\n\n===As Prime Minister===\nOn 2 May 1943 he succeeded [[John Miller Andrews|John M. Andrews]] as [[Prime Minister of Northern Ireland|Prime Minister]].<ref name=NYTimes>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1943/05/02/archives/northern-ireland-gets-new-premier-sir-basil-brooke-54-named-to.html |title=NORTHERN IRELAND GETS NEW PREMIER |accessdate=23 January 2015|author=|date=2 May 1943|work=[[The New York Times]]|quote=resigned after criticism from his own Unionist party with regard to the government's unemployment policy.}}</ref>\n\nIn 1952 Brookeborough, whilst Prime Minister, was raised to the peerage as [[Viscount Brookeborough]], the title taken from the village named after the Brookes. Although a peer, he retained his seat in the [[House of Commons of Northern Ireland|House of Commons]] at [[Stormont Estate|Stormont]] and remained PM for another decade.\n\nAs the [[Northern Ireland economy]] began to de-industrialise in the mid-1950s, leading to high unemployment amongst the Protestant working classes, Brookeborough faced increasing disenchantment amongst UUP [[backbenchers]] for what was regarded as his indifferent and ineffectual approach to mounting economic problems. As this disenchantment grew, British civil servants and some members of the UUP combined to exert discreet and ultimately effective pressure on Brookeborough to resign to make way for [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Captain]] [[Terence O'Neill]], who was [[Minister of Finance (Northern Ireland)|Minister of Finance]].<ref>MacDonald, Michael, ''Children of Wrath'', Cambridge, UK: Polity Press, 1986, p. 71</ref>\n\nIn 1963, his health having worsened, he resigned (at the age of 75) as Prime Minister. But he remained a member of the [[House of Commons of Northern Ireland]] until the [[1969 Northern Ireland general election|1969 general election]], becoming the [[Father of the House]] in 1965. During his last years in the [[Parliament of Northern Ireland]] he publicly opposed the liberal policies of his successor Terence O'Neill, who actively sought to improve relationships with the [[Republic of Ireland]], and who attempted to address some of the grievances of [[Irish Catholics|Catholics]] and grant many of the demands of the [[Northern Ireland Civil Rights Association]] (NICRA).\n\nBrookeborough was noted for his casual style towards his ministerial duties. Terence O'Neill later wrote of him: \"he was good company and a good raconteur, and those who met him imagined that he was relaxing away from his desk. However they did not realise that there was no desk.\"<ref name=\"The Times, 20 August 1973\"/>\n\nWhile Graham Walker wrote \"...Brookeborough's achievements over twenty years were substantial: the Unionist Party maintained essential unity, the anti-partitionist project was thwarted, and a potentially difficult post-war relationship with Britain under Labour was managed to the long-term benefit of Northern Ireland's full participation in the welfare state and new educational opportunities...\",<ref>Graham Walker, p.149</ref> increased educational opportunities for Catholics increased their self-confidence and expectations, which added momentum to the 1960s civil rights movement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=m69v-9b24B8C&pg=PA51&lpg=PA51&dq=northern+ireland+welfare+state+education+catholics&source=bl&ots=k_rs5YcYKB&sig=dgomon4ZSzTK8HZP5RRTsb8Gz2g&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CDUQ6AEwBjgKahUKEwi-gLTmrpzIAhUHThQKHdykAzA#v=onepage&q=northern+ireland+welfare+state+education+catholics&f=false|title=The British State and the Northern Ireland Crisis, 1969-73: From Violence to Power-sharing|first=William Beattie|last=Smith|date=4 July 2018|publisher=US Institute of Peace Press|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==Later life and death==\nIn his retirement Brookeborough developed commercial interests; as chairman of Carreras (Northern Ireland), a director of Devenish Trade, and president of the Northern Ireland [[Institute of Directors]]. He was also made an honorary LLD of [[Queen's University of Belfast|The Queen's University of Belfast]].\n\nFrom 1970 to 1973, years in which the Stormont institution came under its greatest strain and eventually crumbled, Brookeborough made only occasional forays into political life.<ref name=\"The Times, 20 August 1973\"/>  In 1972 he appeared next to [[William Craig (Northern Ireland politician)|Bill Craig]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]] on the balcony of [[Parliament Buildings (Northern Ireland)|Parliament Buildings]] at [[Stormont Estate|Stormont]], a diminutive figure beside the leader of the [[Ulster Vanguard]] who was rallying right-wing Unionists against the Government of Northern Ireland. He opposed the [[Westminster]] [[white paper]] on the future of Northern Ireland and caused some embarrassment to his son, Captain [[John Brooke, 2nd Viscount Brookeborough|John Brooke]], the UUP Chief Whip and an ally of [[Brian Faulkner]], by speaking against the [[Faulkner ministry]]'s proposals.<ref name=\"The Times, 20 August 1973\"/>\n\nLord Brookeborough died at his home, Colebrooke Park, on the Colebrooke Estate, on 18 August 1973.  His remains were cremated at [[Roselawn Cemetery]], East Belfast, three days later, and, in accordance with his wishes, his ashes were scattered on the [[demesne]] surrounding his beloved Colebrooke Park.  In its obituary, ''[[The Times]]'' indirectly blamed him for the continuing Troubles: ''\u201cBrookeborough was a man of courage, conviction and great charm.  But his political sense was seriously found wanting by the intransigence with which he excluded the Roman Catholic minority from responsibility and participation.\u201d'' The obituary continued remarking that Brookeborough was ''\u201c[a] staunch representative of the [[Anglo-Irish]] aristocracy and an unyielding believer in the [[Protestant Ascendancy]]...The sectarian strife now tearing at the fabric of Northern Ireland's society is in part attributable to the immobility imposed in his long period of political leadership.\u201d''<ref name=\"The Times, 20 August 1973\"/>\n\nBrookeborough\u2019s estate<ref>probate, 5 December 1975, CGPLA NIre. \u2022 \u00a342,793 in [[England and Wales]]: probate, 7 November 1973, CGPLA Eng. & Wales</ref> was valued at [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]406,591.83.<ref name=\"The Times, 20 August 1973\"/>\n<ref>[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]</ref> His only surviving son, [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Captain]] [[The Right Honourable]] John W. Brooke, [[Privy Council of Northern Ireland]], MP, succeeded to the [[viscountcy]].<ref name=\"The Times, 20 August 1973\"/>\n\n==Personal life and family==\nBrooke married, firstly, [[Cynthia Brooke, Viscountess Brookeborough|Cynthia Mary Surgison]] (1897\u20131970), second daughter and co-heir of Captain Charles Warden Surgison, of Cuckfield Park, [[Sussex]]. They were married on 3 June 1919 at [[St George's, Hanover Square]]. Their families were already close owing to Surgison's sister's being married to Brookeborough's cousin.<ref name=\"thepeerage.com\"/>  Following their marriage the Brookes went to live at Colebrooke Park. They had three sons, two of whom were killed in action during the [[Second World War]].<ref name=\"The Times, 20 August 1973\">The Times, 20 August 1973</ref>\n\nBrooke was a member of the Hanover Loyal Orange Lodge 1639, which served the Brookeborough estate. Involvement with the [[Orange Order]] was a longstanding family tradition.<ref>Beyond the Banners:The Story of the Orange Order, 92</ref>\n\nLady Brookeborough died in 1970 and the following year, aged 83, Lord Brookeborough married Sarah Eileen Bell Calvert, daughter of Henry Healey, of [[Belfast]], and widow of Cecil Armstrong Calvert, [[FRCS]], director of [[neurosurgery]] at the [[Royal Victoria Hospital, Belfast]]. Sarah Eileen, Viscountess Brookeborough, died in 1989.<ref>{{cite web |last=Lundy |first=Darryl |url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p18107.htm |title= thepeerage.com |publisher= The Peerage}}{{Unreliable source?|failed=y |date=September 2012}}<!--Lundy is not a reliable source so cite Lundy's reliable source See [[WP:SAYWHEREYOUREADIT]]--></ref>\n\nIn his private life, Brookeborough enjoyed farming, and he won many awards for it. He also liked shooting, fishing, and golf.<ref name=\"The Times, 20 August 1973\"/>\n\n===Children===\nBy his first wife, Brookeborough had the following children:\n* [[Lieutenant (British Army and Royal Marines)|Lieutenant]] Basil Julian David Brooke (18 April 1920 \u2013 March 1943 \u2013 [[killed in action]])\n* [[John Warden Brooke, 2nd Viscount Brookeborough]] (9 November 1922 \u2013 5 March 1987)\n* Lieutenant Henry Alan Brooke (29 October 1923 \u2013 April 1945 \u2013 killed in action)\n\n==Awards and decorations==\nHe was awarded the [[Military Cross]]<ref name=\"LG 2 June 1916 (1)\">{{London Gazette |issue=29608 |date=2 June 1916 |pages=5570\u20135571  |supp=y }}</ref> for \"Distinguished Service in the Field\" on 3 June 1916.<ref name=\"LG 2 June 1916 (2)\">{{London Gazette |issue=29608 |date=2 June 1916 |page=5563 |supp=y }}</ref> He was awarded the [[Croix de Guerre]] in 1918.<ref name=\"LG 8 October 1918\">{{London Gazette |issue=30945 |date=8 October 1918 |pages=3213\u201311944 }}</ref>\n\nHaving been appointed [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] in 1921, Brooke was, on 1 July 1952, raised to the [[House of Lords]] as '''Viscount Brookeborough''', ''of Colebrooke, [[County Fermanagh]]''.  He was appointed a [[Knight of the Garter]] in 1965. He held the office of ''Vice-Admiral of Ulster'' between 1961 and 1973.  He held the office of [[Lord Lieutenant of County Fermanagh]] and was [[Custos Rotulorum]] of County Fermanagh between 1963 and 1969.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! scolpe=\"col\" | Ribbon\n! scolpe=\"col\" | Award\n! scolpe=\"col\" | Date\n! scolpe=\"col\" | Post-nominal letters\n|-\n| [[File:Order of the British Empire (Military) Ribbon.png|55px]] || [[Order of the British Empire]] || 1921 || CBE\n|-\n| [[File:Military cross BAR.svg|55px]] || [[Military Cross]] || 1916 || MC\n|-\n| [[File:Order of the Garter UK ribbon.png|55px]] || [[Order of the Garter]] || 1965 || KG\n|-\n| [[File:Croix de Guerre 1914-1918 ribbon.svg|55px]] || [[Croix de guerre 1914\u20131918 (France)|Croix de Guerre]] || 1918 || \n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Northern Ireland Members of the House of Lords]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Brian Barton, ''Brookeborough: the making of a Prime Minister'', The Institute of Irish Studies, Queen's University, Belfast, 1988.\n\n==External links==\n*{{Hansard-contribs | mr-basil-brooke | the Viscount Brookeborough }}\n*{{Cite web|url=http://www.thepeerage.com|title=The Peerage}}\n* {{PM20|FID=pe/002547}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-off}}\n{{Succession box|title=[[Minister of Finance (Northern Ireland)|Assistant Parliamentary Secretary to the Ministry of Finance]]| before = [[Sir Henry Mulholland, 1st Baronet|Henry Mulholland]] | after = [[Wilson Hungerford|Sir Wilson Hungerford]] |years = 1929\u20131933}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Edward Mervyn Archdale]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Minister of Agriculture (Northern Ireland)|Minister of Agriculture]]|years=1933\u20131941}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Daniel Dixon, 2nd Baron Glentoran|Lord Glentoran]]}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[John Milne Barbour]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Minister of Commerce (Northern Ireland)|Minister of Commerce]]|years=1941\u20131943}}\n{{S-aft|after=Himself|as=Minister of Commerce and Production}}\n{{S-bef|before=Himself|as=Minister of Commerce}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Minister of Commerce and Production (Northern Ireland)|Minister of Commerce and Production]]|years=1943\u20131945}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Roland Thomas Nugent]]}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[John Miller Andrews]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of Northern Ireland]]|years=1943\u20131963}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Terence O'Neill]]}}\n{{S-par|ni}}\n{{S-new|constituency}}\n{{S-ttl|title=Member of Parliament for [[Lisnaskea (Northern Ireland Parliament constituency)|Lisnaskea]]|years=1929\u20131968}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[John Brooke, 2nd Viscount Brookeborough|John Brooke]]}}\n{{S-ppo}}\n{{Succession box| title=[[Ulster Unionist Chief Whip|Unionist Assistant Whip]] | before=[[Sir Henry Mulholland, 1st Baronet|Henry Mulholland]]| after=[[Wilson Hungerford|Sir Wilson Hungerford]]| years=1929\u20131933}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[John Miller Andrews]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Ulster Unionist Party|Leader of the Unionist Party]]|years=1946\u20131963}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Terence O'Neill]]}}\n{{S-hon}}\n{{S-bef| before=[[John Cole, 5th Earl of Enniskillen|The Earl of Enniskillen]]}}\n{{S-ttl| title=[[Lord Lieutenant of Fermanagh]] | years=1963\u20131969}}\n{{s-vac | next=[[Thomas Patrick David Scott]]}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Cahir Healy]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Father of the House]]|years=1965\u20131968}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Norman Stronge|Sir Norman Stronge]]}}\n{{S-reg|uk-bt}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Sir Arthur Douglas Brooke, 4th Baronet|Arthur Brooke]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Viscount Brookeborough|Brooke Baronets]]| years=1907\u20131973}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[John Brooke, 2nd Viscount Brookeborough|John Brooke]]}}\n{{S-reg|uk}}\n{{S-new|creation}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Viscount Brookeborough]]|years=1952\u20131973}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[John Brooke, 2nd Viscount Brookeborough|John Brooke]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Northern Ireland heads of government}}\n{{UUP Leaders}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brookeborough, Sir Basil Brooke, 1st Viscount}}\n[[Category:1888 births]]\n[[Category:1973 deaths]]\n[[Category:10th Royal Hussars officers]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Irish people]]\n[[Category:Baronets in the Baronetage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Graduates of the Royal Military College, Sandhurst]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Order of St John]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Garter]]\n[[Category:Lord-Lieutenants of Fermanagh]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Ulster Unionist Party|Brooke, Basil]]\n[[Category:Ulster Unionist Party members of the House of Commons of Northern Ireland|Brooke, Basil]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Commons of Northern Ireland 1929\u20131933|Brooke, Basil]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Commons of Northern Ireland 1933\u20131938|Brooke, Basil]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Commons of Northern Ireland 1938\u20131945|Brooke, Basil]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Commons of Northern Ireland 1945\u20131949|Brooke, Basil]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Commons of Northern Ireland 1949\u20131953|Brooke, Basil]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Commons of Northern Ireland 1953\u20131958|Brooke, Basil]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Commons of Northern Ireland 1958\u20131962|Brooke, Basil]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Commons of Northern Ireland 1962\u20131965|Brooke, Basil]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Commons of Northern Ireland 1965\u20131969|Brooke, Basil]]\n[[Category:Members of the Senate of Northern Ireland 1921\u20131925|Brooke, Basil]]\n[[Category:Northern Ireland Cabinet ministers (Parliament of Northern Ireland)]]\n[[Category:Northern Ireland junior government ministers (Parliament of Northern Ireland)]]\n[[Category:People educated at Winchester College]]\n[[Category:People from Lisnaskea]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Croix de Guerre 1914\u20131918 (France)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Military Cross]]\n[[Category:Royal Fusiliers officers]]\n[[Category:Ulster Special Constabulary officers]]\n[[Category:Viscounts in the Peerage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Commons of Northern Ireland for County Fermanagh constituencies]]\n[[Category:Politicians from County Fermanagh]]\n[[Category:Ulster Unionist Party members of the Senate of Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Ulster Unionist Party hereditary peers]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLater life and death:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basil_Brooke,_1st_Viscount_Brookeborough"}
{"title_page": "Alastair Boyd, 7th Baron Kilmarnock", "text_new": "'''Alastair Ivor Gilbert Boyd, 7th Baron Kilmarnock''' (11 May 1927 \u2013 19 March 2009) was a Scottish writer, Hispanophile, and [[Clan chief|Chief]] of the [[Clan Boyd]].\n\n==Early life==\nBoyd was born into an aristocratic British family, and served as a pageboy at the [[coronation of King George VI and Queen Elizabeth]]. He was educated at [[Bradfield College]] and [[King's College, Cambridge]] and was commissioned into the [[Irish Guards]] in 1946. He served with them until 1948, including a spell in [[Mandatory Palestine|Palestine]].\n\n==Personal life==\nBoyd married Diana Mary Gibson in 1954 but the marriage was dissolved in 1970.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/5024450/Lord-Kilmarnock.html Obituary], ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', 20 March 2009</ref> Gibson died in 1975. He married for a second time, in 1977. His new wife, Hilary Bardwell (\"Hilly\"), had been married twice before: first to [[Kingsley Amis]] (with whom she had three children: Philip Amis, the novelist [[Martin Amis]], and [[Sally Amis]]), and later to [[D. R. Shackleton Bailey]]. Boyd and Bardwell had one son, [[James Charles Edward Boyd]], known as \"Jaime,\" who was born in 1972. After the end of Kingsley Amis's second marriage, he came to live with Lord Kilmarnock and his ex-wife Hilly.\n\nBoyd lived for much of his life at [[Ronda]] in [[Andalusia]], first with Diana, and later with Hilly and their son James, where he variously ran a tapas bar and a language school.\n\nAs Boyd's only son was born before his parents' marriage, the title of Baron Kilmarnock was inherited by Boyd's younger brother, Robin Jordan Boyd (b. 1941), who succeeded to the peerage in 2009. He has two sons, Simon John Boyd, born 1978, and Mark Julian Boyd, born 1981. The heir apparent is the elder of his two sons, Simon John Boyd, who has a son, Lucian Michael Boyd (born 2007).\n\n==Political career==\nAfter inheriting his father's title in 1975, he took his seat in the House of Lords, eventually joining the [[Social Democratic Party (UK)|Social Democratic Party]]. He served as the party's [[chief whip]] in the Lords from 1983 to 1986.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/lord-kilmarnock-writer-and-politician-who-also-helped-care-for-kingsley-amis-in-the-novelists-later-years-1655300.html |title=Lord Kilmarnock: Writer and politician who also helped care for Kingsley Amis in the novelist's later years |date=27 March 2009 |work=The Independent}}</ref> He was the deputy leader of the SDP Peers from 1986\u201387, and served as the chairman of the All-Party Parliamentary Group on Aids from 1987\u201396.\n\n==Writing==\nHis publications include ''Sabbatical Year'' (1958); ''The Road from Ronda'' (1969); ''The Companion Guide to Madrid and Central Spain'' (1974); ''The Essence of Catalonia'' (1988); ''The Sierras of the South'' (1992); ''The Social Market and the State'' (1999); and ''Rosemary: A Memoir'' (2005).\n\nHis essay, The Quest (2006),<ref>{{cite web |title=The Quest - Alastair Boyd |url=http://www.milesrichmond.co.uk/writing/the-quest-alastair-boyd |accessdate=20 May 2019 |date=2006}}</ref> on the paintings of his friend [[Miles Richmond]] (1922\u20132008), appeared in catalogues that accompanied exhibitions by Richmond at the Convento de Santo Domingo, Ronda (2006) and the Galeria Italcable, [[M\u00e1laga]] (2008).\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/obituaries/article5962244.ece ''The Times'' obituary]\n* {{Rayment|date=February 2012}}\n* Debrett's Peerage\n\n==External links==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-alastair-boyd | Lord Kilmarnock }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090925094921/http://www.laserrania.org/?tag=alastair-boyd laserrania.org Lord Kilmarnock]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kilmarnock, Alastair Boyd, 7th Baron}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:2009 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Barons in the Peerage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Irish Guards officers]]\n[[Category:Scottish clan chiefs]]\n[[Category:People educated at Bradfield College]]\n[[Category:Social Democratic Party (UK) hereditary peers]]\n", "text_old": "'''Alastair Ivor Gilbert Boyd, 7th Baron Kilmarnock''' (11 May 1927 \u2013 19 March 2009) was a Scottish writer, Hispanophile, and [[Clan chief|Chief]] of the [[Clan Boyd]].\n\n==Early life==\nBoyd was born into an aristocratic British family, and served as a pageboy at the [[coronation of King George VI and Queen Elizabeth]]. He was educated at [[Bradfield College]] and [[King's College, Cambridge]] and was commissioned into the [[Irish Guards]] in 1946. He served with them until 1948, including a spell in [[Mandatory Palestine|Palestine]].\n\n==Personal life==\nBoyd married Diana Mary Gibson in 1954 but the marriage was dissolved in 1970.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/5024450/Lord-Kilmarnock.html Obituary], ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', 20 March 2009</ref> Gibson died in 1975. He married for a second time, in 1977. His new wife, Hilary Bardwell (\"Hilly\"), had been married twice before: first to [[Kingsley Amis]] (with whom she had three children: Philip Amis, the novelist [[Martin Amis]], and [[Sally Amis]]), and later to [[D. R. Shackleton Bailey]]. Boyd and Bardwell had one son, [[James Charles Edward Boyd]], known as \"Jaime,\" who was born in 1972. After the end of Kingsley Amis's second marriage, he came to live with Lord Kilmarnock and his ex-wife Hilly.\n\nBoyd lived for much of his life at [[Ronda]] in [[Andalusia]], first with Diana, and later with Hilly and their son James, where he variously ran a tapas bar and a language school.\n\nAs Boyd's only son was born before his parents' marriage, the title of Baron Kilmarnock was inherited by Boyd's younger brother, Robin Jordan Boyd (b. 1941), who succeeded to the peerage in 2009. He has two sons, Simon John Boyd, born 1978, and Mark Julian Boyd, born 1981. The heir apparent is the elder of his two sons, Simon John Boyd, who has a son, Lucian Michael Boyd (born 2007).\n\n==Political career==\nAfter inheriting his father's title in 1975, he took his seat in the House of Lords, eventually joining the [[Social Democratic Party (UK)|Social Democratic Party]]. He served as the party's [[chief whip]] in the Lords from 1983 to 1986.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/lord-kilmarnock-writer-and-politician-who-also-helped-care-for-kingsley-amis-in-the-novelists-later-years-1655300.html |title=Lord Kilmarnock: Writer and politician who also helped care for Kingsley Amis in the novelist's later years |date=27 March 2009 |work=The Independent}}</ref> He was the deputy leader of the SDP Peers from 1986\u201387, and served as the chairman of the All-Party Parliamentary Group on Aids from 1987-96.\n\n==Writing==\nHis publications include ''Sabbatical Year'' (1958); ''The Road from Ronda'' (1969); ''The Companion Guide to Madrid and Central Spain'' (1974); ''The Essence of Catalonia'' (1988); ''The Sierras of the South'' (1992); ''The Social Market and the State'' (1999); and ''Rosemary: A Memoir'' (2005).\n\nHis essay, The Quest (2006),<ref>{{cite web |title=The Quest - Alastair Boyd |url=http://www.milesrichmond.co.uk/writing/the-quest-alastair-boyd |accessdate=20 May 2019 |date=2006}}</ref> on the paintings of his friend [[Miles Richmond]] (1922\u20132008), appeared in catalogues that accompanied exhibitions by Richmond at the Convento de Santo Domingo, Ronda (2006) and the Galeria Italcable, [[M\u00e1laga]] (2008).\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/obituaries/article5962244.ece ''The Times'' obituary]\n* {{Rayment|date=February 2012}}\n* Debrett's Peerage\n\n==External links==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-alastair-boyd | Lord Kilmarnock }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090925094921/http://www.laserrania.org/?tag=alastair-boyd laserrania.org Lord Kilmarnock]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kilmarnock, Alastair Boyd, 7th Baron}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:2009 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Barons in the Peerage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Irish Guards officers]]\n[[Category:Scottish clan chiefs]]\n[[Category:People educated at Bradfield College]]\n[[Category:Social Democratic Party (UK) hereditary peers]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePolitical career:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1987-96 \u2192 1987\u201396", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alastair_Boyd,_7th_Baron_Kilmarnock"}
{"title_page": "Ignatius O'Brien, 1st Baron Shandon", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Ignatius O'Brien, 1st Baron Shandon\n| honorific-suffix = [[Privy Council of Ireland|PC]], [[Queen's Counsel|KC]]\n| image        = \n| alt          = \n| caption      = \n| office       = [[Solicitor General for Ireland]]\n| term_start   = 1911\n| term_end     = 1912\n| predecessor  = [[Charles Andrew O'Connor]]\n| successor    = [[Thomas Molony]]\n| office2      = [[Attorney General for Ireland]]\n| term_start2  = 1912\n| term_end2    = 1913\n| predecessor2 = Charles Andrew O'Connor\n| successor2   = Thomas Molony\n| office3      = [[Lord Chancellor of Ireland]]\n| term_start3  = 1913\n| term_end3    = 1918\n| predecessor3 = [[Redmond John Barry]]\n| successor3   = [[James Campbell, 1st Baron Glenavy|Sir James Campbell]]\n| birth_date   = {{birth date|df=y|1857|7|31}}\n| birth_place  = [[Cork (city)|Cork]], Ireland\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|df=y|1930|9|10|1857|7|31}}\n| death_place  = [[London]], England\n}}\n'''Ignatius John O'Brien, 1st Baron Shandon''', [[Privy Council of Ireland|PC (Ire)]], [[Queen's Counsel|KC]] (31 July 1857 \u2013 10 September 1930), known as '''Sir Ignatius O'Brien, Bt''', between 1916 and 1918, was an Irish lawyer and politician. He served as [[Lord Chancellor of Ireland]] between 1913 and 1918.\n\n==Early life==\nO'Brien was born in [[Cork (city)|Cork]], the son of Mark Joseph O'Brien and Jane, daughter of William Dunne.<ref name=\"thepeerage.com\">[http://thepeerage.com/p24201.htm thepeerage.com Ignatius John O'Brien, 1st and last Baron Shandon]</ref> He was educated at the [[Vincentian Family|Vincentian]] School there and, at the age of 16, entered the [[Catholic University of Ireland]] in Dublin but left after two years due to family circumstances. He worked as a junior reporter for the ''Saunders Newsletter'', a Dublin Conservative daily newspaper and then for ''[[Freeman's Journal]]'' while studying part-time for the Bar. Called to the [[barrister|Irish Bar]], [[King's Inn]], in 1881, O'Brien was slow to build a practice and continued to support himself through freelance journalism, within three years he had established a small practice on the [[Munster]] circuit.{{citation needed|date=December 2013}}\n\n==Keller Case==\nIn 1887 O'Brien became involved in the case of [[Canon Keller]] which was to establish his legal career and reputation. Keller, who was the parish priest of [[Youghal]], was called to give evidence in the Bankruptcy Court regarding the financial circumstances of some of his Parishioners involved in the \"[[Plan of Campaign]]\" rent strikes. Keller refused to answer questions of the grounds that he had obtained this information in his capacity as a [[confessor]], and that breaching the seal of the confessional contravened [[Catholic]] [[Canon law (Catholic Church)|Canon law]]. As a result, Keller was imprisoned for [[contempt of court]]. O'Brien argued in support of a writ of [[habeas corpus]]. Although unsuccessful in the [[Court of Queen's Bench (Ireland)|Court of Queen's Bench]], his argument prevailed in the [[Irish Court of Appeal]]<ref>''In re Keller'' (1887) 22 L.R.Ir. 158</ref>\n\n==Later legal and political career==\nPropelled by the reputation he won in the Keller case, O'Brien gave up [[Circuit Court (Ireland)|circuit court]] work and concentrated on [[Court of equity|Chancery]] and Bankruptcy matters and became a leading authority on bankruptcy law. He was called to the Inner Bar as an Irish [[Queen's Counsel]] in 1899, became a bencher of [[King's Inns]] in 1907 and was appointed [[Serjeant-at-law (Ireland)|Serjeant at Law]] (then the highest rank for an Irish barrister) in 1910. A supporter of [[Irish Home Rule|Home Rule]] and the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]], O'Brien campaigned on behalf of Liberal candidates but did not stand for parliament himself. In 1911 he was appointed [[Solicitor General for Ireland]] in [[H. H. Asquith]]'s Liberal administration and advanced to [[Attorney General for Ireland|Attorney General]] in 1912, becoming a member of the [[Irish Privy Council]] in the same year. In 1913 the office of [[Lord Chancellor of Ireland]] fell vacant and O'Brien, as Attorney General, was by a longstanding tradition entitled to claim the position. As a judge he was not highly regarded; his pompous manner in Court  led to unkind comparison with a [[American bullfrog|bullfrog]]; more seriously there were frequent complaints that his constant interruptions from the Bench  made it almost impossible for counsel to present their cases properly.\n\n==Lord Chancellor==\nO'Brien's tenure as Lord Chancellor was only secure as long as the Liberal Party remained in government at Westminster. In 1915 the Asquith Government was forced to resign and enter into a wartime coalition with the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]]. British Conservatives sought to replace O'Brien with his [[Irish Unionist|Unionist]] rival [[James Campbell, 1st Baron Glenavy|James Campbell]]. Out of consideration for [[Irish Nationalist]] opinion, O'Brien remained in office and was created a '''Baronet''', of Ardtona in the Parish of Dundrum in the County of Dublin, in 1916.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=29483 |date=22 February 1916 |page=1946 }}</ref> By 1918 however, Conservative and Unionist opinion was ascendant and O'Brien was replaced as Lord Chancellor by Campbell. He received a [[peerage]] as a consolation and became '''Baron Shandon''', of the City of Cork.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=30793 |date=12 July 1918 |page=8199 }}</ref>\n\n==Later life==\nA constitutional nationalist who supported home rule without breaking the imperial link with Great Britain, O'Brien was opposed to the aims and methods of [[Sinn F\u00e9in]]. After an [[Irish Republican Army|IRA]] raid on his home, he left Ireland for good, settling in the [[Isle of Wight]]. Although sceptical of the [[House of Lords]] {{Citation needed|date=February 2008}}, O'Brien found the peers agreeable and became reconciled with its largely hereditary nature. His participation in the House of Lords was usually limited to matters effecting Ireland or issues on which he had legal expertise. He took an active part in the debates and negotiations surrounding the [[Government of Ireland Act 1920]].\n\nBaron Shandon had no issue but wished to pass on his titles to his nephew but, in order to achieve this, he would need a Letter of Remainder, which could be acquired by an application to the Crown Office at the House of Parliament, Westminster. On reflection, in 1929, he realised that this was not an option open to him as Ireland was no longer under the jurisdiction of the United Kingdom and that both the Baronetcy and Barony were outside that jurisdiction. Added to this fact, the 1922 Act, section 5, precluded them from granting such a Letter of Remainder. \n\nThe Baron believed that he could pass his titles by Way of Remainder and this he so did through his Last Will and Testament. The Letters Patent to both Baronetcy and Barony, along with his Lord Chancellor's Purse, the silver casket containing the Freedom of the City of Cork, various other historical letters patent and other artefacts were passed to his nephew, Gerald Horan KC, first Master of the Rolls and then Master of the High Court in Ireland. Previously Gerald Horan had been Permanent Secretary to the Lord Chancellors of Ireland, [[Clerk of the Crown and Hanaper]], Keeper of the Seal and Captain of the Guard of the Purse \n\nBaron Shandon died in London 10 Sept. 1930, Probate Granted London 23 Oct.1930 \n\nGerald Horan KC held the position of Master of the High Court in Ireland up until a few days before his death from ill health a his residence, St. Peter's, Ailesbury Road, Dublin 4. He was a barrister who became, Clerk of the Crown and Hanaper, Permanent Secretary to the Lord Chancellors of Ireland and, as such, was very much involved in the transition stages of Ireland becoming a separate identity from the UK. \n\nHe was actively involved in reduction of the Unionist demand for ten counties down to six counties for the formation of Northern Ireland. This was only achieved by the Unionist's grouping together every single person of any belief, other than Catholic, or non-belief, to create a majority. A throw away remark at that time said \u2018it needed their cattle, sheep, cats and dogs included to achieve the required majority\u2019.\n\nAfter the establishment of Independence, Gerald Horan KC relinquished his positions under the crown to become Master of the Rolls in Ireland and subsequently Master of the High Court in Ireland. An interesting petition was brought before him by his previous \u2018Masters\u2019 and that was for the return of the Seal Making Equipment to the United Kingdom but, at the same time, there was a petition from those that representing the IRA to have possession of the Seal Making Equipment in order that they might publicly destroy same. \n\nThe decision that Gerald Horan KC came to was that the Seal Making Equipment should be entrusted to the safe keeping of the National Museum where both parties could ponder same, and that is where it is up this date. \n\nDuring his time as Master of the High Court in Ireland, Gerald Horan KC wrote a book entitled Circuit Court Practice (Saorstat Eireann) containing statutes, rules, orders and forms relating to the general procedure and jurisdiction of the Circuit Court. This was written to provide a clear understanding of Circuit Court procedure and became required reading for all involved \n- in his Last Will and Testament, dated 27 Jan 1938, he left all 'his property of every nature and kind whatsoever and wheresoever\u2019 to his wife Kathleen. \nGerald Horan KC died in Dublin 10 May 1949, Probate Granted Dublin 3 Sept.1949 (CS/HC/PO/4/102/4954) \n\nKathleen Horan, wife of Gerald Horan KC, of 37 Trees Road, Mount Merrion, Dublin - in her Last Will & Testament dated 21 Aug. 1963 passed The Letters Patent to both Baronetcy and Barony, along with his Lord Chancellor's Purse, the silver casket containing the Freedom of the City of Cork, various other historical letters patent and other artefacts to Desmond Gerald Horan LLb. Sol., only son of Gerald Horan KC. \n\nKathleen Horan died in Dublin 28 Dec.1963, Probate Granted Dublin 11 June 1964 \n\nDesmond Gerald Horan, a barrister and solicitor, worked in Dublin before taking up a position in the Province of Ontario, Canada, as Mining Court Registrar, later to become Mining Commissioner for Ontario, Canada. During that time he compiled and edited a definitive book on the matter entitled \u2018Mining Court and Mining Commissioners Cases' Vol:3 \n\nIn his Last Will & Testament dated 14 May 1975 - he passed The Letters Patent to both Baronetcy and Barony, along with the Lord Chancellor\u2019s Purse, the silver casket containing the Freedom of the City of Cork, various other historical letters patent and other artefacts including Baron Shandon\u2019s Memoirs to his son Niall Patrick Horan \n\nDesmond Gerald Horan died in Dublin 4 June 1975, Probate Granted Ontario, Canada 29 Sept. 1975 (5853/75) \n\nNiall Patrick Horan, after many years of deliberation, petitioned the [[Chief Herald of Ireland]] for a Grant of Arms to reflect the historic nature of the family history, the relationship to and the decision of Baron Shandon. A Grant of Arms was made with a crest described as \u2018Out of a coronet of four pearls all proper a demi lion rampant or\u2019 on 3 July 1998, Vol. Y, folio 31\n\n==Marriage==\nLord Shandon married Anne, daughter of John Talbot Scallan, a prominent Dublin solicitor, in 1886. She died in February 1929. Their marriage was childless so when O'Brien died in London the following year, aged 73, his peerage became extinct.<ref name=\"thepeerage.com\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-legal}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Solicitor General for Ireland]] | before=[[Charles Andrew O'Connor]] | after=[[Thomas Molony|Thomas Francis Molony]] | years=1911&ndash;1912}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Attorney General for Ireland]] | before=[[Charles Andrew O'Connor]] | after=[[Thomas Molony|Thomas Francis Molony]] | years=1912&ndash;1913}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Lord Chancellor of Ireland]] | before=[[Redmond John Barry]] | after=[[James Campbell, 1st Baron Glenavy|Sir James Campbell]] | years=1913&ndash;1918}}\n{{s-reg|uk}}\n{{s-new | creation}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title  = [[Baron Shandon]]\n | years  = 1918\u20131930\n}}\n{{s-non | reason = Extinct }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shandon, Ignatius Obrien, 1st Baron}}\n[[Category:1857 births]]\n[[Category:1930 deaths]]\n[[Category:Barons in the Peerage of the United Kingdom|Shandon, Ignatius John O'Brien, 1st Baron]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) hereditary peers]]\n[[Category:Lord Chancellors of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Politicians from County Cork]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in England]]\n[[Category:Solicitors-General for Ireland]]\n[[Category:Attorneys-General for Ireland]]\n[[Category:Serjeants-at-law (Ireland)]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's Inns]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Ignatius O'Brien, 1st Baron Shandon\n| honorific-suffix = [[Privy Council of Ireland|PC]], [[Queen's Counsel|KC]]\n| image        = \n| alt          = \n| caption      = \n| office       = [[Solicitor General for Ireland]]\n| term_start   = 1911\n| term_end     = 1912\n| predecessor  = [[Charles Andrew O'Connor]]\n| successor    = [[Thomas Molony]]\n| office2      = [[Attorney General for Ireland]]\n| term_start2  = 1912\n| term_end2    = 1913\n| predecessor2 = Charles Andrew O'Connor\n| successor2   = Thomas Molony\n| office3      = [[Lord Chancellor of Ireland]]\n| term_start3  = 1913\n| term_end3    = 1918\n| predecessor3 = [[Redmond John Barry]]\n| successor3   = [[James Campbell, 1st Baron Glenavy|Sir James Campbell]]\n| birth_date   = {{birth date|df=y|1857|7|31}}\n| birth_place  = [[Cork (city)|Cork]], Ireland\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|df=y|1930|9|10|1857|7|31}}\n| death_place  = [[London]], England\n}}\n'''Ignatius John O'Brien, 1st Baron Shandon''', [[Privy Council of Ireland|PC (Ire)]], [[Queen's Counsel|KC]] (31 July 1857 \u2013 10 September 1930), known as '''Sir Ignatius O'Brien, Bt''', between 1916 and 1918, was an Irish lawyer and politician. He served as [[Lord Chancellor of Ireland]] between 1913 and 1918.\n\n==Early life==\nO'Brien was born in [[Cork (city)|Cork]], the son of Mark Joseph O'Brien and Jane, daughter of William Dunne.<ref name=\"thepeerage.com\">[http://thepeerage.com/p24201.htm thepeerage.com Ignatius John O'Brien, 1st and last Baron Shandon]</ref> He was educated at the [[Vincentian Family|Vincentian]] School there and, at the age of 16, entered the [[Catholic University of Ireland]] in Dublin but left after two years due to family circumstances. He worked as a junior reporter for the ''Saunders Newsletter'', a Dublin Conservative daily newspaper and then for ''[[Freeman's Journal]]'' while studying part-time for the Bar. Called to the [[barrister|Irish Bar]], [[King's Inn]], in 1881, O'Brien was slow to build a practice and continued to support himself through freelance journalism, within three years he had established a small practice on the [[Munster]] circuit.{{citation needed|date=December 2013}}\n\n==Keller Case==\nIn 1887 O'Brien became involved in the case of [[Canon Keller]] which was to establish his legal career and reputation. Keller, who was the parish priest of [[Youghal]], was called to give evidence in the Bankruptcy Court regarding the financial circumstances of some of his Parishioners involved in the \"[[Plan of Campaign]]\" rent strikes. Keller refused to answer questions of the grounds that he had obtained this information in his capacity as a [[confessor]], and that breaching the seal of the confessional contravened [[Catholic]] [[Canon law (Catholic Church)|Canon law]]. As a result, Keller was imprisoned for [[contempt of court]]. O'Brien argued in support of a writ of [[habeas corpus]]. Although unsuccessful in the [[Court of Queen's Bench (Ireland)|Court of Queen's Bench]], his argument prevailed in the [[Irish Court of Appeal]]<ref>''In re Keller'' (1887) 22 L.R.Ir. 158</ref>\n\n==Later legal and political career==\nPropelled by the reputation he won in the Keller case, O'Brien gave up [[Circuit Court (Ireland)|circuit court]] work and concentrated on [[Court of equity|Chancery]] and Bankruptcy matters and became a leading authority on bankruptcy law. He was called to the Inner Bar as an Irish [[Queen's Counsel]] in 1899, became a bencher of [[King's Inns]] in 1907 and was appointed [[Serjeant-at-law (Ireland)|Serjeant at Law]] (then the highest rank for an Irish barrister) in 1910. A supporter of [[Irish Home Rule|Home Rule]] and the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]], O'Brien campaigned on behalf of Liberal candidates but did not stand for parliament himself. In 1911 he was appointed [[Solicitor General for Ireland]] in [[H. H. Asquith]]'s Liberal administration and advanced to [[Attorney General for Ireland|Attorney General]] in 1912, becoming a member of the [[Irish Privy Council]] in the same year. In 1913 the office of [[Lord Chancellor of Ireland]] fell vacant and O'Brien, as Attorney General, was by a longstanding tradition entitled to claim the position. As a judge he was not highly regarded; his pompous manner in Court  led to unkind comparison with a [[American bullfrog|bullfrog]]; more seriously there were frequent complaints that his constant interruptions from the Bench  made it almost impossible for counsel to present their cases properly.\n\n==Lord Chancellor==\nO'Brien's tenure as Lord Chancellor was only secure as long as the Liberal Party remained in government at Westminster. In 1915 the Asquith Government was forced to resign and enter into a wartime coalition with the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]]. British Conservatives sought to replace O'Brien with his [[Irish Unionist|Unionist]] rival [[James Campbell, 1st Baron Glenavy|James Campbell]]. Out of consideration for [[Irish Nationalist]] opinion, O'Brien remained in office and was created a '''Baronet''', of Ardtona in the Parish of Dundrum in the County of Dublin, in 1916.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=29483 |date=22 February 1916 |page=1946 }}</ref> By 1918 however, Conservative and Unionist opinion was ascendant and O'Brien was replaced as Lord Chancellor by Campbell. He received a [[peerage]] as a consolation and became '''Baron Shandon''', of the City of Cork.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=30793 |date=12 July 1918 |page=8199 }}</ref>\n\n==Later life==\nA constitutional nationalist who supported home rule without breaking the imperial link with Great Britain, O'Brien was opposed to the aims and methods of [[Sinn F\u00e9in]]. After an [[Irish Republican Army|IRA]] raid on his home, he left Ireland for good, settling in the [[Isle of Wight]]. Although sceptical of the [[House of Lords]] {{Citation needed|date=February 2008}}, O'Brien found the peers agreeable and became reconciled with its largely hereditary nature. His participation in the House of Lords was usually limited to matters effecting Ireland or issues on which he had legal expertise. He took an active part in the debates and negotiations surrounding the [[Government of Ireland Act 1920]].\n\nBaron Shandon had no issue but wished to pass on his titles to his nephew but, in order to achieve this, he would need a Letter of Remainder, which could be acquired by an application to the Crown Office at the House of Parliament, Westminster. On reflection, in 1929, he realised that this was not an option open to him as Ireland was no longer under the jurisdiction of the United Kingdom and that both the Baronetcy and Barony were outside that jurisdiction. Added to this fact, the 1922 Act, section 5, precluded them from granting such a Letter of Remainder. \n\nThe Baron believed that he could pass his titles by Way of Remainder and this he so did through his Last Will and Testament. The Letters Patent to both Baronetcy and Barony, along with his Lord Chancellor\u2019s Purse, the silver casket containing the Freedom of the City of Cork, various other historical letters patent and other artefacts were passed to his nephew, Gerald Horan KC, first Master of the Rolls and then Master of the High Court in Ireland. Previously Gerald Horan had been Permanent Secretary to the Lord Chancellors of Ireland, [[Clerk of the Crown and Hanaper]], Keeper of the Seal and Captain of the Guard of the Purse \n\nBaron Shandon died in London 10 Sept. 1930, Probate Granted London 23 Oct.1930 \n\nGerald Horan KC held the position of Master of the High Court in Ireland up until a few days before his death from ill health a his residence, St. Peter\u2019s, Ailesbury Road, Dublin 4. He was a barrister who became, Clerk of the Crown and Hanaper, Permanent Secretary to the Lord Chancellors of Ireland and, as such, was very much involved in the transition stages of Ireland becoming a separate identity from the UK. \n\nHe was actively involved in reduction of the Unionist demand for ten counties down to six counties for the formation of Northern Ireland. This was only achieved by the Unionist\u2019s grouping together every single person of any belief, other than Catholic, or non-belief, to create a majority. A throw away remark at that time said \u2018it needed their cattle, sheep, cats and dogs included to achieve the required majority\u2019.\n\nAfter the establishment of Independence, Gerald Horan KC relinquished his positions under the crown to become Master of the Rolls in Ireland and subsequently Master of the High Court in Ireland. An interesting petition was brought before him by his previous \u2018Masters\u2019 and that was for the return of the Seal Making Equipment to the United Kingdom but, at the same time, there was a petition from those that representing the IRA to have possession of the Seal Making Equipment in order that they might publicly destroy same. \n\nThe decision that Gerald Horan KC came to was that the Seal Making Equipment should be entrusted to the safe keeping of the National Museum where both parties could ponder same, and that is where it is up this date. \n\nDuring his time as Master of the High Court in Ireland, Gerald Horan KC wrote a book entitled Circuit Court Practice (Saorstat Eireann) containing statutes, rules, orders and forms relating to the general procedure and jurisdiction of the Circuit Court. This was written to provide a clear understanding of Circuit Court procedure and became required reading for all involved \n- in his Last Will and Testament, dated 27 Jan 1938, he left all 'his property of every nature and kind whatsoever and wheresoever\u2019 to his wife Kathleen. \nGerald Horan KC died in Dublin 10 May 1949, Probate Granted Dublin 3 Sept.1949 (CS/HC/PO/4/102/4954) \n\nKathleen Horan, wife of Gerald Horan KC, of 37 Trees Road, Mount Merrion, Dublin - in her Last Will & Testament dated 21 Aug. 1963 passed The Letters Patent to both Baronetcy and Barony, along with his Lord Chancellor\u2019s Purse, the silver casket containing the Freedom of the City of Cork, various other historical letters patent and other artefacts to Desmond Gerald Horan LLb. Sol., only son of Gerald Horan KC. \n\nKathleen Horan died in Dublin 28 Dec.1963, Probate Granted Dublin 11 June 1964 \n\nDesmond Gerald Horan, a barrister and solicitor, worked in Dublin before taking up a position in the Province of Ontario, Canada, as Mining Court Registrar, later to become Mining Commissioner for Ontario, Canada. During that time he compiled and edited a definitive book on the matter entitled \u2018Mining Court and Mining Commissioners Cases' Vol:3 \n\nIn his Last Will & Testament dated 14 May 1975 - he passed The Letters Patent to both Baronetcy and Barony, along with the Lord Chancellor\u2019s Purse, the silver casket containing the Freedom of the City of Cork, various other historical letters patent and other artefacts including Baron Shandon\u2019s Memoirs to his son Niall Patrick Horan \n\nDesmond Gerald Horan died in Dublin 4 June 1975, Probate Granted Ontario, Canada 29 Sept. 1975 (5853/75) \n\nNiall Patrick Horan, after many years of deliberation, petitioned the [[Chief Herald of Ireland]] for a Grant of Arms to reflect the historic nature of the family history, the relationship to and the decision of Baron Shandon. A Grant of Arms was made with a crest described as \u2018Out of a coronet of four pearls all proper a demi lion rampant or\u2019 on 3 July 1998, Vol. Y, folio 31\n\n==Marriage==\nLord Shandon married Anne, daughter of John Talbot Scallan, a prominent Dublin solicitor, in 1886. She died in February 1929. Their marriage was childless so when O'Brien died in London the following year, aged 73, his peerage became extinct.<ref name=\"thepeerage.com\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-legal}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Solicitor General for Ireland]] | before=[[Charles Andrew O'Connor]] | after=[[Thomas Molony|Thomas Francis Molony]] | years=1911&ndash;1912}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Attorney General for Ireland]] | before=[[Charles Andrew O'Connor]] | after=[[Thomas Molony|Thomas Francis Molony]] | years=1912&ndash;1913}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Lord Chancellor of Ireland]] | before=[[Redmond John Barry]] | after=[[James Campbell, 1st Baron Glenavy|Sir James Campbell]] | years=1913&ndash;1918}}\n{{s-reg|uk}}\n{{s-new | creation}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title  = [[Baron Shandon]]\n | years  = 1918\u20131930\n}}\n{{s-non | reason = Extinct }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shandon, Ignatius Obrien, 1st Baron}}\n[[Category:1857 births]]\n[[Category:1930 deaths]]\n[[Category:Barons in the Peerage of the United Kingdom|Shandon, Ignatius John O'Brien, 1st Baron]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) hereditary peers]]\n[[Category:Lord Chancellors of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Politicians from County Cork]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in England]]\n[[Category:Solicitors-General for Ireland]]\n[[Category:Attorneys-General for Ireland]]\n[[Category:Serjeants-at-law (Ireland)]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's Inns]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLater life:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (4)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ignatius_O%27Brien,_1st_Baron_Shandon"}
{"title_page": "Coastal fortifications of New Zealand", "text_new": "[[File:New Zealand locator map blank.svg|right|thumb|The New Zealand [[List of countries by length of coastline|coastline]]<br />is 15,134 km long.]]\n'''Coastal fortifications''' were constructed in [[New Zealand]] in two main waves: around 1885 as a response to fears of an attack by [[Russia]], and in [[World War II]] due to fears of invasion by the [[Japan]]ese.\n\nThe [[fortifications]] were built from [[United Kingdom|British]] designs adapted to New Zealand conditions. They typically included gun emplacements, pill boxes, fire control or [[observation post]]s, [[camouflage]] strategies, underground [[bunker]]s, sometimes with interconnected tunnels, containing [[Magazine (artillery)|magazines]], supply and plotting rooms and protected engine rooms supplying power to the [[gun turret]]s and [[searchlight]]s. There were also kitchens, [[barracks]], and officer and NCO quarters.<ref name=CoastArtill>{{cite web|url=http://riv.co.nz/rnza/hist/baigent1.htm|title=Coast Artillery Defences in New Zealand|work=riv.co.nz|access-date=20 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091017115627/http://riv.co.nz/rnza/hist/baigent1.htm|archive-date=17 October 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==The \"Russian-scare\" forts of 1885==\nIn the 1870s New Zealand was a young self-governing colony of [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|Britain]]. It had developed no coastal defences of any consequence and was becoming increasingly sensitive to how vulnerable its harbours were to attack by a hostile power or opportunistic [[Commerce raiding|raider]]. In the aftermath of the [[Crimean war]], Tsarist [[Russia]] seemed particularly suspicious.\t\n\n<blockquote>\n(In 1873 an [[Auckland]] editor perpetrated) ...what has been hailed the greatest spoof in the country's history. The Monday, 18 February 1873 edition of the ''Southern Cross'' reported the sudden declaration of war between England and [[Russia]]. As a result, the Russian warship ''Kaskowiski'' \u2013 whose very name should have made sober readers suspicious \u2013 had allegedly entered Auckland Harbour on the previous Saturday night and proceeded to capture a British ship, along with the city's arms and ammunition supply, and hold a number of leading citizens for ransom. The 954-man Russian vessel obviously meant business, with a dozen 30-ton guns as well as a remarkably new advance in warfare, a paralysing and deadly \"water-gas\" that could be injected into enemy ships from a great distance.<ref name=Wolfe>Wolfe, Richard (2007) ''With Honour \u2013 Our Army Our Nation Our History.'' Page 51. {{ISBN|978-0-670-04565-5}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nThe ''Southern Cross'' article created panic and the Government commissioned its first reports on the colony's defences. It was now clearly understood that Britain would protect its territories and vital shipping routes, but the defence of individual ports was the responsibility of each self-governing colony. Then Russia declared [[Russo-Turkish War (1877\u20131878)|war on Turkey]] in 1877 producing another \"scare\". The decision was taken to construct fortifications and [[Early naval vessels of New Zealand#Fears of Russian invasion|purchase naval boats]] which would protect the harbours at [[Auckland]], [[Wellington]], [[Lyttelton, New Zealand|Lyttelton]] and [[Port Chalmers]]. These [[coastal artillery]] fortifications or [[Land battery|land batteries]] were to be based on British designs. Heavy [[artillery]] pieces and ammunition was ordered from Britain. By 1885 work started in earnest on the construction of what eventually became seventeen forts, further encouraged by yet another [[Panjdeh Incident|Russian scare]].<ref name=Wolfe />\n\n===Artillery===\n[[File:North Head South Battery.jpg|right|thumb|[[BL 8 inch Mk I - VII naval gun|BL 8-inch]] Armstrong [[disappearing gun]] at [[North Head, New Zealand|North Head]].]]\nIn 1885 the New Zealand Government bought ten Armstrong [[BL 8 inch Mk I - VII naval gun|BL 8-inch]] and thirteen Armstrong [[BL 6 inch gun Mk V|BL 6-inch]] guns on disappearing carriages. The [[disappearing gun]] was the very latest in military technology in the 1880s. It was \"disappearing\" because as it fired, the recoil pushed the gun back underground where it could be reloaded under cover. The total costs of this artillery plus the costs of installation including land, emplacements, magazines and barracks was about \u00a3160,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://riv.co.nz/rnza/hist/dgun/harbdef1885.htm|title=Harbour Defences 1885|first=CM|last=Rivers|work=riv.co.nz|accessdate=20 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081015063532/http://riv.co.nz/rnza/hist/dgun/harbdef1885.htm|archive-date=15 October 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the \"second Russian scare\" a number of additional RML 7-inch and 64-pr guns were also installed <ref>{{cite web|url=http://riv.co.nz/rnza/hist/dgun/index.htm|title=Disappearing Guns|first=CM|last=Rivers|work=riv.co.nz|access-date=20 September 2016|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807121544/http://riv.co.nz/rnza/hist/dgun/index.htm|archive-date=7 August 2016|df=}}</ref>\n {| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Artillery circa 1890\n! Number\n! Range\n! Notes\n|-\n| Armstrong [[BL 8 inch Mk I - VII naval gun|BL 8-inch Mk VII]] [[disappearing gun]]s\n| 10\n| 4 miles \n| Weighed 13.5 tons and fired a 180-pound shell.\n|-\n| Armstrong [[BL 6 inch gun Mk V|BL 6-inch]] [[disappearing gun]]s\n| 13\n| 3 miles\n| Weighed 5 tons and fired a 100-pound shell.\n|-\n| [[RML 7 inch 7 ton gun]]s \n| 11\n|  \n| Weighed 7 tons.\n|-\n| [[RML 64 pounder 64 cwt gun|RML 64-pr Mk 3]] guns\n| 9\n| 2 miles\n| Weighed 64 [[Hundredweight|cwt]]\n|}\n\n===The forts===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|-\n!Fort\n!Harbour\n!width=\"30\"|Way-<br />point\n!width=\"100\"|Ordnance<br />circa 1890\n!width=\"35\"|Range<br />(miles)\n!width=\"35\"|Dates\n!width=\"370\"|Notes\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| [[North Head, New Zealand|North Head]]\n| Auckland\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|36|49|39|S|174|48|44|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |name=North Head |display=inline}}\n| 1x[[BL 8 inch Mk VII naval gun|BL 8in gun]]<br />RML 7in guns<br />64-pr guns\n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1870\n| At Devonport, divided into three sub-forts:\n* North Battery (to defend Rangitoto Channel) \n* South Battery (with a 7in gun to protect the inner harbour) \n* Fort Cautley (with the 8in gun on the summit).<ref name=NthHeadHR>{{cite web|url=http://www.doc.govt.nz/parks-and-recreation/places-to-visit/auckland/central-and-south-auckland/north-head-historic-reserve/|title=Maungauika/North Head Historic Reserve|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=NthHead>{{cite web|url=http://www.devonport.co.nz/north_head.htm|title=North Head|publisher=|access-date=5 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413075550/http://www.devonport.co.nz/north_head.htm|archive-date=13 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>[http://www.doc.govt.nz/upload/documents/conservation/historic/by-region/north-head-self-guided-walk.pdf North Head self-guided walk]</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| [[Bastion Point]]\n| Auckland\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|36|50|43|S|174|49|29|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline |name=Bastion Point}}\n| 2xBL 6in guns\n| align=\"center\"| \n|1885\u2013\n| In [[Mission Bay, New Zealand|Mission Bay]]. Not completed.\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Fort Resolution\n| Auckland\n| align=\"center\"| \n| 2xBL 6in guns \n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1885\n| In Parnell.\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Fort Takapuna\n| Auckland\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Fort Takapuna |36|48|55|S|174|48|24|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2xBL 6in guns\n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1886\u2013\n| <ref name=9CoastReg>{{cite web|url=http://riv.co.nz/rnza/units/9c/taka.htm|title=9 Coast Regiment at Fort Takapuna|first=CM|last=Rivers|work=riv.co.nz|accessdate=20 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170406045417/http://riv.co.nz/rnza/units/9c/taka.htm|archive-date=6 April 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=FtTakapunaWalk>{{cite web|url=http://www.doc.govt.nz/parks-and-recreation/tracks-and-walks/auckland/central-and-south-auckland/fort-takapuna-historic-walk/|title=Fort Takapuna Historic Walk|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=FtTakapunaHR>{{cite web|url=http://www.doc.govt.nz/parks-and-recreation/places-to-visit/auckland/central-and-south-auckland/fort-takapuna-historic-reserve/|title=Fort Takapuna Historic Reserve|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Fort Takapuna\">[http://www.doc.govt.nz/upload/documents/conservation/historic/by-region/fort-takapuna-hgmp-may-2001.pdf  Fort Takapuna]</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| [[Mount Victoria, Auckland|Fort Victoria]]\n| Auckland\n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1x[[BL 8 inch Mk VII naval gun|BL 8in gun]]\n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1885\n| On Mount Victoria, Devonport. The gun fired only once because of complaints from residents whose windows were broken.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.teara.govt.nz/NewZealandInBrief/GovernmentAndNation/10/ENZ-Resources/Standard/1/en|title=Fortifications at Mt Victoria, Auckland \u2013 Nation and government \u2013 Te Ara Encyclopedia of New Zealand|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080405215632/http://www.teara.govt.nz/NewZealandInBrief/GovernmentAndNation/10/ENZ-Resources/Standard/1/en|archive-date=5 April 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| [[Fort Ballance]]\n| Wellington\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Fort Ballance |41|17|41|S|174|50|02|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2x7\" RML guns<br />1x6\" BLHP gun<br />2 x [[QF 6 pounder Nordenfelt]] guns\n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1885\n| (1885\u20131886) Point Gordon. At Miramar. Wellington's primary military fort until 1911 when Fort Dorset opened.<ref name=FtBallance>{{cite web|url=http://www.capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/pre1930/ballnce1.htm|title=Fort Ballance, Wellington|work=orcon.net.nz|access-date=20 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080124043211/http://www.capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/pre1930/ballnce1.htm|archive-date=24 January 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Fort Gordon\n| Wellington\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Fort Ballance |41|17|41|S|174|50|02|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 1x8\" BLHP gun\n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1895-1924\n| Point Gordon\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| [[Fort Buckley]]\n| Wellington\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Fort Buckley |41|15|38|S|174|47|17|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2x64-pr RML guns\n| align=\"center\"| 2\n| \n| At Kaiwharawhara.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/pre1930/bukley1.htm|title=Fort Buckley|work=orcon.net.nz|access-date=20 September 2016|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041212140642/http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/pre1930/bukley1.htm|archive-date=12 December 2004|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/period/buklyp1.htm|title=Fort Buckley: period photo|work=orcon.net.nz|access-date=20 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010803190650/http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/period/buklyp1.htm|archive-date=3 August 2001|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/36251685@N00/sets/683677|title=Fort Buckley|work=Flickr|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Haswell Battery\n| Wellington\n| align=\"center\"|\n| 1xBL 8in gun\n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1889\n| At Miramar.\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| [[Kau Point Battery]]\n| Wellington\n| align=\"center\"|\n| 1xBL 8in gun\n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1891-1922\n| At Miramar.\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Fort Kelburne\n| Wellington\n| \n| 2xBL 8in guns \n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1885\n| At Ngauranga.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/period/ftkelburne1.htm|title=Fort Kelburne: Period photo|work=orcon.net.nz|access-date=20 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020906094154/http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/period/ftkelburne1.htm|archive-date=6 September 2002|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Battery Point\n| Lyttelton\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Battery Point |43|36|10|S|172|44|25|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2x7in RML guns<br />1x QF 6 pounder Nordenfelt guns\n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1885\n| On the north side of Lyttelton Harbour, 3 miles from mouth.<ref name=BatteryPt>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzrifle.com/ml_battery_point.htm|title=WWII Coastal Defence Fortifications - Battery point|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=BatteryPtFoto>[http://www.nzrifle.com/images/ml_images/ml_bty_point_images/bty_point_%20overveiw02(index).jpg Annotated photo of Battery Point]</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| [[Ripapa Island#Fort Jervois|Fort Jervois]]\n| Lyttelton\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Ripapa Island |43|37|11|S|172|45|15|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2x8in BL guns<br />2x6in BL guns\n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1886\n| On [[Ripapa Island]] on the south side of Lyttelton Harbour (often called 'Ripa') <ref name=FtJervoisRipapa>{{cite web|url=http://www.doc.govt.nz/conservation/historic/by-region/canterbury/christchurch-and-banks-peninsula/fort-jervois-ripapa-island/|title=New Zealand historic heritage: Our work|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref> Fort Jervois is an internationally rare 1880s \u201cRussian Invasion Scare\u201d  structure, which has retained a high level of authenticity of both structure and hardware (6\u201d and 8\u201d disappearing guns). It is one of only five examples of this type of fortification in the world. The Island has been managed by the Department of Conservation since 1990.<ref name=FtJervoisRestore>{{Cite web |url=http://www.doc.govt.nz/upload/documents/about-doc/tenders/carbon-sink-tenders/conservation-projects/fort-jervois-restoration-ripapa-island-lyttelton-harbour.pdf |title=Fort Jervois Restoration |access-date=2007-12-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081016225618/http://doc.govt.nz/upload/documents/about-doc/tenders/carbon-sink-tenders/conservation-projects/fort-jervois-restoration-ripapa-island-lyttelton-harbour.pdf |archive-date=2008-10-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Spur Point Battery\n| Lyttelton\n| align=\"center\"|\n| 1x64-pounder RML gun\n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1885\n| Site of battery, quarried away as part of land reclamation during the 1970s to build Cashin Quay.<ref>{{cite book |last=Glackin |first=Russel |authorlink= |title=In Defence of Our Land: A Tour of New Zealand's Historic Harbour Forts |url= |accessdate= |year=2009 |publisher=Penguin Group |location= |isbn=978-014301186-6 |page=64 }}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| [[Lawyer's Head]] Battery \n| Port Chalmers\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Lawyer's Head Battery |45|54|32|S|170|32|06|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| \n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1885\n| Eastern Ocean Beach, Dunedin South.\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Ocean Beach Battery \n| Port Chalmers\n| align=\"center\"| \n| \n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1886\n| \n|-valign=\"top\"\n| [[Saint Clair, New Zealand|St Clair]] Battery \n| Port Chalmers\n| align=\"center\"| \n| \n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1885\n| On a spur of Forbury Hill above [[Second Beach (New Zealand)|Second Beach]], Dunedin. No remnants remain; the area was cleared and subdivided for residential housing.\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| [[Taiaroa Head|Fort Taiaroa]]\n| Port Chalmers\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Fort Taiaroa |45|46|26|S|170|43|40|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 1xBL 6in gun \n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1885\n| Otago Harbour. This Armstrong Disappearing Gun was installed in May 1889 and was recommissioned during World War II. It is the only one of its kind working and is still in its original gun pit.<ref>[http://www.albatross.org.nz/Fort.htm Fort Taiaroa]</ref><ref>[http://www.army.mil.nz/at-a-glance/news/army-news/365/rtg.htm Raising the Guns]</ref>\n|}\n\n==World War II coastal fortifications==\n[[File:NZ-StonyBatter1.jpg|right|thumb|Tunnel layout for a three gun emplacement system.]] \nThe second main wave of building coastal fortifications occurred during [[World War II]]. This was mainly a response to a perceived threat of invasion by the [[Japan]]ese after the attack on [[Attack on Pearl Harbor|Pearl Harbor]]. From 1942 until 1944, when the threat receded, 42 [[coastal artillery]] fortifications or [[Land battery|land batteries]] were either developed using historical fortifications or were built from scratch. The fortifications were built from [[United Kingdom|British]] designs adapted to New Zealand conditions.  [[Radar]] was installed which allowed long range shooting at night and replaced the traditional fortress system of [[Rangefinder|range finding]].<ref name=CoastArtill />\n\n===Ordnance===\n[[File:NZ-StonyBatter3.jpg|right|thumb|9.2 inch gun emplacement at [[Stony Batter]].]]\nThe fortifications were equipped with both old and new [[Ammunition#Ordnance ammunition|ordnance]], mostly British. Some World War I ordnance was requisitioned from museums and recommissioned.{{Citation needed|date=June 2010}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Ordnance used during World War II\n! Number\n! Range\n! Notes\n|-\n| [[BL 9.2 inch gun Mk IX - X|9.2 inch guns]]\n| 6\n| 18 miles\n| \n|-\n| [[British ordnance terms#BL|BL]]  [http://www.navweaps.com/Weapons/WNBR_6-50_mk22.htm BL 6 inch Mk 24 guns]\n| 3\n| 14 miles\n| \n|-\n| BL 6&nbsp;inch Mk 21 guns\n| 6\n| 13 miles\n| \n|-\n| [[BL 6 inch Gun Mk 7|6 inch Mark 7 guns]]\n| 32\n| 12 miles\n| \n|-\n| [https://web.archive.org/web/20160807121544/http://riv.co.nz/rnza/hist/dgun/index.htm 6in EOC gun]\n| 2\n| 6 miles\n| Elswick Ordnance Company\n|-\n| [[5\"/51 caliber gun]]s<ref name=DiGiulian>DiGiulian, Tony, [http://www.navweaps.com/Weapons/WNUS_5-51_mk7.htm \"United States of America 5\"/51 (12.7 cm) Marks 7, 8, 9, 14 and 15. British 5\"/51 (12.7 cm) BL Marks VI and VII]</ref> (USA naval guns)\n| 6\n| 10 miles\n| 51 calibre MkVII 1912 \n|-\n| [[QF 4.7 inch Gun Mk I - IV|4.7in guns]]\n| 1\n| 6 miles\n| \n|-\n| [[BL 4 inch naval gun Mk VII|4 inch Mark 7 guns]]\n| 11\n| 9 miles\n| \n|-\n| [[M114 155 mm howitzer|155mm guns]]\n| 2\n| 9 miles\n| \n|-\n| [[75 mm gun (US)|75mm guns]]\n| 2\n| \n| \n|-\n| [[British ordnance terms#QF|QF]] [https://web.archive.org/web/20071226221500/http://riv.co.nz/rnza/hist/local/qf12pr.htm 12 pdr guns]\n| 8\n| 8 miles\n| \n|-\n| [[British ordnance terms#QF|QF]] [[Ordnance QF 6 pounder|6 pdr guns]]\n| 12\n|5 miles\n| \n|-\n| [https://web.archive.org/web/20071227143347/http://riv.co.nz/rnza/hist/local/qf40mmaa.htm Bofors 40mm guns]\n| 48\n| 4 miles\n| \n|-\n| [[Searchlight|CASLs]]\n| 48\n| \n| Coastal Artillery Searchlight \n|}\n\n===The fortifications===\nThe fortifications were administered by the [[Royal New Zealand Artillery]], which grouped them into four areas. Each area was under the command of a heavy artillery regiment. Within each regiment the fortifications were grouped into batteries.{{Citation needed|date=June 2010}}\n{| \n|-\n|style=\"background:#ffffdd;\"| <small>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Also used (highlighted below in yellow) were seven of the now historic Russian scare fortifications &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </small>\n|}\n\n====Upper North Island====\nUnder the command of the 9th Heavy (Coast) Regiment.{{Citation needed|date=June 2010}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!width=\"35\"|Battery\n!width=\"70\"|Name\n!width=\"30\"|Way-<br />point\n!width=\"100\"|World War II<br />Ordnance\n!width=\"35\"|Range<br />(miles)\n!width=\"35\"|Dates\n!width=\"335\"|Notes\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 60\n| [[Motutapu Island]]\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|36|45|03|S|174|55|09|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline |name=Motutapu Island}}\n| 3 x 6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;21&nbsp;guns<br /> 2 x CASLs \n| align=\"center\"|13\n| 1936<br />-1945\n| Consisted of a battery, camp, gun emplacement, pill boxes and US naval magazines. Its remains are administered by DOC.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doc.govt.nz/conservation/historic/by-region/auckland/hauraki-gulf-islands/motutapu-island-recreation-reserve/|title=New Zealand historic heritage: Our work|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 61<br />RHQ \n| style=\"background:#ffffdd;\"| [[North Head, New Zealand|North Head]]<br /><small>[Russian scare]</small>\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|36|49|39|S|174|48|44|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |name=North Head |display=inline}}\n| 2 x [[BL 4 inch naval gun Mk VII|4in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7 guns]]<br />2 x 12pdr guns<br />4 x 6pdr H&N<br />6 x CASLs\n| align=\"center\"| 9\n| 1870<br />-1957\n| Part of Auckland's coastal defence system from the [[Panjdeh Incident|Russian scare]] in 1885 to World War I. By World War II, with ships' guns able to fire long distances, the old fort was too close to the city it was meant to defend. New batteries were built at Motutapu, Castor Bay, Whangaparaoa and Waiheke Island and North Head became the centre of administration.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doc.govt.nz/conservation/historic/by-region/auckland/central-and-south-auckland/north-head-historic-reserve/history-of-the-reserve/|title=Maungauika/North Head Historic Reserve|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref> A complex of tunnels, guns, searchlights and other fortifications remain and it is now a historic reserve managed by the Department of Conservation.<ref name=NthHeadHR /><ref name=NthHead />\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 61\n| style=\"background:#ffffdd;\"| [[Bastion Point]]<br /><small>[Russian scare]</small>\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Bastion Point |36|50|43|S|174|49|29|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2 x 12pdr gun<br />Twin 6pdr guns<br />3xCASLs \n| align=\"center\"| 8\n|1885\u2013\n| Located in [[Mission Bay, New Zealand|Mission Bay]]. The fortifications were buried in the 1940s when the [[Michael Joseph Savage]] memorial was built, and effectively forgotten. The underlying tunnels were later rediscovered.\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 61\n| [[Great Barrier Island]]\n| \n| 6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;gun<br />[[BL 4 inch naval gun Mk VII|4in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7 gun]]<br />4 x [[Bofors 40 mm gun|40mm&nbsp;Bofors]] \n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| \n| \n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 61\n| Manukau\n| \n| 1x4.7in gun\n| align=\"center\"| 6\n| 1942\n| Built by American Forces [unknown unit] at the end of Harvey Road, Manukau Heads, approximately 100 m north of lighthouse site, this open fronted fortification had one gun, and an observation post inland. Accommodation was at the end of Harvey Road, with only concrete pads remaining for some buildings. Due to the erosive nature of these compacted sandhills the gun emplacement was undermined and slipped down the cliffs in the early 1980s. According to local residents, the gun was only fired 6 times, cracking the concrete abutments.\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 61\n| [[Motuihe Island]]\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Motuihe Island |36|48|40|S|174|49|29|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2 x [[BL 4 inch naval gun Mk VII|4in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7 guns]] \n| align=\"center\"| 9\n| 1872\u2013\n| During World War II (1941) the Motuihe buildings became HMNZS Tamaki naval base, a training establishment.  Now in the care of the Department of Conservation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doc.govt.nz/conservation/historic/by-region/auckland/hauraki-gulf-islands/hauraki-gulf-defences/|title=New Zealand historic heritage: Our work|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://www.navymuseum.mil.nz/history/time/49-2000/training/tamaki.htm HMNZS ''Tamaki'']</ref><ref>[http://www.navymuseum.mil.nz/history/pers/name-index/l/long-a-g.htm  Long, Instructor Lieutenant A.G.]</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 62\n| style=\"background:#ffffdd;\"| Fort Takapuna<br /><small>[Russian scare]</small>\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Fort Takapuna |36|48|55|S|174|48|24|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2 x [[BL 4 inch naval gun Mk VII|4in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7 guns]]<br /> 2 x CASLs \n| align=\"center\"| 9\n| 1886\u2013\n| Also known as HMNZS Tamaki, and Narrow Neck. In 1963 the RNZN moved its New Entry Training School HMNZS Tamaki from Motuihe Island to the fort. The navy built a new Gunnery School and set up an Officer Training School. Previously officers had been sent overseas for training. Only the Officer and Trade Training schools remain. Has been under the care of the Department of Conservation since 2000.<ref name=9CoastReg /><ref name=FtTakapunaWalk /><ref name=FtTakapunaHR /><ref name=FtTakapunaHR /><ref name=\"Fort Takapuna\"/>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 63\n| [[Castor Bay]]\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Castor Bay |36|45|22|S|174|46|0|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2 x [[BL 6 inch Mk VII naval gun|6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;guns]]<br /> 2 x CASLs \n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| 1942<br />-1944\n| [[File:J F Kennedy bunker.jpg|thumb|80px|right|Bunker at Castor Bay]]\nNotable for its camouflage strategies during World War II.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livingheritage.org.nz/schools/primary/campbellsbay/campbells_war/stories/storyReader$45.html|title=Campbell's Bay Primary School|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref><ref>McCarthy, Christine (2002) Camouflage: Military Upholstery and Interior Disguise. ''Space and Culture'', Vol5, No4, 320\u2013332.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://riv.co.nz/rnza/tales/ngaire1.htm|title=Ngaire's War - 9th Heavy Regiment|first=CM|last=Rivers|work=riv.co.nz|accessdate=20 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170407042201/http://riv.co.nz/rnza/tales/ngaire1.htm|archive-date=7 April 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 64\n| [[Whangaparaoa|Whanga-<br />paraoa]]\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Whangaparaoa |36|36|09|S|174|50|16|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2 x [[BL 6 inch Mk VII naval gun|6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;guns]]<br /> 2 x CASLs \n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| \n| SE tip of peninsula\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 163    \n| [[Whangaparaoa|Whanga-<br />paraoa]]\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Whangaparaoa |36|36|09|S|174|50|17|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2 x [[BL 9.2 inch gun Mk IX - X|9.2in guns]]\n| align=\"center\"| 18\n| \n| SE tip of peninsula\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 164    \n| [[Stony Batter]]<br />\n| align=\"center\"|  {{Coord|name=Stoney Batter |36|45|45|S|175|10|27|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2 x 9.2in guns\n| align=\"center\"| 18\n| 1942\u2013\n| Waiheke Island. Now in the care of the Department of Conservation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doc.govt.nz/conservation/historic/by-region/auckland/hauraki-gulf-islands/stony-batter-historic-reserve-waiheke-island/|title=New Zealand historic heritage: Our work|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.tourismwaiheke.co.nz/stonybatter.htm |title=Stony Batter |access-date=2007-12-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071215104803/http://www.tourismwaiheke.co.nz/stonybatter.htm |archive-date=2007-12-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 68\n| Moturoa Island\n| align=\"center\"|  {{Coord|name=Moturoa Island |35|13|07|S|174|11|21|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 4 x [[BL 6 inch Mk VII naval gun|6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;guns]]<br /> 8 x [[Bofors 40 mm gun|40mm&nbsp;Bofors]]\n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| \n| Bay of Islands\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 68\n| [[Whangaroa]]\n| align=\"center\"|  {{Coord|name=Whangaroa |35|00|40|S|173|45|21|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;gun\n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| \n| South Head of harbour.\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 139\n| [[Bream Head]]<br />\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Bream Head |35|51|01|S|174|31|35|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| [[5\"/51 caliber gun|5in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;gun]]&nbsp;(USA)\n| align=\"center\"| 10\n| 1942<br />-1944\n| Entrance to Whangarei harbour. Remaining structures are the (Colchester) gun shelter, engine room, and observation post. The most significant feature is the spotting mural with compass bearings painted above the slit window in the observation post.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doc.govt.nz/conservation/historic/by-region/northland/whangarei/bream-head/#Bream|title=New Zealand historic heritage: Our work|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.breamheadtrust.org.nz/display.php?id_item=19 |title=Bream Head Gun \u2013 Well worth a visit |access-date=2007-12-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080126094451/http://www.breamheadtrust.org.nz/display.php?id_item=19 |archive-date=2008-01-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|}\n\n====Lower North Island====\nUnder the command of the 10th Heavy (Coast) Regiment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://riv.co.nz/rnza/tales/wright2.htm|title=10 Coast Regiment|first=CM|last=Rivers|work=riv.co.nz|accessdate=20 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170408122642/http://riv.co.nz/rnza/tales/wright2.htm|archive-date=8 April 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!width=\"35\"|Battery\n!width=\"70\"|Name\n!width=\"30\"|Way-<br />point\n!width=\"100\"|World War II<br />Ordnance\n!width=\"35\"|Range<br />(miles)\n!width=\"35\"|Dates\n!width=\"335\"|Notes\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 70    \n| Palmer Head\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Palmer Head |41|20|14|S|174|49|01|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 3x6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;21&nbsp;guns<br />4xCASLs \n| align=\"center\"| 13\n| 1936<br />-1957\n| At the entrance to the Wellington Harbour. The abandoned gun pits were blown up in the late 1960s. The only remains are the underground plotting rooms, which are closed for safety reasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/post1930/palmnd1.htm|title=Palmer Heads fortress, Wellington|work=orcon.net.nz|access-date=20 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081008023236/http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/post1930/palmnd1.htm|archive-date=8 October 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 71<br />RHQ    \n| Fort Dorset\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Fort Dorset |41|19|33|S|174|50|14|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2x6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;guns<br />2x4in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7guns<br />4x12pdr guns<br />7xCASLs\n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| 1908<br />-1991\n| At the inner entrance to Wellington harbour. The fort was demolished in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/other/dorset1.htm|title=Fort Dorset|work=orcon.net.nz|access-date=20 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020305034905/http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/other/dorset1.htm|archive-date=5 March 2002|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/period/dorstp1.htm|title=Photos of guns at Fort Dorset|work=orcon.net.nz|access-date=20 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010803191056/http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/period/dorstp1.htm|archive-date=3 August 2001|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 72    \n| style=\"background:#ffffdd;\"| [[Fort Ballance]]<br /><small>[Russian scare]</small>\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Fort Ballance |41|17|41|S|174|50|02|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2x4in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7guns<br />Twin 6pdr guns<br />2x75mm guns<br />6xCASLs\n| align=\"center\"| 9\n| 1885\u2013<br />1945\n| (1885\u20131886) Point Gordon\nBy Mount Crawford, Karaka Bays, Wellington's primary fort until 1911 when Fort Dorset opened, Fort Ballance was closed in 1945 but remnants remain.<ref name=FtBallance />\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 73    \n| Fort Opau\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Opau |41|13|20|S|174|41|46|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2x6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;guns \n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| 1942<br />-1944\n| On a high headland above Makara, on Wellington's west coast, protecting [[Cook Strait]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/post1930/opau1.htm|title=Fort Opau, Wellington|work=orcon.net.nz|access-date=20 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081008023119/http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/post1930/opau1.htm|archive-date=8 October 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/post1930/opau2.htm|title=Fort Opau: Photos|work=orcon.net.nz|access-date=20 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080124043146/http://www.capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/post1930/opau2.htm|archive-date=24 January 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rickp.net/web%20pages/Makara%20Gun%20Emplacements/index.html |title=Fort Opau: More photos |access-date=2008-01-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080123160201/http://www.rickp.net/web%20pages/Makara%20Gun%20Emplacements/index.html |archive-date=2008-01-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The fort was built in 1941, and comprised two covered 6\" gun emplacements, a battery operations post, and an observation post and a radar post, with a large barracks several hundred metres inland.\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 165    \n| [[Wrights Hill Fortress]]\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Wrights Hill Fortress |41|17|46|S|174|44|21|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2x9.2in guns\n| align=\"center\"| 18\n| 1942<br />1957\n| This British-designed fortress was similar to the 9.2&nbsp;inch fortresses built at Whangaparaoa and Stoney Batter. 2,030 feet (620 metres) of interconnecting tunnels were dug. Two 185&nbsp;hp diesel generators provided power to manoeuvre the guns. Each gun weighed 135 tons and could fire a 380-pound (172&nbsp;kg) shell across Cook Strait or up to Plimmerton. The fortress was used for training purposes up to the mid-1950s. In early 1960 the guns were sold for scrap, ironically, to the Japanese. The Wrights Hill Fortress Restoration Society is restoring the coastal battery to its former state.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whfrs.org.nz/|title=Wrights Hill Fortress: Home Page|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/post1930/wrthil1.htm|title=Wrights Hill Fortress|work=orcon.net.nz|access-date=20 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081008023459/http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/post1930/wrthil1.htm|archive-date=8 October 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 77\n| Bluff Hill\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Bluff Hill |39|28|43|S|176|55|03|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2x6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;guns<br />4x40mm&nbsp;Bofors\n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| \n| At Napier. Also a signal station during World War II,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.napier.govt.nz/napier/parks/memorials/bluff-hill-lookout|title=Bluff Hill Lookout|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref> although never a lighthouse,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newzealandlighthouses.com/napier_bluff.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150202215305/http://www.newzealandlighthouses.com/napier_bluff.htm|title=Napier Bluff|work=newzealandlighthouses.com|archivedate=2 February 2015|accessdate=20 September 2016}}</ref> despite being situated on Lighthouse Road.\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 77\n| [[Titirangi (hill)|Titirangi]] (Kaiti Hill)\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Kaiti Hill |38|42|03|S|178|03|56|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 5in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;gun&nbsp;(USA)\n| align=\"center\"| 10\n| \n| Located at Gisborne.\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 78    \n| [[Moturoa]]\n| \n| 2x155mm guns<br />4x40mm&nbsp;Bofors\n| align=\"center\"| 9\n| \n| At New Plymouth.\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 140\n| Languard Bluff\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Languard Bluff |39|57|30|S|175|01|20|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 5in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;gun&nbsp;(USA) \n| align=\"center\"| 10\n| \n| At Wanganui.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/post1930/wngpil1.htm|title=Wanganui gun emplacements|work=orcon.net.nz|access-date=20 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041212140859/http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/post1930/wngpil1.htm|archive-date=12 December 2004|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/post1930/wngpcd3.htm|title=Photos of Wanganui Coastal Battery|work=orcon.net.nz|access-date=20 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060117203218/http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/post1930/wngpcd3.htm|archive-date=17 January 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|}\n\n====Upper South Island====\nUnder the command of the 11th Heavy (Coast) Regiment.{{Citation needed|date=June 2010}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!width=\"35\"|Battery\n!width=\"70\"|Name\n!width=\"30\"|Way-<br />point\n!width=\"100\"|World War II<br />Ordnance\n!width=\"35\"|Range<br />(miles)\n!width=\"35\"|Dates\n!width=\"335\"|Notes\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 80<br />RHQ    \n| Godley Head\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Godley Head |43|35|13|S|172|48|21|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 3x6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;24&nbsp;guns<br />2xCASLs\n| align=\"center\"| 14\n| 1939<br />-1963\n| At the northern entrance to Lyttelton Harbour, the last NZA to be decommissioned. It last fired a gun in 1959. In its heyday in World War II, it was staffed by over 400 men and women and was a self-contained community. It is ranked in the top ten New Zealand coastal defence heritage sites.<ref name=Godley-Head>{{cite web|title=Godley Head coastal defence battery|url=http://www.doc.govt.nz/conservation/historic/by-region/canterbury/christchurch-and-banks-peninsula/godley-head-coastal-defence-battery/}}</ref>  It is now under the care of the Department of Conservation and the Godley Head Heritage Trust.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://homepages.paradise.net.nz/peterwil/godleyhead/|title=The Godley Head Heritage Trust|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://homepages.paradise.net.nz/peterwil/godleyhead/history/ww2/godleyAndCamp.html |title=Godley Battery and Camp |access-date=2007-12-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080123141203/http://homepages.paradise.net.nz/peterwil/godleyhead/history/ww2/godleyAndCamp.html |archive-date=2008-01-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 81\n|  style=\"background:#ffffdd;\"|Battery Point<br /><small>[Russian scare]</small>\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Battery Point |43|36|10|S|172|44|25|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2x4in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7guns<br />Twin 6pdr guns<br />5xCASLs \n| align=\"center\"| 9\n| 1886\u2013\n| On the northern side of Lyttelton Harbour, 3 miles from mouth.<ref name=BatteryPt /><ref name=BatteryPtFoto />\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 81\n| style=\"background:#ffffdd;\"| [[Ripapa Island#Fort Jervois|Fort Jervois]]<br /><small>[Russian scare]</small>\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Ripapa Island |43|37|11|S|172|45|15|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 6in EOC gun\n| align=\"center\"| 6\n| 1886\n| On [[Ripapa Island]] on the southern side of Lyttelton Harbour.<ref name=FtJervoisRipapa /> It is an internationally rare 1880s \u201cRussian Invasion Scare\u201d military defence structure, which has retained a high level of authenticity of both structure and hardware (6\u201d and 8\u201d disappearing guns). It is one of only five examples of this type of fortification in the world. The island has been managed by the Department of Conservation since 1990.<ref name=FtJervoisRestore />\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| \n| style=\"background:#ffffdd;\"| Magazine Bay<br /><small>[Russian scare]</small>\n| align=\"center\"| \n| ?\n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1886\n| [[Lyttelton, New Zealand|Lyttelton]], in conjunction with nearby torpedo boat base.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lytteltonheritage.co.nz Magazine Bay torpedo Boat museum}}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 84\n| Tory Channel entrance \n| \n| 6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;gun<br />12x40mm&nbsp;Bofors\n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| \n| Queen Charlotte Sound\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 84\n| Maraetai\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Maraetai |41|15|21|S|174|08|01|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;gun \n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| \n| In Tory Channel, Queen Charlotte Sound.\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 84\n| [[Blumine Island]]\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Blumine Island 1 |41|09|30|S|174|14|11|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}; {{Coord|name=Blumine Island 2 |41|09|31|S|174|14|39|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2x6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;guns \n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| 1942<br />-1945\n| Guarding the northern entrance to [[Queen Charlotte Sound (New Zealand)|Queen Charlotte Sound]], the guns are positioned separately on the two northern points of Blumine Island. Associated with each emplacement are a magazine, observation post and accommodation camp.<ref>[http://www.ianbowman.co.nz/stories/storyReader$65#DefenceInstallations Defence Installations, Blumine Island]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sustainableblumine.wikispaces.com/Background|title=SustainableBlumine - Background|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 84\n| Post Office Point\n| \n| 6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;gun\n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| \n| In Pelorus Sound.\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 84\n| [[Maud Island]] \n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Maud Island |41|01|01|S|173|54|21|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;gun\n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| \n| At the entrance to [[Pelorus Sound]]. Under the care of the Department of Conservation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doc.govt.nz/parks-and-recreation/places-to-visit/marlborough/sounds-area/maud-island/|title=Maud Island (Te Hoiere) (Scientific Reserve)|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naturespic.com/NewZealand/image.asp?id=15187|title=Second World War Gun Emplacement on the NE point of Maud Island. Te Hoire, Maud Island, Marlborough Sounds, Marlborough District, Marlborough Region, New Zealand (NZ).|work=naturespic.com|accessdate=20 September 2016}}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 84\n| Port Hills\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Port Hills |41|16|10|S|173|15|59|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;gun\n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| \n| In [[Nelson, New Zealand|Nelson]].\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 85    \n| Smithfield Freezing Works\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Smithfield Freezing Works |44|22|16|S|171|14|41|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2x6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;guns<br />4x40mm&nbsp;Bofors\n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| 1942\u2013<br />1944\n| In [[Timaru]]. The No 2 (Colchester type) gun shelter is in an excellent state of preservation <ref>{{cite web|url=http://nzrifle.com/ml_timaru.htm|title=WWII Coastal Defence Fortifications - Timaru|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 134\n| Westport\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Westport Gun Emplacement |41|43|48|S|171|35|15|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 5in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;gun&nbsp;(USA)<br />4x40mm&nbsp;Bofors\n| align=\"center\"| 10\n| 1942\u2013<br />1944\n| On South Spit. The gun emplacement is no longer there but the battery observation post is visible on Google Earth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzrifle.com/ml_westport.htm|title=WWII Coastal Defence Fortifications -Westport|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 134\n| Cobden\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Cobden |42|26|15|S|171|12|45|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 5in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;gun&nbsp;(USA)<br />4x40mm&nbsp;Bofors\n| align=\"center\"| 10\n| 1942\u2013<br />1944\n| At Greymouth. Establishment: 2 Officers, 1 WO, 3 Sergeants and 26 ORs. [[Grey District Council]] destroyed part of this site, without consultation, in 2007 to make way for a sewer line <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzrifle.com/ml_cobden.htm|title=WWII Coastal Defence Fortifications - Cobden|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 143\n| Wainui\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Wainui |43|49|46|S|172|54|17|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n \n| 2x6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;guns<br />4x40mm&nbsp;Bofors<br />2xCASLs\n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| 1942\u2013<br />1944\n| At [[Akaroa Harbour]] on [[Banks Peninsula]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzrifle.com/ml_akaroa.htm|title=WWII Coastal Defence Fortifications - Akaroa|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref>\n|}\n\n====Lower South Island====\nUnder the command of the 13th Heavy (Coast) Regiment.{{Citation needed|date=June 2010}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!width=\"35\"|Battery\n!width=\"70\"|Name\n!width=\"30\"|Way-<br />point\n!width=\"100\"|World War II<br />Ordnance\n!width=\"35\"|Range<br />(miles)\n!width=\"35\"|Dates\n!width=\"335\"|Notes\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| RHQ\n| Dunedin\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 82\n| style=\"background:#ffffdd;\"| [[Taiaroa Head|Fort Taiaroa]]<br /><small>[Russian scare]</small>\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Taiaroa Heads |45|47|12|S|170|43|39|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 6in EOC gun<br />5xCASLs\n| align=\"center\"| 6\n| \n|[[File:Disappearing Gun Taiaroa Head.jpg|thumb|60px|left|Armstrong disappearing gun at Taiaroa Head]]Close to Taiaroa Head at the northeastern tip of Otago Peninsula. Restored, and open to the public. Includes what is believed to be the only 1889 [[Armstrong Disappearing gun]] remaining in working condition in its original gun pit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.otago-peninsula.co.nz/royalalbatrosscentre.html|title=Otago Peninsula Royal Albatross Centre|first=Herman van|last=Velthoven|work=otago-peninsula.co.nz|accessdate=20 September 2016}}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 82\n| Rerewahine\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Rerewahine |45|47|13|S|170|44|45|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2x6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;guns \n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| \n| Otago Peninsula.\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 82\n| [[Ocean Grove, New Zealand|Tomahawk]]\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Tomahawk |45|54|19|S|170|33|11|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2x6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;guns\n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| \n| Dunedin\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 82\n| [[Harington Point]]\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Harrington Point |-45.7834|170.7245|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2xTwin 6pdr guns<br />2x6pdr H&N\n| \n| \n| Dunedin\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 141    \n| [[Cape Wanbrow]]\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Cape Wanbrow |45|07|13|S|170|58|50|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 5in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;gun&nbsp;(USA)\n| align=\"center\"| 10\n| 1942\u2013\n| Under the care of the [[Oamaru]] Coastal Defence Restoration Group <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzrifle.com/ml_oamaru.htm|title=WWII Coastal Defence Fortifications - Oamaru|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visitoamaru.co.nz/?precinct&ln=cape_wanbrow|title=Home|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 142\n| Bluff\n| \n| 6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;gun \n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| \n| \n|}\n\n==Post war==\nThe advent of air warfare and missiles made these forts redundant and most were decommissioned by the 1950s. Godley Head continued because of compulsory military training and last fired a gun in 1959. The Department of Conservation has the remains of around 30 installations on land it manages.<ref name=Godley-Head />\n\n==Postscript==\nNone of the forts fired a gun in anger, though in October 1939 a Battery Point gun at Lyttleton accidentally sank the fishing boat \"Dolphin\" and killed its skipper.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/today-in-history/9266344/Today-in-History-October-12|accessdate=21 February 2017|title=Today in History: October 12|date=12 October 2013|publisher=Stuff.co.nz}}</ref>\n\nIn 1972 the [[United States]] declassified a contingency plan for invading New Zealand.  This plan consisted of a 120-page intelligence document called ''Naval War Plan for the Attack of Auckland, New Zealand''. The intelligence for the report was gathered during the visit of the [[Great White Fleet]] to Auckland over six days in 1908. The plan advocated [[Manukau Harbour]] as the best invasion point and landing heavy guns on [[Rangitoto Island]] to shell the forts on the [[North Shore City|North Shore]]. The plan was not very realistic and may have been an exercise to keep young officers busy (see [[United States color-coded war plans|United States war plans]]; which allocated the colour Garnet to New Zealand as part of [[War Plan Red]]).<ref>Stevens, David and Reeve, John (2001) [https://books.google.com/books?id=5LremxKXzkMC&pg=PA187&lpg=PA187&dq=%22naval+war+plan+for+the+attack+of+auckland%22&source=web&ots=ojirAVaYnA&sig=ghD3VDDCZFBrIDuuvb0uKWmBRSM#PPA187,M1 ''Southern Trident: Strategy, History and the Rise of Australian Naval Power'', Page 184\u2013188.] Allen & Unwin. {{ISBN|978-1-86508-462-6}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Early naval vessels of New Zealand]]\n* [[Coastal defences of Australia during World War II]]\n* [[Coastal Forces of the Royal New Zealand Navy]]\n* [[Axis naval activity in New Zealand waters]]\n* [[British hardened field defences of World War II]]\n* [[British anti-invasion preparations of World War II]]\n* [[Seacoast Defense (US)]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Cooke, Peter (2002) [https://web.archive.org/web/20030615141423/http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/review/dnzcoke.htm ''Defending New Zealand: Ramparts on the Sea 1840s\u20131950s.''] (Wellington). Two volumes. {{ISBN|0-473-08923-8}}.\n* Corbett, Peter D. (2003). ''A First Class Defended Port: The History of the Coast Defences of Auckland, its Harbour and Approaches.'' {{ISBN|0-478-22452-4}} (Available from Auckland Conservancy, Department of Conservation).\n* Glackin, Russell (2009) ''In defence of our land: a tour of New Zealand's historic harbour forts'', Penguin, {{ISBN|0-14-301186-3}}.\n\n==External links==\n{{GeoGroupTemplate}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081015043526/http://riv.co.nz/rnza/rf/ww2/nz2.htm NZ coastal artillery units of World War II]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091017115627/http://riv.co.nz/rnza/hist/baigent1.htm Coast Artillery Defences]\n* [http://www.doc.govt.nz/upload/692/Coast-Defence-Sites.gif Map of Coastal Defence Sites around Auckland]\n* [http://www.doc.govt.nz/conservation/historic/by-region/auckland/hauraki-gulf-islands/hauraki-gulf-defences/ Hauraki Gulf Defences]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071213052955/http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/ Capital Defence \u2013 Coastal Defence Sites around Wellington]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091027131228/http://www.geocities.com/CollegePark/Den/5417/index.html Wellington's Coastal Defences]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080123222149/http://www.angelfire.com/ne/4WDNZ/fortifications.htm World War II Fortifications in Canterbury and Westland]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080223122600/http://riv.co.nz/rnza/hist/local/index.htm Artillery pieces in New Zealand]\n* [http://www.ozatwar.com/ozatwar/bunkers.htm Bunkers, tunnels, fortifications in Australia during World War II]\n\n[[Category:Forts in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Coastline of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:New Zealand Army]]\n[[Category:Military history of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Military history of New Zealand during World War II]]\n[[Category:World War II sites in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Coastal fortifications]]\n[[Category:19th-century fortifications]]\n[[Category:20th-century fortifications]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:New Zealand locator map blank.svg|right|thumb|The New Zealand [[List of countries by length of coastline|coastline]]<br />is 15,134 km long.]]\n'''Coastal fortifications''' were constructed in [[New Zealand]] in two main waves: around 1885 as a response to fears of an attack by [[Russia]], and in [[World War II]] due to fears of invasion by the [[Japan]]ese.\n\nThe [[fortifications]] were built from [[United Kingdom|British]] designs adapted to New Zealand conditions. They typically included gun emplacements, pill boxes, fire control or [[observation post]]s, [[camouflage]] strategies, underground [[bunker]]s, sometimes with interconnected tunnels, containing [[Magazine (artillery)|magazines]], supply and plotting rooms and protected engine rooms supplying power to the [[gun turret]]s and [[searchlight]]s. There were also kitchens, [[barracks]], and officer and NCO quarters.<ref name=CoastArtill>{{cite web|url=http://riv.co.nz/rnza/hist/baigent1.htm|title=Coast Artillery Defences in New Zealand|work=riv.co.nz|access-date=20 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091017115627/http://riv.co.nz/rnza/hist/baigent1.htm|archive-date=17 October 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==The \"Russian-scare\" forts of 1885==\nIn the 1870s New Zealand was a young self-governing colony of [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|Britain]]. It had developed no coastal defences of any consequence and was becoming increasingly sensitive to how vulnerable its harbours were to attack by a hostile power or opportunistic [[Commerce raiding|raider]]. In the aftermath of the [[Crimean war]], Tsarist [[Russia]] seemed particularly suspicious.\t\n\n<blockquote>\n(In 1873 an [[Auckland]] editor perpetrated) ...what has been hailed the greatest spoof in the country's history. The Monday, 18 February 1873 edition of the ''Southern Cross'' reported the sudden declaration of war between England and [[Russia]]. As a result, the Russian warship ''Kaskowiski'' \u2013 whose very name should have made sober readers suspicious \u2013 had allegedly entered Auckland Harbour on the previous Saturday night and proceeded to capture a British ship, along with the city's arms and ammunition supply, and hold a number of leading citizens for ransom. The 954-man Russian vessel obviously meant business, with a dozen 30-ton guns as well as a remarkably new advance in warfare, a paralysing and deadly \"water-gas\" that could be injected into enemy ships from a great distance.<ref name=Wolfe>Wolfe, Richard (2007) ''With Honour \u2013 Our Army Our Nation Our History.'' Page 51. {{ISBN|978-0-670-04565-5}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nThe ''Southern Cross'' article created panic and the Government commissioned its first reports on the colony's defences. It was now clearly understood that Britain would protect its territories and vital shipping routes, but the defence of individual ports was the responsibility of each self-governing colony. Then Russia declared [[Russo-Turkish War (1877\u20131878)|war on Turkey]] in 1877 producing another \"scare\". The decision was taken to construct fortifications and [[Early naval vessels of New Zealand#Fears of Russian invasion|purchase naval boats]] which would protect the harbours at [[Auckland]], [[Wellington]], [[Lyttelton, New Zealand|Lyttelton]] and [[Port Chalmers]]. These [[coastal artillery]] fortifications or [[Land battery|land batteries]] were to be based on British designs. Heavy [[artillery]] pieces and ammunition was ordered from Britain. By 1885 work started in earnest on the construction of what eventually became seventeen forts, further encouraged by yet another [[Panjdeh Incident|Russian scare]].<ref name=Wolfe />\n\n===Artillery===\n[[File:North Head South Battery.jpg|right|thumb|[[BL 8 inch Mk I - VII naval gun|BL 8-inch]] Armstrong [[disappearing gun]] at [[North Head, New Zealand|North Head]].]]\nIn 1885 the New Zealand Government bought ten Armstrong [[BL 8 inch Mk I - VII naval gun|BL 8-inch]] and thirteen Armstrong [[BL 6 inch gun Mk V|BL 6-inch]] guns on disappearing carriages. The [[disappearing gun]] was the very latest in military technology in the 1880s. It was \"disappearing\" because as it fired, the recoil pushed the gun back underground where it could be reloaded under cover. The total costs of this artillery plus the costs of installation including land, emplacements, magazines and barracks was about \u00a3160,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://riv.co.nz/rnza/hist/dgun/harbdef1885.htm|title=Harbour Defences 1885|first=CM|last=Rivers|work=riv.co.nz|accessdate=20 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081015063532/http://riv.co.nz/rnza/hist/dgun/harbdef1885.htm|archive-date=15 October 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the \"second Russian scare\" a number of additional RML 7-inch and 64-pr guns were also installed <ref>{{cite web|url=http://riv.co.nz/rnza/hist/dgun/index.htm|title=Disappearing Guns|first=CM|last=Rivers|work=riv.co.nz|access-date=20 September 2016|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807121544/http://riv.co.nz/rnza/hist/dgun/index.htm|archive-date=7 August 2016|df=}}</ref>\n {| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Artillery circa 1890\n! Number\n! Range\n! Notes\n|-\n| Armstrong [[BL 8 inch Mk I - VII naval gun|BL 8-inch Mk VII]] [[disappearing gun]]s\n| 10\n| 4 miles \n| Weighed 13.5 tons and fired a 180-pound shell.\n|-\n| Armstrong [[BL 6 inch gun Mk V|BL 6-inch]] [[disappearing gun]]s\n| 13\n| 3 miles\n| Weighed 5 tons and fired a 100-pound shell.\n|-\n| [[RML 7 inch 7 ton gun]]s \n| 11\n|  \n| Weighed 7 tons.\n|-\n| [[RML 64 pounder 64 cwt gun|RML 64-pr Mk 3]] guns\n| 9\n| 2 miles\n| Weighed 64 [[Hundredweight|cwt]]\n|}\n\n===The forts===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|-\n!Fort\n!Harbour\n!width=\"30\"|Way-<br />point\n!width=\"100\"|Ordnance<br />circa 1890\n!width=\"35\"|Range<br />(miles)\n!width=\"35\"|Dates\n!width=\"370\"|Notes\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| [[North Head, New Zealand|North Head]]\n| Auckland\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|36|49|39|S|174|48|44|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |name=North Head |display=inline}}\n| 1x[[BL 8 inch Mk VII naval gun|BL 8in gun]]<br />RML 7in guns<br />64-pr guns\n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1870\n| At Devonport, divided into three sub-forts:\n* North Battery (to defend Rangitoto Channel) \n* South Battery (with a 7in gun to protect the inner harbour) \n* Fort Cautley (with the 8in gun on the summit).<ref name=NthHeadHR>{{cite web|url=http://www.doc.govt.nz/parks-and-recreation/places-to-visit/auckland/central-and-south-auckland/north-head-historic-reserve/|title=Maungauika/North Head Historic Reserve|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=NthHead>{{cite web|url=http://www.devonport.co.nz/north_head.htm|title=North Head|publisher=|access-date=5 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413075550/http://www.devonport.co.nz/north_head.htm|archive-date=13 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>[http://www.doc.govt.nz/upload/documents/conservation/historic/by-region/north-head-self-guided-walk.pdf North Head self-guided walk]</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| [[Bastion Point]]\n| Auckland\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|36|50|43|S|174|49|29|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline |name=Bastion Point}}\n| 2xBL 6in guns\n| align=\"center\"| \n|1885\u2013\n| In [[Mission Bay, New Zealand|Mission Bay]]. Not completed.\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Fort Resolution\n| Auckland\n| align=\"center\"| \n| 2xBL 6in guns \n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1885\n| In Parnell.\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Fort Takapuna\n| Auckland\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Fort Takapuna |36|48|55|S|174|48|24|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2xBL 6in guns\n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1886\u2013\n| <ref name=9CoastReg>{{cite web|url=http://riv.co.nz/rnza/units/9c/taka.htm|title=9 Coast Regiment at Fort Takapuna|first=CM|last=Rivers|work=riv.co.nz|accessdate=20 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170406045417/http://riv.co.nz/rnza/units/9c/taka.htm|archive-date=6 April 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=FtTakapunaWalk>{{cite web|url=http://www.doc.govt.nz/parks-and-recreation/tracks-and-walks/auckland/central-and-south-auckland/fort-takapuna-historic-walk/|title=Fort Takapuna Historic Walk|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=FtTakapunaHR>{{cite web|url=http://www.doc.govt.nz/parks-and-recreation/places-to-visit/auckland/central-and-south-auckland/fort-takapuna-historic-reserve/|title=Fort Takapuna Historic Reserve|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Fort Takapuna\">[http://www.doc.govt.nz/upload/documents/conservation/historic/by-region/fort-takapuna-hgmp-may-2001.pdf  Fort Takapuna]</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| [[Mount Victoria, Auckland|Fort Victoria]]\n| Auckland\n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1x[[BL 8 inch Mk VII naval gun|BL 8in gun]]\n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1885\n| On Mount Victoria, Devonport. The gun fired only once because of complaints from residents whose windows were broken.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.teara.govt.nz/NewZealandInBrief/GovernmentAndNation/10/ENZ-Resources/Standard/1/en|title=Fortifications at Mt Victoria, Auckland \u2013 Nation and government \u2013 Te Ara Encyclopedia of New Zealand|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080405215632/http://www.teara.govt.nz/NewZealandInBrief/GovernmentAndNation/10/ENZ-Resources/Standard/1/en|archive-date=5 April 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| [[Fort Ballance]]\n| Wellington\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Fort Ballance |41|17|41|S|174|50|02|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2x7\" RML guns<br />1x6\" BLHP gun<br />2 x [[QF 6 pounder Nordenfelt]] guns\n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1885\n| (1885\u20131886) Point Gordon. At Miramar. Wellington's primary military fort until 1911 when Fort Dorset opened.<ref name=FtBallance>{{cite web|url=http://www.capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/pre1930/ballnce1.htm|title=Fort Ballance, Wellington|work=orcon.net.nz|access-date=20 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080124043211/http://www.capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/pre1930/ballnce1.htm|archive-date=24 January 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Fort Gordon\n| Wellington\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Fort Ballance |41|17|41|S|174|50|02|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 1x8\" BLHP gun\n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1895-1924\n| Point Gordon\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| [[Fort Buckley]]\n| Wellington\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Fort Buckley |41|15|38|S|174|47|17|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2x64-pr RML guns\n| align=\"center\"| 2\n| \n| At Kaiwharawhara.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/pre1930/bukley1.htm|title=Fort Buckley|work=orcon.net.nz|access-date=20 September 2016|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041212140642/http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/pre1930/bukley1.htm|archive-date=12 December 2004|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/period/buklyp1.htm|title=Fort Buckley: period photo|work=orcon.net.nz|access-date=20 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010803190650/http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/period/buklyp1.htm|archive-date=3 August 2001|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/36251685@N00/sets/683677|title=Fort Buckley|work=Flickr|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Haswell Battery\n| Wellington\n| align=\"center\"|\n| 1xBL 8in gun\n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1889\n| At Miramar.\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| [[Kau Point Battery]]\n| Wellington\n| align=\"center\"|\n| 1xBL 8in gun\n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1891-1922\n| At Miramar.\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Fort Kelburne\n| Wellington\n| \n| 2xBL 8in guns \n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1885\n| At Ngauranga.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/period/ftkelburne1.htm|title=Fort Kelburne: Period photo|work=orcon.net.nz|access-date=20 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020906094154/http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/period/ftkelburne1.htm|archive-date=6 September 2002|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Battery Point\n| Lyttelton\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Battery Point |43|36|10|S|172|44|25|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2x7in RML guns<br />1x QF 6 pounder Nordenfelt guns\n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1885\n| On the north side of Lyttelton Harbour, 3 miles from mouth.<ref name=BatteryPt>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzrifle.com/ml_battery_point.htm|title=WWII Coastal Defence Fortifications - Battery point|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=BatteryPtFoto>[http://www.nzrifle.com/images/ml_images/ml_bty_point_images/bty_point_%20overveiw02(index).jpg Annotated photo of Battery Point]</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| [[Ripapa Island#Fort Jervois|Fort Jervois]]\n| Lyttelton\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Ripapa Island |43|37|11|S|172|45|15|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2x8in BL guns<br />2x6in BL guns\n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1886\n| On [[Ripapa Island]] on the south side of Lyttelton Harbour (often called 'Ripa') <ref name=FtJervoisRipapa>{{cite web|url=http://www.doc.govt.nz/conservation/historic/by-region/canterbury/christchurch-and-banks-peninsula/fort-jervois-ripapa-island/|title=New Zealand historic heritage: Our work|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref> Fort Jervois is an internationally rare 1880s \u201cRussian Invasion Scare\u201d  structure, which has retained a high level of authenticity of both structure and hardware (6\u201d and 8\u201d disappearing guns). It is one of only five examples of this type of fortification in the world. The Island has been managed by the Department of Conservation since 1990.<ref name=FtJervoisRestore>{{Cite web |url=http://www.doc.govt.nz/upload/documents/about-doc/tenders/carbon-sink-tenders/conservation-projects/fort-jervois-restoration-ripapa-island-lyttelton-harbour.pdf |title=Fort Jervois Restoration |access-date=2007-12-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081016225618/http://doc.govt.nz/upload/documents/about-doc/tenders/carbon-sink-tenders/conservation-projects/fort-jervois-restoration-ripapa-island-lyttelton-harbour.pdf |archive-date=2008-10-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Spur Point Battery\n| Lyttelton\n| align=\"center\"|\n| 1x64-pounder RML gun\n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1885\n| Site of battery, quarried away as part of land reclamation during the 1970s to build Cashin Quay.<ref>{{cite book |last=Glackin |first=Russel |authorlink= |title=In Defence of Our Land: A Tour of New Zealand's Historic Harbour Forts |url= |accessdate= |year=2009 |publisher=Penguin Group |location= |isbn=978-014301186-6 |page=64 }}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| [[Lawyer's Head]] Battery \n| Port Chalmers\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Lawyer's Head Battery |45|54|32|S|170|32|06|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| \n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1885\n| Eastern Ocean Beach, Dunedin South.\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| Ocean Beach Battery \n| Port Chalmers\n| align=\"center\"| \n| \n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1886\n| \n|-valign=\"top\"\n| [[Saint Clair, New Zealand|St Clair]] Battery \n| Port Chalmers\n| align=\"center\"| \n| \n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1885\n| On a spur of Forbury Hill above [[Second Beach (New Zealand)|Second Beach]], Dunedin. No remnants remain; the area was cleared and subdivided for residential housing.\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| [[Taiaroa Head|Fort Taiaroa]]\n| Port Chalmers\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Fort Taiaroa |45|46|26|S|170|43|40|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 1xBL 6in gun \n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1885\n| Otago Harbour. This Armstrong Disappearing Gun was installed in May 1889 and was recommissioned during World War II. It is the only one of its kind working and is still in its original gun pit.<ref>[http://www.albatross.org.nz/Fort.htm Fort Taiaroa]</ref><ref>[http://www.army.mil.nz/at-a-glance/news/army-news/365/rtg.htm Raising the Guns]</ref>\n|}\n\n==World War II coastal fortifications==\n[[File:NZ-StonyBatter1.jpg|right|thumb|Tunnel layout for a three gun emplacement system.]] \nThe second main wave of building coastal fortifications occurred during [[World War II]]. This was mainly a response to a perceived threat of invasion by the [[Japan]]ese after the attack on [[Attack on Pearl Harbor|Pearl Harbor]]. From 1942 until 1944, when the threat receded, 42 [[coastal artillery]] fortifications or [[Land battery|land batteries]] were either developed using historical fortifications or were built from scratch. The fortifications were built from [[United Kingdom|British]] designs adapted to New Zealand conditions.  [[Radar]] was installed which allowed long range shooting at night and replaced the traditional fortress system of [[Rangefinder|range finding]].<ref name=CoastArtill />\n\n===Ordnance===\n[[File:NZ-StonyBatter3.jpg|right|thumb|9.2 inch gun emplacement at [[Stony Batter]].]]\nThe fortifications were equipped with both old and new [[Ammunition#Ordnance ammunition|ordnance]], mostly British. Some World War I ordnance was requisitioned from museums and recommissioned.{{Citation needed|date=June 2010}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Ordnance used during World War II\n! Number\n! Range\n! Notes\n|-\n| [[BL 9.2 inch gun Mk IX - X|9.2 inch guns]]\n| 6\n| 18 miles\n| \n|-\n| [[British ordnance terms#BL|BL]]  [http://www.navweaps.com/Weapons/WNBR_6-50_mk22.htm BL 6 inch Mk 24 guns]\n| 3\n| 14 miles\n| \n|-\n| BL 6&nbsp;inch Mk 21 guns\n| 6\n| 13 miles\n| \n|-\n| [[BL 6 inch Gun Mk 7|6 inch Mark 7 guns]]\n| 32\n| 12 miles\n| \n|-\n| [https://web.archive.org/web/20160807121544/http://riv.co.nz/rnza/hist/dgun/index.htm 6in EOC gun]\n| 2\n| 6 miles\n| Elswick Ordnance Company\n|-\n| [[5\"/51 caliber gun]]s<ref name=DiGiulian>DiGiulian, Tony, [http://www.navweaps.com/Weapons/WNUS_5-51_mk7.htm \"United States of America 5\"/51 (12.7 cm) Marks 7, 8, 9, 14 and 15. British 5\"/51 (12.7 cm) BL Marks VI and VII]</ref> (USA naval guns)\n| 6\n| 10 miles\n| 51 calibre MkVII 1912 \n|-\n| [[QF 4.7 inch Gun Mk I - IV|4.7in guns]]\n| 1\n| 6 miles\n| \n|-\n| [[BL 4 inch naval gun Mk VII|4 inch Mark 7 guns]]\n| 11\n| 9 miles\n| \n|-\n| [[M114 155 mm howitzer|155mm guns]]\n| 2\n| 9 miles\n| \n|-\n| [[75 mm gun (US)|75mm guns]]\n| 2\n| \n| \n|-\n| [[British ordnance terms#QF|QF]] [https://web.archive.org/web/20071226221500/http://riv.co.nz/rnza/hist/local/qf12pr.htm 12 pdr guns]\n| 8\n| 8 miles\n| \n|-\n| [[British ordnance terms#QF|QF]] [[Ordnance QF 6 pounder|6 pdr guns]]\n| 12\n|5 miles\n| \n|-\n| [https://web.archive.org/web/20071227143347/http://riv.co.nz/rnza/hist/local/qf40mmaa.htm Bofors 40mm guns]\n| 48\n| 4 miles\n| \n|-\n| [[Searchlight|CASLs]]\n| 48\n| \n| Coastal Artillery Searchlight \n|}\n\n===The fortifications===\nThe fortifications were administered by the [[Royal New Zealand Artillery]], which grouped them into four areas. Each area was under the command of a heavy artillery regiment. Within each regiment the fortifications were grouped into batteries.{{Citation needed|date=June 2010}}\n{| \n|-\n|style=\"background:#ffffdd;\"| <small>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Also used (highlighted below in yellow) were seven of the now historic Russian scare fortifications &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </small>\n|}\n\n====Upper North Island====\nUnder the command of the 9th Heavy (Coast) Regiment.{{Citation needed|date=June 2010}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!width=\"35\"|Battery\n!width=\"70\"|Name\n!width=\"30\"|Way-<br />point\n!width=\"100\"|World War II<br />Ordnance\n!width=\"35\"|Range<br />(miles)\n!width=\"35\"|Dates\n!width=\"335\"|Notes\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 60\n| [[Motutapu Island]]\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|36|45|03|S|174|55|09|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline |name=Motutapu Island}}\n| 3 x 6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;21&nbsp;guns<br /> 2 x CASLs \n| align=\"center\"|13\n| 1936<br />-1945\n| Consisted of a battery, camp, gun emplacement, pill boxes and US naval magazines. Its remains are administered by DOC.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doc.govt.nz/conservation/historic/by-region/auckland/hauraki-gulf-islands/motutapu-island-recreation-reserve/|title=New Zealand historic heritage: Our work|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 61<br />RHQ \n| style=\"background:#ffffdd;\"| [[North Head, New Zealand|North Head]]<br /><small>[Russian scare]</small>\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|36|49|39|S|174|48|44|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |name=North Head |display=inline}}\n| 2 x [[BL 4 inch naval gun Mk VII|4in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7 guns]]<br />2 x 12pdr guns<br />4 x 6pdr H&N<br />6 x CASLs\n| align=\"center\"| 9\n| 1870<br />-1957\n| Part of Auckland's coastal defence system from the [[Panjdeh Incident|Russian scare]] in 1885 to World War I. By World War II, with ships' guns able to fire long distances, the old fort was too close to the city it was meant to defend. New batteries were built at Motutapu, Castor Bay, Whangaparaoa and Waiheke Island and North Head became the centre of administration.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doc.govt.nz/conservation/historic/by-region/auckland/central-and-south-auckland/north-head-historic-reserve/history-of-the-reserve/|title=Maungauika/North Head Historic Reserve|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref> A complex of tunnels, guns, searchlights and other fortifications remain and it is now a historic reserve managed by the Department of Conservation.<ref name=NthHeadHR /><ref name=NthHead />\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 61\n| style=\"background:#ffffdd;\"| [[Bastion Point]]<br /><small>[Russian scare]</small>\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Bastion Point |36|50|43|S|174|49|29|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2 x 12pdr gun<br />Twin 6pdr guns<br />3xCASLs \n| align=\"center\"| 8\n|1885\u2013\n| Located in [[Mission Bay, New Zealand|Mission Bay]]. The fortifications were buried in the 1940s when the [[Michael Joseph Savage]] memorial was built, and effectively forgotten. The underlying tunnels were later rediscovered.\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 61\n| [[Great Barrier Island]]\n| \n| 6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;gun<br />[[BL 4 inch naval gun Mk VII|4in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7 gun]]<br />4 x [[Bofors 40 mm gun|40mm&nbsp;Bofors]] \n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| \n| \n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 61\n| Manukau\n| \n| 1x4.7in gun\n| align=\"center\"| 6\n| 1942\n| Built by American Forces [unknown unit] at the end of Harvey Road, Manukau Heads, approximately 100 m north of lighthouse site, this open fronted fortification had one gun, and an observation post inland. Accommodation was at the end of Harvey Road, with only concrete pads remaining for some buildings. Due to the erosive nature of these compacted sandhills the gun emplacement was undermined and slipped down the cliffs in the early 1980s. According to local residents, the gun was only fired 6 times, cracking the concrete abutments.\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 61\n| [[Motuihe Island]]\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Motuihe Island |36|48|40|S|174|49|29|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2 x [[BL 4 inch naval gun Mk VII|4in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7 guns]] \n| align=\"center\"| 9\n| 1872\u2013\n| During World War II (1941) the Motuihe buildings became HMNZS Tamaki naval base, a training establishment.  Now in the care of the Department of Conservation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doc.govt.nz/conservation/historic/by-region/auckland/hauraki-gulf-islands/hauraki-gulf-defences/|title=New Zealand historic heritage: Our work|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://www.navymuseum.mil.nz/history/time/49-2000/training/tamaki.htm HMNZS ''Tamaki'']</ref><ref>[http://www.navymuseum.mil.nz/history/pers/name-index/l/long-a-g.htm  Long, Instructor Lieutenant A.G.]</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 62\n| style=\"background:#ffffdd;\"| Fort Takapuna<br /><small>[Russian scare]</small>\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Fort Takapuna |36|48|55|S|174|48|24|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2 x [[BL 4 inch naval gun Mk VII|4in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7 guns]]<br /> 2 x CASLs \n| align=\"center\"| 9\n| 1886\u2013\n| Also known as HMNZS Tamaki, and Narrow Neck. In 1963 the RNZN moved its New Entry Training School HMNZS Tamaki from Motuihe Island to the fort. The navy built a new Gunnery School and set up an Officer Training School. Previously officers had been sent overseas for training. Only the Officer and Trade Training schools remain. Has been under the care of the Department of Conservation since 2000.<ref name=9CoastReg /><ref name=FtTakapunaWalk /><ref name=FtTakapunaHR /><ref name=FtTakapunaHR /><ref name=\"Fort Takapuna\"/>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 63\n| [[Castor Bay]]\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Castor Bay |36|45|22|S|174|46|0|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2 x [[BL 6 inch Mk VII naval gun|6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;guns]]<br /> 2 x CASLs \n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| 1942<br />-1944\n| [[File:J F Kennedy bunker.jpg|thumb|80px|right|Bunker at Castor Bay]]\nNotable for its camouflage strategies during World War II.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livingheritage.org.nz/schools/primary/campbellsbay/campbells_war/stories/storyReader$45.html|title=Campbell's Bay Primary School|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref><ref>McCarthy, Christine (2002) Camouflage: Military Upholstery and Interior Disguise. ''Space and Culture'', Vol5, No4, 320\u2013332.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://riv.co.nz/rnza/tales/ngaire1.htm|title=Ngaire's War - 9th Heavy Regiment|first=CM|last=Rivers|work=riv.co.nz|accessdate=20 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170407042201/http://riv.co.nz/rnza/tales/ngaire1.htm|archive-date=7 April 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 64\n| [[Whangaparaoa|Whanga-<br />paraoa]]\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Whangaparaoa |36|36|09|S|174|50|16|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2 x [[BL 6 inch Mk VII naval gun|6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;guns]]<br /> 2 x CASLs \n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| \n| SE tip of peninsula\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 163    \n| [[Whangaparaoa|Whanga-<br />paraoa]]\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Whangaparaoa |36|36|09|S|174|50|17|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2 x [[BL 9.2 inch gun Mk IX - X|9.2in guns]]\n| align=\"center\"| 18\n| \n| SE tip of peninsula\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 164    \n| [[Stony Batter]]<br />\n| align=\"center\"|  {{Coord|name=Stoney Batter |36|45|45|S|175|10|27|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2 x 9.2in guns\n| align=\"center\"| 18\n| 1942\u2013\n| Waiheke Island. Now in the care of the Department of Conservation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doc.govt.nz/conservation/historic/by-region/auckland/hauraki-gulf-islands/stony-batter-historic-reserve-waiheke-island/|title=New Zealand historic heritage: Our work|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.tourismwaiheke.co.nz/stonybatter.htm |title=Stony Batter |access-date=2007-12-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071215104803/http://www.tourismwaiheke.co.nz/stonybatter.htm |archive-date=2007-12-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 68\n| Moturoa Island\n| align=\"center\"|  {{Coord|name=Moturoa Island |35|13|07|S|174|11|21|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 4 x [[BL 6 inch Mk VII naval gun|6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;guns]]<br /> 8 x [[Bofors 40 mm gun|40mm&nbsp;Bofors]]\n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| \n| Bay of Islands\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 68\n| [[Whangaroa]]\n| align=\"center\"|  {{Coord|name=Whangaroa |35|00|40|S|173|45|21|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;gun\n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| \n| South Head of harbour.\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 139\n| [[Bream Head]]<br />\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Bream Head |35|51|01|S|174|31|35|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| [[5\"/51 caliber gun|5in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;gun]]&nbsp;(USA)\n| align=\"center\"| 10\n| 1942<br />-1944\n| Entrance to Whangarei harbour. Remaining structures are the (Colchester) gun shelter, engine room, and observation post. The most significant feature is the spotting mural with compass bearings painted above the slit window in the observation post.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doc.govt.nz/conservation/historic/by-region/northland/whangarei/bream-head/#Bream|title=New Zealand historic heritage: Our work|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.breamheadtrust.org.nz/display.php?id_item=19 |title=Bream Head Gun \u2013 Well worth a visit |access-date=2007-12-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080126094451/http://www.breamheadtrust.org.nz/display.php?id_item=19 |archive-date=2008-01-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|}\n\n====Lower North Island====\nUnder the command of the 10th Heavy (Coast) Regiment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://riv.co.nz/rnza/tales/wright2.htm|title=10 Coast Regiment|first=CM|last=Rivers|work=riv.co.nz|accessdate=20 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170408122642/http://riv.co.nz/rnza/tales/wright2.htm|archive-date=8 April 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!width=\"35\"|Battery\n!width=\"70\"|Name\n!width=\"30\"|Way-<br />point\n!width=\"100\"|World War II<br />Ordnance\n!width=\"35\"|Range<br />(miles)\n!width=\"35\"|Dates\n!width=\"335\"|Notes\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 70    \n| Palmer Head\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Palmer Head |41|20|14|S|174|49|01|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 3x6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;21&nbsp;guns<br />4xCASLs \n| align=\"center\"| 13\n| 1936<br />-1957\n| At the entrance to the Wellington Harbour. The abandoned gun pits were blown up in the late 1960s. The only remains are the underground plotting rooms, which are closed for safety reasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/post1930/palmnd1.htm|title=Palmer Heads fortress, Wellington|work=orcon.net.nz|access-date=20 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081008023236/http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/post1930/palmnd1.htm|archive-date=8 October 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 71<br />RHQ    \n| Fort Dorset\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Fort Dorset |41|19|33|S|174|50|14|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2x6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;guns<br />2x4in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7guns<br />4x12pdr guns<br />7xCASLs\n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| 1908<br />-1991\n| At the inner entrance to Wellington harbour. The fort was demolished in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/other/dorset1.htm|title=Fort Dorset|work=orcon.net.nz|access-date=20 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020305034905/http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/other/dorset1.htm|archive-date=5 March 2002|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/period/dorstp1.htm|title=Photos of guns at Fort Dorset|work=orcon.net.nz|access-date=20 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010803191056/http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/period/dorstp1.htm|archive-date=3 August 2001|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 72    \n| style=\"background:#ffffdd;\"| [[Fort Ballance]]<br /><small>[Russian scare]</small>\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Fort Ballance |41|17|41|S|174|50|02|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2x4in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7guns<br />Twin 6pdr guns<br />2x75mm guns<br />6xCASLs\n| align=\"center\"| 9\n| 1885\u2013<br />1945\n| (1885\u20131886) Point Gordon\nBy Mount Crawford, Karaka Bays, Wellington's primary fort until 1911 when Fort Dorset opened, Fort Ballance was closed in 1945 but remnants remain.<ref name=FtBallance />\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 73    \n| Fort Opau\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Opau |41|13|20|S|174|41|46|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2x6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;guns \n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| 1942<br />-1944\n| On a high headland above Makara, on Wellington's west coast, protecting [[Cook Strait]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/post1930/opau1.htm|title=Fort Opau, Wellington|work=orcon.net.nz|access-date=20 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081008023119/http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/post1930/opau1.htm|archive-date=8 October 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/post1930/opau2.htm|title=Fort Opau: Photos|work=orcon.net.nz|access-date=20 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080124043146/http://www.capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/post1930/opau2.htm|archive-date=24 January 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rickp.net/web%20pages/Makara%20Gun%20Emplacements/index.html |title=Fort Opau: More photos |access-date=2008-01-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080123160201/http://www.rickp.net/web%20pages/Makara%20Gun%20Emplacements/index.html |archive-date=2008-01-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The fort was built in 1941, and comprised two covered 6\" gun emplacements, a battery operations post, and an observation post and a radar post, with a large barracks several hundred metres inland.\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 165    \n| [[Wrights Hill Fortress]]\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Wrights Hill Fortress |41|17|46|S|174|44|21|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2x9.2in guns\n| align=\"center\"| 18\n| 1942<br />1957\n| This British-designed fortress was similar to the 9.2&nbsp;inch fortresses built at Whangaparaoa and Stoney Batter. 2,030 feet (620 metres) of interconnecting tunnels were dug. Two 185&nbsp;hp diesel generators provided power to manoeuvre the guns. Each gun weighed 135 tons and could fire a 380-pound (172&nbsp;kg) shell across Cook Strait or up to Plimmerton. The fortress was used for training purposes up to the mid-1950s. In early 1960 the guns were sold for scrap, ironically, to the Japanese. The Wrights Hill Fortress Restoration Society is restoring the coastal battery to its former state.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whfrs.org.nz/|title=Wrights Hill Fortress: Home Page|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/post1930/wrthil1.htm|title=Wrights Hill Fortress|work=orcon.net.nz|access-date=20 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081008023459/http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/post1930/wrthil1.htm|archive-date=8 October 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 77\n| Bluff Hill\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Bluff Hill |39|28|43|S|176|55|03|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2x6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;guns<br />4x40mm&nbsp;Bofors\n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| \n| At Napier. Also a signal station during World War II,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.napier.govt.nz/napier/parks/memorials/bluff-hill-lookout|title=Bluff Hill Lookout|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref> although never a lighthouse,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newzealandlighthouses.com/napier_bluff.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150202215305/http://www.newzealandlighthouses.com/napier_bluff.htm|title=Napier Bluff|work=newzealandlighthouses.com|archivedate=2 February 2015|accessdate=20 September 2016}}</ref> despite being situated on Lighthouse Road.\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 77\n| [[Titirangi (hill)|Titirangi]] (Kaiti Hill)\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Kaiti Hill |38|42|03|S|178|03|56|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 5in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;gun&nbsp;(USA)\n| align=\"center\"| 10\n| \n| Located at Gisborne.\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 78    \n| [[Moturoa]]\n| \n| 2x155mm guns<br />4x40mm&nbsp;Bofors\n| align=\"center\"| 9\n| \n| At New Plymouth.\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 140\n| Languard Bluff\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Languard Bluff |39|57|30|S|175|01|20|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 5in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;gun&nbsp;(USA) \n| align=\"center\"| 10\n| \n| At Wanganui.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/post1930/wngpil1.htm|title=Wanganui gun emplacements|work=orcon.net.nz|access-date=20 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041212140859/http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/post1930/wngpil1.htm|archive-date=12 December 2004|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/post1930/wngpcd3.htm|title=Photos of Wanganui Coastal Battery|work=orcon.net.nz|access-date=20 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060117203218/http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/prfles/post1930/wngpcd3.htm|archive-date=17 January 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|}\n\n====Upper South Island====\nUnder the command of the 11th Heavy (Coast) Regiment.{{Citation needed|date=June 2010}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!width=\"35\"|Battery\n!width=\"70\"|Name\n!width=\"30\"|Way-<br />point\n!width=\"100\"|World War II<br />Ordnance\n!width=\"35\"|Range<br />(miles)\n!width=\"35\"|Dates\n!width=\"335\"|Notes\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 80<br />RHQ    \n| Godley Head\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Godley Head |43|35|13|S|172|48|21|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 3x6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;24&nbsp;guns<br />2xCASLs\n| align=\"center\"| 14\n| 1939<br />-1963\n| At the northern entrance to Lyttelton Harbour, the last NZA to be decommissioned. It last fired a gun in 1959. In its heyday in World War II, it was staffed by over 400 men and women and was a self-contained community. It is ranked in the top ten New Zealand coastal defence heritage sites.<ref name=Godley-Head>{{cite web|title=Godley Head coastal defence battery|url=http://www.doc.govt.nz/conservation/historic/by-region/canterbury/christchurch-and-banks-peninsula/godley-head-coastal-defence-battery/}}</ref>  It is now under the care of the Department of Conservation and the Godley Head Heritage Trust.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://homepages.paradise.net.nz/peterwil/godleyhead/|title=The Godley Head Heritage Trust|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://homepages.paradise.net.nz/peterwil/godleyhead/history/ww2/godleyAndCamp.html |title=Godley Battery and Camp |access-date=2007-12-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080123141203/http://homepages.paradise.net.nz/peterwil/godleyhead/history/ww2/godleyAndCamp.html |archive-date=2008-01-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 81\n|  style=\"background:#ffffdd;\"|Battery Point<br /><small>[Russian scare]</small>\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Battery Point |43|36|10|S|172|44|25|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2x4in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7guns<br />Twin 6pdr guns<br />5xCASLs \n| align=\"center\"| 9\n| 1886\u2013\n| On the northern side of Lyttelton Harbour, 3 miles from mouth.<ref name=BatteryPt /><ref name=BatteryPtFoto />\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 81\n| style=\"background:#ffffdd;\"| [[Ripapa Island#Fort Jervois|Fort Jervois]]<br /><small>[Russian scare]</small>\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Ripapa Island |43|37|11|S|172|45|15|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 6in EOC gun\n| align=\"center\"| 6\n| 1886\n| On [[Ripapa Island]] on the southern side of Lyttelton Harbour.<ref name=FtJervoisRipapa /> It is an internationally rare 1880s \u201cRussian Invasion Scare\u201d military defence structure, which has retained a high level of authenticity of both structure and hardware (6\u201d and 8\u201d disappearing guns). It is one of only five examples of this type of fortification in the world. The island has been managed by the Department of Conservation since 1990.<ref name=FtJervoisRestore />\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| \n| style=\"background:#ffffdd;\"| Magazine Bay<br /><small>[Russian scare]</small>\n| align=\"center\"| \n| ?\n| align=\"center\"| \n| 1886\n| [[Lyttelton, New Zealand|Lyttelton]], in conjunction with nearby torpedo boat base.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lytteltonheritage.co.nz Magazine Bay torpedo Boat museum}}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 84\n| Tory Channel entrance \n| \n| 6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;gun<br />12x40mm&nbsp;Bofors\n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| \n| Queen Charlotte Sound\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 84\n| Maraetai\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Maraetai |41|15|21|S|174|08|01|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;gun \n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| \n| In Tory Channel, Queen Charlotte Sound.\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 84\n| [[Blumine Island]]\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Blumine Island 1 |41|09|30|S|174|14|11|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}; {{Coord|name=Blumine Island 2 |41|09|31|S|174|14|39|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2x6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;guns \n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| 1942<br />-1945\n| Guarding the northern entrance to [[Queen Charlotte Sound (New Zealand)|Queen Charlotte Sound]], the guns are positioned separately on the two northern points of Blumine Island. Associated with each emplacement are a magazine, observation post and accommodation camp.<ref>[http://www.ianbowman.co.nz/stories/storyReader$65#DefenceInstallations Defence Installations, Blumine Island]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sustainableblumine.wikispaces.com/Background|title=SustainableBlumine - Background|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 84\n| Post Office Point\n| \n| 6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;gun\n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| \n| In Pelorus Sound.\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 84\n| [[Maud Island]] \n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Maud Island |41|01|01|S|173|54|21|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;gun\n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| \n| At the entrance to [[Pelorus Sound]]. Under the care of the Department of Conservation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doc.govt.nz/parks-and-recreation/places-to-visit/marlborough/sounds-area/maud-island/|title=Maud Island (Te Hoiere) (Scientific Reserve)|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naturespic.com/NewZealand/image.asp?id=15187|title=Second World War Gun Emplacement on the NE point of Maud Island. Te Hoire, Maud Island, Marlborough Sounds, Marlborough District, Marlborough Region, New Zealand (NZ).|work=naturespic.com|accessdate=20 September 2016}}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 84\n| Port Hills\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Port Hills |41|16|10|S|173|15|59|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;gun\n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| \n| In [[Nelson, New Zealand|Nelson]].\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 85    \n| Smithfield Freezing Works\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Smithfield Freezing Works |44|22|16|S|171|14|41|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2x6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;guns<br />4x40mm&nbsp;Bofors\n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| 1942\u2013<br />1944\n| In [[Timaru]]. The No 2 (Colchester type) gun shelter is in an excellent state of preservation <ref>{{cite web|url=http://nzrifle.com/ml_timaru.htm|title=WWII Coastal Defence Fortifications - Timaru|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 134\n| Westport\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Westport Gun Emplacement |41|43|48|S|171|35|15|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 5in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;gun&nbsp;(USA)<br />4x40mm&nbsp;Bofors\n| align=\"center\"| 10\n| 1942\u2013<br />1944\n| On South Spit. The gun emplacement is no longer there but the battery observation post is visible on Google Earth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzrifle.com/ml_westport.htm|title=WWII Coastal Defence Fortifications -Westport|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 134\n| Cobden\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Cobden |42|26|15|S|171|12|45|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 5in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;gun&nbsp;(USA)<br />4x40mm&nbsp;Bofors\n| align=\"center\"| 10\n| 1942\u2013<br />1944\n| At Greymouth. Establishment: 2 Officers, 1 WO, 3 Sergeants and 26 ORs. [[Grey District Council]] destroyed part of this site, without consultation, in 2007 to make way for a sewer line <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzrifle.com/ml_cobden.htm|title=WWII Coastal Defence Fortifications - Cobden|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 143\n| Wainui\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Wainui |43|49|46|S|172|54|17|E|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n \n| 2x6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;guns<br />4x40mm&nbsp;Bofors<br />2xCASLs\n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| 1942\u2013<br />1944\n| At [[Akaroa Harbour]] on [[Banks Peninsula]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzrifle.com/ml_akaroa.htm|title=WWII Coastal Defence Fortifications - Akaroa|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref>\n|}\n\n====Lower South Island====\nUnder the command of the 13th Heavy (Coast) Regiment.{{Citation needed|date=June 2010}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!width=\"35\"|Battery\n!width=\"70\"|Name\n!width=\"30\"|Way-<br />point\n!width=\"100\"|World War II<br />Ordnance\n!width=\"35\"|Range<br />(miles)\n!width=\"35\"|Dates\n!width=\"335\"|Notes\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| RHQ\n| Dunedin\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 82\n| style=\"background:#ffffdd;\"| [[Taiaroa Head|Fort Taiaroa]]<br /><small>[Russian scare]</small>\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Taiaroa Heads |45|47|12|S|170|43|39|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 6in EOC gun<br />5xCASLs\n| align=\"center\"| 6\n| \n|[[File:Disappearing Gun Taiaroa Head.jpg|thumb|60px|left|Armstrong disappearing gun at Taiaroa Head]]Close to Taiaroa Head at the northeastern tip of Otago Peninsula. Restored, and open to the public. Includes what is believed to be the only 1889 [[Armstrong Disappearing gun]] remaining in working condition in its original gun pit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.otago-peninsula.co.nz/royalalbatrosscentre.html|title=Otago Peninsula Royal Albatross Centre|first=Herman van|last=Velthoven|work=otago-peninsula.co.nz|accessdate=20 September 2016}}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 82\n| Rerewahine\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Rerewahine |45|47|13|S|170|44|45|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2x6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;guns \n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| \n| Otago Peninsula.\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 82\n| [[Ocean Grove, New Zealand|Tomahawk]]\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Tomahawk |45|54|19|S|170|33|11|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2x6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;guns\n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| \n| Dunedin\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 82\n| [[Harington Point]]\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Harrington Point |-45.7834|170.7245|type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 2xTwin 6pdr guns<br />2x6pdr H&N\n| \n| \n| Dunedin\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 141    \n| [[Cape Wanbrow]]\n| align=\"center\"| {{Coord|name=Cape Wanbrow |45|07|13|S|170|58|50|E |type:landmark_region:NZ |display=inline}}\n| 5in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;gun&nbsp;(USA)\n| align=\"center\"| 10\n| 1942\u2013\n| Under the care of the [[Oamaru]] Coastal Defence Restoration Group <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzrifle.com/ml_oamaru.htm|title=WWII Coastal Defence Fortifications - Oamaru|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visitoamaru.co.nz/?precinct&ln=cape_wanbrow|title=Home|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref>\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| align=\"center\"| 142\n| Bluff\n| \n| 6in&nbsp;Mk&nbsp;7&nbsp;gun \n| align=\"center\"| 12\n| \n| \n|}\n\n==Post war==\nThe advent of air warfare and missiles made these forts redundant and most were decommissioned by the 1950s. Godley Head continued because of compulsory military training and last fired a gun in 1959. The Department of Conservation has the remains of around 30 installations on land it manages.<ref name=Godley-Head />\n\n==Postscript==\nNone of the forts fired a gun in anger, though in October 1939 a Battery Point gun at Lyttleton accidentally sank the fishing boat \"Dolphin\" and killed its skipper.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/today-in-history/9266344/Today-in-History-October-12|accessdate=21 February 2017|title=Today in History: October 12|date=12 October 2013|publisher=Stuff.co.nz}}</ref>\n\nIn 1972 the [[United States]] declassified a contingency plan for invading New Zealand.  This plan consisted of a 120-page intelligence document called ''Naval War Plan for the Attack of Auckland, New Zealand''. The intelligence for the report was gathered during the visit of the [[Great White Fleet]] to Auckland over six days in 1908. The plan advocated [[Manukau Harbour]] as the best invasion point and landing heavy guns on [[Rangitoto Island]] to shell the forts on the [[North Shore City|North Shore]]. The plan was not very realistic and may have been an exercise to keep young officers busy (see [[United States color-coded war plans|United States war plans]]; which allocated the colour Garnet to New Zealand as part of [[War Plan Red]]).<ref>Stevens, David and Reeve, John (2001) [https://books.google.com/books?id=5LremxKXzkMC&pg=PA187&lpg=PA187&dq=%22naval+war+plan+for+the+attack+of+auckland%22&source=web&ots=ojirAVaYnA&sig=ghD3VDDCZFBrIDuuvb0uKWmBRSM#PPA187,M1 ''Southern Trident: Strategy, History and the Rise of Australian Naval Power'', Page 184\u2013188.] Allen & Unwin. {{ISBN|978-1-86508-462-6}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Early naval vessels of New Zealand]]\n* [[Coastal defences of Australia during World War II]]\n* [[Coastal Forces of the Royal New Zealand Navy]]\n* [[Axis naval activity in New Zealand waters]]\n* [[British hardened field defences of World War II]]\n* [[British anti-invasion preparations of World War II]]\n* [[Seacoast Defense (US)]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Cooke, Peter (2002) [https://web.archive.org/web/20030615141423/http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/review/dnzcoke.htm ''Defending New Zealand: Ramparts on the Sea 1840s\u20131950s.''] (Wellington). Two volumes. {{ISBN|0-473-08923-8}}. [http://www.phanza.org.nz/users/peter-cooke Peter Cooke] is a professional military historian.\n* Corbett, Peter D. (2003). ''A First Class Defended Port: The History of the Coast Defences of Auckland, its Harbour and Approaches.'' {{ISBN|0-478-22452-4}} (Available from Auckland Conservancy, Department of Conservation).\n* Glackin, Russell (2009) ''In defence of our land: a tour of New Zealand's historic harbour forts'', Penguin, {{ISBN|0-14-301186-3}}.\n\n==External links==\n{{GeoGroupTemplate}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081015043526/http://riv.co.nz/rnza/rf/ww2/nz2.htm NZ coastal artillery units of World War II]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091017115627/http://riv.co.nz/rnza/hist/baigent1.htm Coast Artillery Defences]\n* [http://www.doc.govt.nz/upload/692/Coast-Defence-Sites.gif Map of Coastal Defence Sites around Auckland]\n* [http://www.doc.govt.nz/conservation/historic/by-region/auckland/hauraki-gulf-islands/hauraki-gulf-defences/ Hauraki Gulf Defences]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071213052955/http://capitaldefence.orcon.net.nz/ Capital Defence \u2013 Coastal Defence Sites around Wellington]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091027131228/http://www.geocities.com/CollegePark/Den/5417/index.html Wellington's Coastal Defences]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080123222149/http://www.angelfire.com/ne/4WDNZ/fortifications.htm World War II Fortifications in Canterbury and Westland]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080223122600/http://riv.co.nz/rnza/hist/local/index.htm Artillery pieces in New Zealand]\n* [http://www.ozatwar.com/ozatwar/bunkers.htm Bunkers, tunnels, fortifications in Australia during World War II]\n\n[[Category:Forts in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Coastline of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:New Zealand Army]]\n[[Category:Military history of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Military history of New Zealand during World War II]]\n[[Category:World War II sites in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Coastal fortifications]]\n[[Category:19th-century fortifications]]\n[[Category:20th-century fortifications]]\n", "name_user": "Epipelagic", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBibliography:not notable by itself", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coastal_fortifications_of_New_Zealand"}
{"title_page": "Social Democrats (Denmark)", "text_new": "{{short description|Political party in Denmark}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| native_name = {{#property:P1705}}\n| logo = Social_Democrats_(Denmark)_logo.svg\n| logo_size = 250px\n| leader = [[{{#property:P488}}]]\n| leader1_title = Deputy Leader\n| leader1_name = [[Mogens Jensen (politician)|Mogens Jensen]]<br>[[Frank Jensen]]\n| foundation = {{#property:P571}}\n| student_wing = [[Frit Forum|Frit Forum \u2013 Social Democratic Students of Denmark]]\n| headquarters = Vester Voldgade 96<br>1552 [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]\n| ideology = [[Social democracy]]<ref name=\"Nordsieck\"/><ref name=\"Merkel\"/>\n| position = [[Centre-left politics|Centre-left]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Milne|first=Richard|title=Denmark's centre-left seeks common ground with populists|url=https://www.ft.com/content/f73883a6-621e-11e7-91a7-502f7ee26895|accessdate=12 March 2019|work=Financial Times|date=10 July 2017}}</ref>\n| international = [[Progressive Alliance]]<ref name=\"PA\">{{cite web|url=http://progressive-alliance.info/network/parties-and-organisations/|title=Parties & Organisations|publisher=Progressive Alliance|accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref>\n| european = [[Party of European Socialists]]\n| europarl = [[Progressive Alliance of Socialists and Democrats]]\n| affiliation1_title = Nordic affiliation\n| affiliation1 = [[SAMAK]]<br />[[The Social Democratic Group]]\n| youth_wing = [[Social Democratic Youth of Denmark]]\n| newspaper = Socialdemokraten\n| membership = 40,060<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.dk/da/ofte-stillede-spoergsmaal/parti_hvor-mange-medlemmer-har-de-politiske-partier|title=Hvor mange medlemmer har de politiske partier?|publisher=Folketinget|language=Danish|date=2016|accessdate=8 June 2019}}</ref>\n| membership_year = 2016\n| colours = {{nowrap|{{colour box|#C9002D}} [[Red]]<ref name=\"Red\">[http://maerkesag.dk/valgkamp-har-mange-nuancer-af-roed/ \"Valgkamp har mange nuancer af r\u00f8d\"] (in Danish).</ref><br>{{colour box|{{Social Democrats (Denmark)/meta/color}}}} [[Orange (colour)|Competition orange]]<ref name=\"Red\"/><ref>[https://www.bt.dk/politik/socialdemokraterne-aendrer-den-roede-farve-her-er-partiets-nye-kuloer \"Socialdemokraterne \u00e6ndrer den r\u00f8de farve: Her er partiets nye kul\u00f8r\"] (in Danish).</ref>}}\n| colorcode = {{Social Democrats (Denmark)/meta/color}}\n| seats1_title = [[Folketing]]\n| seats1 = {{composition bar|48|179|hex={{Social Democrats (Denmark)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats2_title = [[European Parliament]]\n| seats2 = {{composition bar|3|14|hex={{Social Democrats (Denmark)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats3_title = [[Regions of Denmark|Regions]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statistikbanken.dk/akva3|work=Statistics Denmark|title=AKVA3: Valg til regions r\u00e5d efter omr\u00e5de, parti og stemmer/kandidater/k\u00f8n|accessdate=13 June 2010}}</ref>\n| seats3 = {{composition bar|70|205|hex={{Social Democrats (Denmark)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats4_title = [[List of municipalities of Denmark|Municipalities]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statistikbanken.dk/valgk3|work=Statistics Denmark|title=VALGK3: Valg til kommunale r\u00e5d efter omr\u00e5de, parti og stemmer/kandidater/k\u00f8n|accessdate=13 June 2010}}</ref>\n| seats4 = {{composition bar|842|2432|hex={{Social Democrats (Denmark)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats5_title = [[Mayor]]s\n| seats5 = {{composition bar|47|98|hex={{Social Democrats (Denmark)/meta/color}}}}\n| symbol = [[File:Dnk party a.svg|50px]]\n| website = {{url|socialdemokratiet.dk}}\n| country = Denmark\n}}\nThe '''Social Democrats''' ({{lang-da|Socialdemokraterne}}, {{IPA-da|so\u02c8\u0255\u025b\u02c0lte\u031dmo\u02cck\u02b0\u0281\u0251\u02c0t\u0250n\u0259|pron}}), officially the '''Social Democratic Party''' or simply '''Social Democracy''' (Danish: ''Socialdemokratiet'', {{IPA-da|so\u02c8\u0255\u025b\u02c0lte\u031dmok\u02b0\u0281\u0251\u02ccts\u02b0i\u02c0\u00f0\u0329|pron}}), is a [[social-democratic]] [[List of political parties in Denmark|political party in Denmark]].<ref name=\"Nordsieck\">{{cite web|url=http://parties-and-elections.eu/denmark.html|title=Denmark|last=Nordsieck|first=Wolfram|date=2019|website=Parties and Elections in Europe}}</ref><ref name=\"Merkel\">{{cite book|title=Social Democracy in Power: the capacity to reform|last1=Merkel|first1=Wolfgang|first2=Alexander|last2=Petring|first3=Christian|last3=Henkes|first4=Christoph|last4=Egle|year=2008|publisher=Taylor & Francis|location=London|isbn=978-0-415-43820-9}}</ref>\n\nFounded by [[Louis Pio]] in 1871, the party first entered the [[Folketing]] in the [[1884 Danish Folketing election|1884 elections]]. By the early 20th century, it had become the party with the largest representation in the Folketing, a distinction it would hold for 77 years. It first formed a government after the [[1924 Danish Folketing election|1924 elections]] under [[Thorvald Stauning]], the longest-serving [[List of Prime Ministers of Denmark|Danish Prime Minister]] of the 20th century. During Stauning's government which lasted until the [[1926 Danish Folketing election|1926 elections]], the Social Democrats exerted a profound influence on [[Danish society]], laying the foundation of the Danish [[welfare state]]. From 2002 to 2016, the party used the name ''Socialdemokraterne'' in some contexts.<ref name=\"name1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bt.dk/nyheder/socialdemokratiet-skifter-navn|title=Socialdemokratiet skifter navn|date=14 September 2002|accessdate=26 September 2016|work=BT/Ritzau}}</ref><ref name=\"name2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.altinget.dk/artikel/socialdemokratiet-laegger-navn-i-graven|title=Socialdemokratiet laver lille navne\u00e6ndring|date=24 September 2016|accessdate=26 September 2016|work=Altinget|last1=Lange|first1=Lasse|last2=Holsten|first2=Erik}}</ref>\n\nThe party was the [[Cabinet of Helle Thorning-Schmidt|major coalition partner]] in government from the [[2011 Danish general election|2011 elections]], with then-party leader [[Helle Thorning-Schmidt]] as [[Prime Minister of Denmark|Prime Minister]]. After the [[2015 Danish general election|2015 elections]], the party was no longer in government, although it regained the position as the largest party in the Danish parliament, the Folketing, with 47 of 179 seats. Thorning-Schmidt withdrew as party leader on the night of the election as a direct consequence of the loss of government control and she was succeeded on 28 June 2015 by the former vice leader [[Mette Frederiksen]], who shifted the party back to the [[Left-wing politics|left]] on economics while criticising [[mass immigration]].<ref name=\"The Guardian\">{{cite news|last=Orange|first=Richard|title=Mette Frederiksen: the anti-migrant left leader set to win power in Denmark|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/may/11/denmark-election-matte-frederiksen-leftwing-immigration?CMP=share_btn_fb|work=The Guardian|date=11 May 2018|accessdate=12 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Politico\">{{cite web|last=O'Leary|first=Naomi|title=Danish left veering right on immigration|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/danish-copenhagen-left-veers-right-on-immigration-policy-integration/|work=Politico|date=6 September 2018|accessdate=13 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nA member of the [[Party of European Socialists]], the Social Democrats have three MEPs in the [[European Parliament]].\n\n== Name and symbol ==\nThe party traces its own history back to the International Labour Association, founded in 1871 and banned in 1873, loosely re-organised in the Social Democratic Labour Party which in 1876 issued the Gimle program, but as a formal political party it was first founded in 1878 as the Social Democratic Federation. This name was formally carried by the party for almost a hundred years, although in practice it also used a number of other names until it changed its name to Social Democracy in 1965. At a congress in [[Aalborg]] in 2002, the party changed its name to the Social Democrats, but from 2016 again only Social Democracy is used.<ref name=\"name1\"/><ref name=\"name2\"/>\n\nThe party has the letter A as a symbol, but the abbreviation S is often used in the media. The party's classic symbol is a [[Rose (symbolism)|red rose]] and in recent times an A in a red circle.\n\n== History ==\n{{expand section|date=December 2013}}\n\n=== 19th century ===\n{{social democracy sidebar}}\nThe party was founded as in 1871 by [[Louis Pio]], [[Harald Brix]] and [[Paul Geleff]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kb.dk/da/nb/materialer/smaatryk/polprog/Socialdemokraterne/index.html|title=Socialdemokraterne \u2013 Socialdemokratiet|publisher=Det Kongelige Bibliotek|language=Danish|accessdate=18 November 2013}}</ref> The goal was to organise the emerging [[working class]] on a [[Democratic socialism|democratic and socialist]] basis. The [[industrialisation]] of Denmark had begun in the mid-19th century and a period of rapid [[urbanisation]] had led to an emerging class of [[Proletariat|urban workers]]. The social democratic movement emerged from the desire to give this group [[political rights]] and [[Representation (politics)|representation]] in the [[Folketing]], the Danish [[parliament]]. In 1876, the party held an annual conference, adopting the first party manifesto. The stated policy was as follows: {{quote|The Danish Social Democratic Labour Party works in its national form, but is convinced of the international nature of the labour movement and ready to sacrifice everything and fulfill all obligations to provide: Freedom, equality and brotherhood among all nations.}}\n\nIn 1884, the party had their first two members of parliament elected, namely [[Peter Thygesen Holm]] and [[Chresten H\u00f8rdum]].\n\n=== 20th century ===\nIn 1906, the party created the Social Democratic Youth Association, lasting until 1920 when the [[Social Democratic Youth of Denmark]] and current party's [[youth wing]] was founded.\n\nIn the [[1924 Danish Folketing election|1924 elections]], the party won the majority with 36.6 percent of the vote and its first government was put in place with [[Thorvald Stauning]] as [[Prime Minister of Denmark|Prime Minister]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kristeligt-dagblad.dk/artikel/86834:Danmark--Den-skjulte-forskel|title=Den skjulte forskel|work=Kristeligt Dagblad|date=5 February 2005|accessdate=18 November 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130718072428/http://www.kristeligt-dagblad.dk/artikel/86834:Danmark--Den-skjulte-forskel|archivedate=18 July 2013}}</ref> That same year, he appointed [[Nina Bang]] as the world's first female minister, nine years after [[women's suffrage]] had been given in Denmark. Stauning stayed in power until his death in 1942, with his party laying the foundations for the Danish [[welfare state]] based on a close collaboration between labor unions and the government.\n\nIn January 1933, Stauning's government entered into what was then the most extensive settlement yet in [[Danish politics]]\u2014the [[Kanslergadeforliget|Kanslergade settlement]] ({{lang-da|Kanslergadeforliget}})\u2014with the liberal party [[Venstre (Denmark)|Venstre]].<ref>Skou, p. 367.</ref> The settlement was named after Stauning's apartment in Kanslergade in [[Copenhagen]] and included extensive [[agricultural subsidy|agricultural subsidies]] and reforms of the legislation and administration in the social sector.<ref>{{cite book|last=M\u00f8rch|first=S\u00f8ren|title=24 statsministre: 24 fort\u00e6llinger om magten i Danmark i det tyvende \u00e5rhundrede og en kort forklaring p\u00e5, hvor den 25. er blevet af|page=165|publisher=Gyldendal|location=Copenhagen|year=2002|isbn=9788702003611|language=Danish}}</ref> In 1935, Stauning was reelected with the famous slogan \"[[Stauning or Chaos]]\".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Svensson|first=Palle|title=Support for the Danish Social Democratic Party 1924\u201339 \u2014 Growth and Response|journal=[[Scandinavian Political Studies]]|volume=9|issue=A9|pages=127\u2013146|doi=10.1111/j.1467-9477.1974.tb00536.x|date=January 1974|ref=harv}} [https://tidsskrift.dk/index.php/scandinavian_political_studies/article/viewFile/12501/23835 Full text].</ref>\n\n[[File:Socialdemokratiet1945.jpg|thumb|Social Democrats election poster for the October 1945 general election]]\nStauning's second cabinet lasted until the [[Nazism|Nazi]] [[occupation of Denmark]] in 1940, when the cabinet was widened to include all political parties for a [[national unity government]] and the Danish government pursued a collaborative policy with the German occupiers. Through the 1940s and until 1972, [[List of Prime Ministers of Denmark|Denmark's Prime Ministers]] were all from the party.\n\n=== Poul Nyrup Rasmussen government coalition: 1993\u20132001 ===\nThe Social Democrats' [[social policy]] through the 1990s and continuing in the 21st century involved a significant [[Redistribution (economics)|redistribution of income]] and the maintenance of a large state apparatus with collectively financed core [[public services]] such as [[public healthcare]], [[education]] and [[infrastructure]].\n\nSocial Democrats-led coalition governments (the [[Cabinet of Poul Nyrup Rasmussen I|I]], [[Cabinet of Poul Nyrup Rasmussen II|II]], [[Cabinet of Poul Nyrup Rasmussen III|III]] and [[Cabinet of Poul Nyrup Rasmussen IV|IV]] Cabinets of [[Poul Nyrup Rasmussen]]) implemented the system known as [[flexicurity]] (flexibility and social security), mixing strong Scandinavian [[unemployment benefits]] with deregulated employment laws, making it easier for employers to fire and rehire people in order to encourage [[economic growth]] and reduce unemployment.<ref>Volkesn, Andrea (2004). \"Policy Changes of European Social Democrats 1945\u201398\". In Bonoli, Giuliano (ed.). ''Social Democratic Party Policies in Contemporary Europe''. Psychology Press.</ref>\n\nThe Cabinets of Poul Nyrup Rasmussen maintained a parliamentary majority during the period from 1993 to 2001 by virtue of their support from the [[Socialist People's Party (Denmark)|Socialist People's Party]] and the [[Red\u2013Green Alliance (Denmark)|Red\u2013Green Alliance]].\n\nTowards the end of the 1990s, a [[trade surplus]] of 30 billion [[Danish krone|kroner]] (US$4.9 billion) turned into a [[Trade deficit|deficit]].{{citation needed|date=February 2007}} To combat this, the government increased taxes, limiting [[Consumption (economics)|private consumption]]. The 1998 initiative, dubbed the Whitsun Packet (Danish: ''Pinsepakken'') from the season it was issued, was not universally popular with the electorate which may have been a factor in the Social Democrats' defeat in the [[2001 Danish general election|2001 elections]].\n\n=== In opposition: 2001\u20132011 ===\nAfter being defeated by the [[Venstre (Denmark)|Liberal Party]] in the 2001 elections, the party chairmanship went to former [[Finance Minister of Denmark|finance]] and [[Foreign Minister of Denmark|foreign minister]] [[Mogens Lykketoft]]. Following another defeat in the [[2005 Danish general election|2005 elections]], Lykketoft announced his resignation as party leader and at an extraordinary congress on 12 March it was decided that all members of the party would cast votes in an election of a new party leader. The two contenders for the leadership represented the two wings in the party, with [[Helle Thorning-Schmidt]] being viewed as [[Centrism|centrist]] and [[Frank Jensen]] being viewed as slightly more [[Centre-left politics|left-leaning]]. On 12 April 2005, Thorning-Schmidt was elected as the new leader.\n\n=== Helle Thorning-Schmidt government coalition: 2011\u20132015 ===\nIn the [[2011 Danish general election|2011 elections]], the Social Democrats gained 44 seats in parliament, the lowest number since 1953.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://s-dialog.dk/A-English+version-Votes-and-seats-default.aspx?site=english&func=article.view&menuAction=selectClose&menuID=123060&id=123059|title=Socialdemokraterne \u2013 English version \u2013 Votes and seats|publisher=S-dialog.dk|accessdate=18 November 2013}}</ref> Nonetheless, the party succeeded in establishing a minority government with the [[Danish Social Liberal Party]] and the [[Socialist People's Party (Denmark)|Socialist People's Party]]. The incumbent centre-right coalition led by the [[Venstre (Denmark)|Liberal Party]] lost power to a centre-left coalition led by the Social Democrats, making Thorning-Schmidt the country's first female Prime Minister. The Danish Social Liberal Party and the Socialist People's Party became part of the three-party centre-left coalition government. The new parliament convened on 4 October. The government rolled back anti-immigration legislation enacted by the previous government<ref>{{cite journal|last=Lee|first=William|url=http://world.time.com/2011/10/06/a-slap-to-europes-far-right-denmark-reshapes-its-immigration-policies/|title=Denmark's New Government Rolls Back an Anti-Immigrant Legacy|journal=Time|date=6 October 2011|accessdate=18 November 2013}}</ref> and passed a tax-reform with support from the liberal-conservative opposition.<ref name=\"ThorningTaxreform\"/> The tax reform raised the top tax threshold, effectively lowering tax rates for the wealthiest citizens.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cphpost.dk/news/politics/pm-supports-call-raise-top-tax-threshold|title=PM supports call to raise top tax threshold|work=The Copenhagen Post|date=16 May 2012|accessdate=18 November 2013}}</ref> The aim of the tax reform was to increase labour output to fend off a projected labour shortage within the next decades. The stated goal was to entice Danes to work more in order to compensate for the decreasing workforce by lowering tax on wages and gradually lowering welfare payments to those outside of the labour market to increase the economic benefit of working relative to receiving welfare.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.nordiclabourjournal.org/nyheter/news-2011-1/article.2011-10-06.6407706507|title=Helle Thorning-Schmidt: Danes must work more|journal=Nordic Labour Journal|date=6 October 2011|accessdate=18 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 February 2014, the Socialist People's Party left the government in protest over the sale of shares in the public energy company [[DONG Energy]] to the investment bank [[Goldman Sachs]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Hakim|first=Danny|title=Goldman Deal Threatens Danish Government|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/01/30/goldman-deal-threatens-danish-government/|work=The New York Times|date=30 January 2014|accessdate=24 June 2015}}</ref> Because of the government's minority status and of its dependency on the support of the Danish Social Liberal Party, the government had to jettison many of the policies that the Social Democrats\u2013Socialist People's Party coalition had given during the campaign. Although critics have accused the government of breaking its promises, other studies argue that it accomplished half of its stated goals, blaming instead poor public relations strategies for its increasingly negative public image.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cphpost.dk/news/politics/government-track-message|title=Government on track but off message|work=The Copenhagen Post|date=18 May 2012|accessdate=18 November 2013}}</ref> The government pursued a centrist compromise agenda, building several reforms with support from both sides of the parliament. This caused friction with the supporting Red\u2013Green Alliance which was kept outside of influence.<ref name=\"ThorningTaxreform\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cphpost.dk/news/politics/government-defends-tax-deal-opposition|title=Government defends tax deal with opposition|work=The Copenhagen Post|date=25 June 2012|accessdate=18 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== In opposition: 2015\u20132019 ===\nIn the [[2015 Danish general election|2015 elections]], the Social Democrats gained seats and became the biggest party in the parliament again since 2001, yet lost the government because the right-wing parties had a majority. The results of the 2015 election and the defeat of the left-bloc led Thorning-Schmidt to resign as Prime Minister on election night and making way for the next leader [[Mette Frederiksen]].<ref>[http://nyheder.tv2.dk/valg2015/2015-06-19-portraet-den-utraditionelle-socialdemokrat-traekker-sig \"Den utraditionelle socialdemokrat tr\u00e6kker sig\"] (in Danish).</ref> Under Frederiksen, the Social Democrats voted in favor of a law allowing Danish authorities to confiscate money, jewellery and other valuable items refugees crossing the border may have,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.citylab.com/equity/2016/01/denmark-refugees-asylum-immigrants-syria/429240/|title=Denmark Will Strip Refugees of Their Valuables|first=Feargus|last=O'Sullivan|work=CityLab|date=26 January 2016|accessdate=13 June 2019}}</ref> despite harsh condemnation from the [[United Nations Human Rights Council|United Nations Human Right Council]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thelocal.dk/20160121/danish-migrant-bill-blasted-at-un|title=Danish migrant bill blasted at UN|first=Nina|last=Larson|work=The Local|date=21 January 2016|accessdate=18 December 2015}}</ref> and widespread comparisons between the plan and the treatment of [[Jews]] in [[Nazi-occupied Europe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2015/12/17/denmark-wants-to-seize-jewelry-from-refugees/|title=Denmark wants to seize jewelry and cash from refugees|first=Rick|last=Noack|work=The Washington Post|date=26 January 2016|accessdate=18 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nSimilarly, the Social Democrats voted for a law [[Burqa ban|banning wearing]] of [[burqa]]s and [[niqab]]s while abstaining during a vote on a law on mandatory handshakes irrespective of religious sentiment at citizenship ceremonies and on a plan to house criminal [[asylum seeker]]s on an island used for researching contagious animal diseases. Frederiksen has also backed the right-wing populist [[Danish People's Party]] in their paradigm shift push to make [[repatriation]] rather than [[Social integration|integration]] the goal of asylum policy. She has called for a cap on non-Western immigrants, expulsion of asylum seekers to a reception centre in North Africa and forced labour for immigrants in exchange for benefits. Labeling economic foreign policies of Europe as too [[Economic liberalism|liberal]], Frederiksen has criticised other social democratic parties for losing their voters' trust by failing to prevent globalisation chipping away at labour rights, increasing inequality and exposing them to uncontrolled immigration.{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\n=== Mette Frederiksen government: 2019\u2013present ===\nIn the [[2019 Danish general election|2019 elections]], the Social Democrats gained one further seat and the opposition red bloc of [[left-wing]] and [[centre-left]] parties (the Social Democrats, the Danish Social Liberal Party, the Socialist People's Party and the Red\u2013Green Alliance along with the [[Faroe Islands|Faroese]] [[Social Democratic Party (Faroe Islands)|Social Democratic Party]] and [[Greenland]]'s [[Inuit Ataqatigiit]] and [[Siumut]]) won a majority of 93 out of 179 seats in the Folketing while support for the [[Danish People's Party]] and the [[Liberal Alliance (Denmark)|Liberal Alliance]] collapsed, costing [[Lars L\u00f8kke Rasmussen]] his majority. With the result beyond doubt on election night, Rasmussen conceded defeat and Frederiksen has been commissioned by [[Margrethe II of Denmark|Queen Margrethe II]] to lead the negotiations to form a new government.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dr.dk/nyheder/politik/folketingsvalg/loekke-mette-frederiksen-udpeget-som-kongelig-undersoeger|title=L\u00f8kke: Mette Frederiksen udpeget som kongelig unders\u00f8ger|last=Ingvorsen|first=Emil S\u00f8nderg\u00e5rd|publisher=DR|date=6 June 2019|language=Danish|accessdate=16 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dr.dk/nyheder/politik/danmarks-nye-regering-er-nu-paa-plads-se-hele-mette-frederiksens-ministerhold-her|title=Danmarks nye regering er nu p\u00e5 plads: Se hele Mette Frederiksens ministerhold her|last=M\u00fcller|first=Thea Deleuran|publisher=DR|date=27 June 2019|language=Danish|accessdate=28 June 2019}}</ref> On 27 June 2019, Frederiksen was successful in forming the [[Frederiksen Cabinet]], an exclusively Social Democratic minority government supported by the red bloc, becoming the second woman in the role after Thorning-Schmidt as well as the youngest Prime Minister in Danish history at the age of 41.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/denmarks-youngest-prime-minister-to-lead-new-government/a-49357121|title=Denmark's youngest prime minister to lead new government|publisher=Deutsche Welle|date=25 June 2019|accessdate=27 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nDespite having run on an [[anti-immigration]] stance during the election, Frederiksen shifted her stance on immigration by allowing more foreign labour and reversing government plans to hold foreign criminals offshore after winning government.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/mette-frederiksen-social-democrats-form-government-in-denmark/|title=Social Democrats form government in Denmark|newspaper=Politico|date=26 June 2019|accessdate=31 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/denmark-new-government-left-mette-frederiksen-welfare-spending-anti-immigration-a8975096.html|title=Denmark gets new left-wing government with plans to increase welfare spending and scrap anti-immigration measures|newspaper=The Independent|date=26 June 2019|accessdate=31 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2019/06/26/world/politics-diplomacy-world/denmark-becomes-third-nordic-country-form-leftist-government-year/|title=Denmark becomes third Nordic country to form leftist government this year|newspaper=The Japan Times|date=26 June 2019|accessdate=31 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Platform ==\nSince its foundation, the lemma of the party has been \"[[Libert\u00e9, \u00e9galit\u00e9, fraternit\u00e9|Liberty, Equality and Brotherhood]]\" and these values are still described as central in the party program. In the political program, these values are described as being consistent with a focus on solidarity with the poorest and social welfare to those who need it, with individual responsibility in relation to other members in society and with an increased involvement in the [[European Union|European political project]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.socialdemokraterne.dk/download.aspx?docId=717618|title=Handen Pa Hjertet|publisher=Socialdemokratiet|accessdate=16 November 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130616101723/http://socialdemokraterne.dk/download.aspx?docId=717618|archivedate=16 June 2013}}</ref> As well as adopting more [[left-leaning]] economics, the party has become increasingly sceptical of [[Economic liberalism|liberal]] [[mass immigration]] from a left-wing point of view as it believes it has had negative impacts for much of the population, a more pressing issue since at least 2001 after the [[11 September attacks]] which intensified during the [[2015 European migrant crisis]], including the view that perception of adopting the [[Third Way]] and practicing [[centrist]], [[neoliberal economics]] and supporting unrestricted [[Economic globalisation|globalisation]] contributed to its poor electoral performance in the early 21st century.<ref name=\"The Guardian\"/><ref name=\"Politico\"/> In a recent biography, party leader and Danish Prime Minister [[Mette Frederiksen]] further argued: \"For me, it is becoming increasingly clear that the price of unregulated globalisation, mass immigration and the free movement of labour is paid for by the lower classes\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/may/11/denmark-election-matte-frederiksen-leftwing-immigration|title=Mette Frederiksen: the anti-immigration left leader set to win power in Denmark|first=Richard Orange|last=Copenhagen|work=The Guardian|date=11 May 2019|accessdate=8 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Political leadership ==\nThe Party Leader is [[Mette Frederiksen]]. She succeeded [[Helle Thorning-Schmidt]], who stepped down after the left bloc's defeat in the [[2015 Danish general election|2015 elections]]. Deputy Party Leaders are [[Lord Mayor of Copenhagen]] [[Frank Jensen]] and Mogens Jensen. The Secretary General is Jan Juul Christensen.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.socialdemokratiet.dk/da/partiet/in-english-the-social-democratic-party/the-social-democratic-partys-organisation}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Cabinet of Helle Thorning-Schmidt]], the party had ten ministers, including the Prime Minister.<ref name=\"Copenhagen Post\">{{cite news|title=Here are Denmark\u2019s new ministers|url=http://www.cphpost.dk/news/politics/90-politics/52255-here-are-denmarks-new-ministers.html|accessdate=4 October 2011|work=The Copenhagen Post|date=3 October 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111003184742/http://cphpost.dk/news/politics/90-politics/52255-here-are-denmarks-new-ministers.html|archivedate=3 October 2011}}</ref>\n{|\n|-\n|[[File:Helle Thorning-Schmidt government.jpg|thumb|500px|Cabinet of [[Helle Thorning-Schmidt]] in front of [[Amalienborg]] in 2011]]\n|-\n|[[Prime Minister of Denmark|Prime Minister]]\n|[[Helle Thorning-Schmidt]]\n|-\n|[[Finance Minister of Denmark|Minister for Finance]]\n|[[Bjarne Corydon]]\n|-\n|[[Justice Minister of Denmark|Minister for Justice]]\n|[[Karen H\u00e6kkerup]]\n|-\n|[[Defence Minister of Denmark|Minister for Defence]]\n|[[Nicolai Wammen]]\n|-\n|Minister for the City, Housing and Rural Affairs\n|[[Carsten Hansen (politician)|Carsten Hansen]]\n|-\n|Minister for Employment\n|[[Mette Frederiksen]]\n|-\n|[[Minister of Education (Denmark)|Minister for Children and Education]]\n|[[Christine Antorini]]\n|-\n|[[Ministry of Economic and Business Affairs (Denmark)|Minister for Business and Growth]]\n|[[Henrik Sass Larsen]]\n|-\n|[[List of Ministers for Food, Agriculture and Fisheries of Denmark|Minister for Food, Agriculture and Fisheries]]\n|[[Dan J\u00f8rgensen]]\n|-\n|Minister for European Affairs\n|[[Nick H\u00e6kkerup]]\n|}\n\n== Electoral performance ==\nThe Social Democrats governed Denmark for most of the 20th century, with a few intermissions such as the [[Conservative People's Party (Denmark)|Conservative People's Party]]-led government of [[Poul Schl\u00fcter]] in the 1980s. It continued to be Denmark's largest party until 2001 when [[Anders Fogh Rasmussen]]'s liberal [[Venstre (Denmark)|Venstre]] party gained a landslide victory, becoming the largest party and forming a centre-right government.\n\n<timeline>\nImageSize  = width:1300 height:240\nPlotArea   = width:1200 height:160 left:75 bottom:60\nAlignBars  = justify\n\nDateFormat = x.y\nPeriod     = from:0 till:50\nTimeAxis   = orientation:vertical\nAlignBars  = justify\nScaleMajor = unit:year increment:5 start:0\n\nPlotData   =\n  bar:% color:claret width:15   mark:(line,white) align:left fontsize:S\n\n  bar:1884 from:start till:4.9 text:4.9\n  bar:1887 from:start till:3.5 text:3.5\n  bar:1890 from:start till:7.3 text:7.3\n  bar:1892 from:start till:8.9 text:8.9\n  bar:1895 from:start till:11.3 text:11.3\n  bar:1898 from:start till:14.2 text:14.2\n  bar:1901 from:start till:17.8 text:17.8\n  bar:1903 from:start till:21.0 text:21.0\n  bar:1906 from:start till:25.4 text:25.4 \n  bar:1909 from:start till:29.0 text:29.0\n  bar:1910 from:start till:28.3 text:28.3\n  bar:1913 from:start till:29.6 text:29.6\n  bar:1918 from:start till:28.7 text:28.7\n  bar:1920 from:start till:29.2 text:29.2\n  bar:1920-2 from:start till:29.8 text:29.8\n  bar:1920-3 from:start till:32.2 text:32.2\n  bar:1924 from:start till:36.6 text:36.6\n  bar:1926 from:start till:37.2 text:37.2\n  bar:1929 from:start till:41.8 text:41.8\n  bar:1932 from:start till:42.7 text:42.7\n  bar:1935 from:start till:46.4 text:46.4\n  bar:1939 f