elm Klein]]\n* 1875 \u2013 February 1877: [[Louis Pio]]\n* 1877 February\u2013July 1878: [[Chresten H\u00f8rdum]]\n* 1878 February\u2013July: [[A.C. Meyer]]\n* 1878\u20131879: [[Saxo W. Wiegell]]\n* 1880\u20131882: [[Chresten H\u00f8rdum]]\n* 1882\u20131910: [[Peter Christian Knudsen]]\n* 1910\u20131939: [[Thorvald Stauning]] (Prime Minister: 1924\u20131926, 1929\u20131942)\n* 1939\u20131955: [[Hans Hedtoft]] (Prime Minister: 1947\u20131955; [[Alsing Andersen]] as ''de facto'' leader in 1941\u20131945)\n* 1955\u20131960: [[H. C. Hansen]] (Prime Minister: 1955\u20131960)\n* 1960\u20131962: [[Viggo Kampmann]] (Prime Minister: 1960\u20131962)\n* 1962\u20131972: [[Jens Otto Krag]] (Prime Minister: 1962\u20131968, 1971\u20131972; [[Erling Dinesen]] as ''de facto'' leader from October 1972 to September 1973)\n* 1973\u20131987: [[Anker J\u00f8rgensen]] (Prime Minister: 1972\u20131973, 1975\u20131981)\n* 1987\u20131992: [[Svend Auken]]\n* 1992\u20132002: [[Poul Nyrup Rasmussen]] (Prime Minister: 1993\u20132001)\n* 2002\u20132005: [[Mogens Lykketoft]]\n* 2005\u20132015: [[Helle Thorning-Schmidt]] (Prime Minister: 2011\u20132015)\n* 2015\u2013present: [[Mette Frederiksen]] (Prime Minister: 2019\u2013present)\n\n== International affiliations ==\nThe party was a member of the [[Labour and Socialist International]] between 1923 and 1940.<ref>Kowalski, Werner (1985). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=83QdPwAACAAJ Geschichte der sozialistischen arbeiter-internationale: 1923 \u2013 19]''. Berlin: Dt. Verl. d. Wissenschaften. p. 290.</ref> It is now a member of the [[Progressive Alliance]], an association of progressive social democratic parties. The Social Democrats are also a member of the [[Party of European Socialists]] while the party's [[Member of the European Parliament|MEPs]] sit in the [[Progressive Alliance of Socialists and Democrats|Socialists & Democrats]] group.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Socialism|Denmark}}\n* [[List of political parties in Denmark]]\n* [[Politics of Denmark]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website}} {{in lang|da}}\n* [https://www.socialdemokratiet.dk/da/partiet/in-english-the-social-democratic-party/ Official website] {{in lang|en}}\n\n{{Danish political parties}}\n{{Party of European Socialists}}\n\n[[Category:Social democratic parties in Europe]]\n[[Category:1871 establishments in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 1871]]\n[[Category:Social Democrats (Denmark)| ]]\n[[Category:Members of the Labour and Socialist International]]\n[[Category:Party of European Socialists member parties]]\n[[Category:Progressive Alliance]]\n[[Category:Second International]]\n[[Category:Socialist parties in Denmark]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Political party in Denmark}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| native_name = {{#property:P1705}}\n| logo = Social_Democrats_(Denmark)_logo.svg\n| logo_size = 250px\n| leader = [[{{#property:P488}}]]\n| leader1_title = Deputy Leader\n| leader1_name = [[Mogens Jensen (politician)|Mogens Jensen]]<br>[[Frank Jensen]]\n| foundation = {{#property:P571}}\n| student_wing = [[Frit Forum|Frit Forum \u2013 Social Democratic Students of Denmark]]\n| headquarters = Vester Voldgade 96<br>1552 [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]\n| ideology = [[Social democracy]]<ref name=\"Nordsieck\"/><ref name=\"Merkel\"/>\n| position = [[Centre-left politics|Centre-left]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Milne|first=Richard|title=Denmark's centre-left seeks common ground with populists|url=https://www.ft.com/content/f73883a6-621e-11e7-91a7-502f7ee26895|accessdate=12 March 2019|work=Financial Times|date=10 July 2017}}</ref>\n| international = [[Progressive Alliance]]<ref name=\"PA\">{{cite web|url=http://progressive-alliance.info/network/parties-and-organisations/|title=Parties & Organisations|publisher=Progressive Alliance|accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref>\n| european = [[Party of European Socialists]]\n| europarl = [[Progressive Alliance